w1448 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LatinAmericanBriefs 1stLd-Writethru   08-04 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs, 1st Ld-Writethru,0803 </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: ADDS details on kidnapped senator to Colombia item. &QL; 
 &UR; By The Associated Press

<TEXT>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ Leftist rebels have suspended peace
talks with civic leaders and confirmed that they abducted a ruling
party senator.
	   Jailed representatives of the 5,000-member National Liberation
Army, or ELN, had planned to meet Monday with business and civic
leaders in a prison near Medellin, the country's second largest
city.
	   The contacts were supposed to help pave the way for direct
negotiations with President-elect Andres Pastrana, who takes office
August 7.
	   The decision to suspend the talks follows a weekend of rebel
attacks_ including the abduction Saturday of Sen. Carlos Espinoza _
that left eight dead and raised doubts about the guerrillas' desire
for peace.
	   The ELN pledged last month to scale back kidnappings and attacks
on civilian installations as a gesture to improve the climate for
peace.
	   Violence between rebels, the army and rightist paramilitary
groups has forced hundreds of thousands of Colombians to flee their
homes.
	   In the latest such incident, several thousand peasants have fled
to the oil-refining city of Barrancabermeja, some 165 miles (265
kilometers) northeast of Bogota.
	   In a statement broadcast by radio Monday, an ELN spokesman said
the group would free Espinoza providing the Senate appoints a
commission to meet with the refugees in Barrancabermeja and that an
international committee is created to verify that any promises to
the refugees are kept.
	   In a separate statement Monday the rebels said they would not
resume talks with a civilian peace commission until the civic
leaders explain a July 26 agreement with paramilitary groups.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ A local police association has called for the
resignation of the city's top cop, arguing he is incapable of
curbing crime or police corruption, newspapers reported Monday.
	   The National Coordinator of Security Workers also urged
lawmakers to revise labor laws to allow creation of a formal police
union that could help win pensions and other benefits, steps it
said would fight the ranks' reputation for corruption.
	   The association, representing 150,000 police and security
guards, called on city police Capt. Rodolfo Debernardi to step down
over a recent scandal in which police officers allegedly kidnapped
three teen-age girls and raped two of them.
	   Association leaders said Sunday the case shows that Debernardi
has no control over his officers.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ The Roman Catholic archbishop of Oaxaca state
says he spoke with leftist rebels on two occasions but stressed the
church has no intention of acting as a mediator between the group
and the government, newspapers reported Monday.
	   Archbishop Hector Gonzalez Martinez said Sunday he met members
of the Popular Revolutionary Army during religious services _ the
first time a Catholic church official has acknowledged doing so,
the daily Reforma said.
	   He did not specify when the meetings took place.
	   The rebels, known by their Spanish initials EPR, rose up in
neighboring Guerrero state in 1996 on the anniversary of a massacre
of 17 peasants by state police. The group has demanded sweeping
political reforms.
	   Gonzalez, who said neither he nor the church is looking to
mediate in the conflict, said he urged the rebels to revise their
political tactics and objectives and adopt a ``more civil''
approach to their goals.
	   ___
	   ACAPULCO, Mexico (AP) _ A farm laborer has been found shot to
death in a region of Guerrero state where political tensions have
been high.
	   Relatives of the slain man, Juan Mejia Hernandez, 44, said they
could not explain his death since he was not involved with any
political party.
	   A family member found Mejia's body Sunday in a corn field in
Aguas Blancas, a community 16 miles (25 kilometers) northwest of
Acapulco where state police massacred 17 men in 1995. The next
year, a rebel group surfaced in the area demanding political
reform.
	   Since then there have been periodic clashes between troops and
suspected rebels or rebel supporters.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ A passenger bus flipped on a mountain road in
the southern state of Oaxaca, killing four passengers and injuring
nine, local authorities reported Monday.
	   The four died at the scene of the wreck, which occurred late
Sunday in the township of Juquila Mixe, Oaxaca, about 60 miles (100
kilometers) east of Oaxaca City, the state government said in a
press statement.
	   The state government did not provide information on the
condition of the injured.
	   The bus driver, who was among the injured, was blamed for poor
driving in the accident, the government news agency Notimex
reported.
</TEXT>
