w1457 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Baseball-NLRou     08-04 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-NL Roundup,0848 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Giants beat Phillies 6-1; Expos beat Padres 6-1
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS to UPDATE with late games. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) _ Danny Darwin won for the first time in nine
starts since June 8 and Barry Bonds drove in two runs as the San
Francisco Giants beat the Philadelphia Phillies 6-1 Monday to
complete a four-game sweep.
	   Darwin (7-9), who had lost six consecutive decisions, allowed
four hits in five shutout innings, striking out three and walking
three.
	   Carlton Loewer (5-4) allowed three runs and seven hits in six
innings, struck out seven and walked one.
 &UR; Expos 6, Padres 1
	   In Montreal, Dustin Hermanson took a shutout into the ninth and
Vladimir Guerrero hit a two-run, first-inning homer.
	   Hermanson (9-9) matched his season high with eight strikeouts
and walked four, allowing four hits in 8 2-3 innings. With two outs
in the ninth, Greg Myers hit an RBI single, and Steve Kline came in
for the final out.
	   Brian Boehringer (5-2), making his first start of the season,
allowed five runs _ four earned _ and six hits in four innings. He
was starting because Joey Hamilton was in San Diego with his wife
Angie, due to deliver their first child.
 &UR; Marlins 11, Astros 3 &QC; 
	   In Miami, struggling rookie Andy Larkin pitched 6 2-3 strong
innings and Gregg Zaun matched a career high with four RBIs to help
the Florida Marlins beat the Houston Astros 11-3 Monday night.
	   Florida's Craig Counsell was hit in the jaw by a pitch from C.J.
Nitkowski in the eighth inning. Counsell remained on his feet but
immediately left the game for treatment.
	   Nitkowski, who had hit the two previous batters to load the
bases, was taken out of the game after he hit Counsell. It was the
third time in the major leagues since 1900 that a pitcher had hit
three consecutive batters _ Dock Ellis of Pittsburgh did it in 1974
and Wilbur Wood of the Chicago White Sox did it in 1977.
	   Larkin (3-6) allowed five hits and three runs, lowering his ERA
from 7.97 to 7.58. He raised his batting average from .083 to .160
with singles in his first two at-bats.
 &UR; Rockies 7, Pirates 2 &QC; 
	   In Pittsburgh, Bobby Jones pitched eight strong innings and hit
a pair of RBI singles as the Colorado Rockies beat the Pittsburgh
Pirates.
	   Jeff Reed went 4-for-4 and drove in two runs and newly acquired
Darryl Hamilton also had two RBIs. The Rockies won for just the
third time in their last 14 road games.
	   Jones (5-4), making his first start in 11 days, gave up five
hits, walked two and struck out six.
	   The Rockies beat Jon Lieber (8-12) for the second time in six
days. The Pirates lost for the seventh time in eight games to fall
a season-low 12 games under .500.
 &UR; Dodgers 8, Mets 5 &QC; 
	   In New York, Hideo Nomo and Mike Piazza came up big against
their former team, leaving the Mets in position for an emotional
win. Raul Mondesi and Eric Karros changed that real fast.
	   Mondesi's second homer of the game tied the score in the
seventh, and Karros hit a tiebreaking two-run shot later in the
inning to lift the Los Angeles Dodgers over the New York Mets.
	   Nomo, 3-1 for the Mets following a 2-7 start for Los Angeles,
left with a 5-2 lead in the seventh but was undone when shortstop
Rey Ordonez threw Eric Young's easy one-out, double-play grounder
into right field for an error.
	   Mark Grudzielanek followed with a sacrifice fly, and Mondesi
then connected off Greg McMichael (2-4). Gary Sheffield singled,
and Karros also homered off McMichael, who faced eight batters and
allowed five hits.
 &UR; Brewers 6, Cardinals 5
	   In Milwaukee, Steve Woodard won his career-high sixth straight
decision and the Milwaukee Brewers kept Mark McGwire in the
ballpark.
	   Since hitting his 45th home run against Milwaukee at Busch
Stadium last Tuesday, McGwire has gone 22 at-bats without homering.
He went 1-for-4 with a double, a line drive off the left-field wall
that fell about a foot short of the yellow home run rail.
	   Gary Gaetti's two-run homer with one out in the ninth off Bob
Wickman cut the Brewers' lead to 6-5. Wickman retired the next two
batters for his 18th save in 21 chances.
	   Woodard (9-5), who gave up three runs on five hits in six-plus
innings, gave up a two-run homer to Ron Gant in the second and a
solo shot to Ray Lankford _ who was later ejected _ in the fourth.
 &UR; Diamondbacks 6, Cubs 5 &QC; 
	   In Chicago, Tony Batista, batting for injured Matt Williams,
connected for the first pinch-hit home run in team history as the
Arizona Diamondbacks beat the Chicago Cubs.
	   The Diamondbacks won for the fourth time in five games. Chicago,
leading the NL wild-card race, has lost three of five.
	   Williams was activated from the 15-day disabled list before the
game after being sidelined by a micro-stress fracture in his left
foot. But the third baseman was hit in the right hand by a pitch in
the third inning, and was replaced by Batista in the fifth.
	   Batista's two-run homer made it 5-0. It was the 161st pinch-hit
at-bat for the Diamondbacks. Williams was listed as day-to-day with
a bruised hand.
</TEXT>
