w1461 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-Taiwan-Kidnappi     08-04 0403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Taiwan-Kidnapping </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Family of murdered Taiwan politician agrees to autopsy
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Relatives of a Taiwan politician killed by
kidnappers in China have agreed to an autopsy to help clarify the
circumstances of her death, the state-run Xinhua News Agency
reported Tuesday.
	   Lin Ti-chuan's July 29 death in northeast Liaoning province,
apparently due to an overdose of drugs forced on her by the
kidnappers, has become the latest point of contention between the
rival governments in Taiwan and China.
	   The decision to conduct an autopsy was part of an agreement
reached Monday with Chinese authorities that will allow Lin's
family to take her body back to Taiwan, Xinhua reported.
	   Initially, Lin's political allies in Taiwan and her family
resisted having an autopsy performed, in keeping with the
traditional Chinese custom of keeping a body intact after death. It
was unclear why the family reportedly agreed to the autopsy.
	   Lin, a city councillor in the southern Taiwan city of Kaohsiung,
was kidnapped on July 27 together with her Taiwanese boyfriend,
allegedly because of a business dispute. Lin's boyfriend escaped
and reported the abduction to police, who launched a massive
manhunt that ended with the discovery of Lin's body at a hospital
in the Liaoning city of Haicheng last Thursday.
	   Taiwan officials have warned that mishandling of the case could
hinder efforts to improve ties with China, and that the killing is
likely to discourage Taiwan investment in the Chinese mainland.
	   Taiwan and China have been political rivals since the communist
takeover of the mainland in 1949. They are moving slowly to resume
a dialogue which was suspended in 1995. While China is pushing for
political talks on reunification, Taiwan wants negotiations on
practical matters, such as the safety of Taiwanese in China.
	   Taiwan officials have reported an alarming rise in crimes
against Taiwanese businessmen in China.
	   As of mid-April, the semiofficial Straits Exchange Foundation
had recorded 19 cases of violence against Taiwanese investors in
China this year, compared with 27 cases for all of 1997.
	   Those 19 cases included five murders, six disappearances, and
eight kidnappings. Most occurred in southern Guangdong province and
in coastal Fujian, where large numbers of migrants desperate for
work have resorted to crime, officials of the foundation said. 	   
</TEXT>
