w1469 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NewZealand-MaoriTribe     08-04 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-New Zealand-Maori Tribes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Traditional Maori tribes owners of fish assets, judge rules
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) _ The High Court has ruled that
traditional Maori tribes, or ``iwi,'' are the owners of more than
U.S. dlrs 250 million of fisheries assets, snubbing claims by urban
Maori for a share in tribal fishing wealth.
	   The decision means that urban Maori groups, which claim to
represent one-third of the country's 520,000 Maori, have no claim
on the fishing assets granted to tribes as part of a settlement of
historic sea fisheries ownership.
	   The urban groups went to the High Court seeking control over
some of the fisheries assets, with Maori deeply divided over the
right of non-tribal Maori to claim ownership of part of the fishing
wealth.
	   But Justice Barry Paterson said Tuesday the right to determine
the distribution of the fisheries assets rested with ``iwi,'' which
he took to mean traditional tribes in the context of a 1992
settlement.
	   The meaning of the word ``iwi,'' or tribe, was central to the
case.
	   The judge said the tribes had a duty to ensure that any scheme
to allocate the assets included urban Maori who could claim iwi
links.
	   ``A fair settlement should benefit all Maori,'' he said in his
landmark ruling.
	   He added that the intent of the government in the fisheries
settlement was ultimately to benefit all Maori and there were
strong arguments why this should be so.
	   Paterson said urban Maori authorities were legal bodies which
stood in similar relationship to the people they served as did iwi
authorities to members of the iwi.
	   However, urban authorities did not have a tribal basis in the
sense that they did not have a genealogical, blood or kinship link.
	   The case is one of a number on how assets or funding should be
distributed among Maori.
	   Maori Affairs Minister Tau Henare said at least U.S. dlrs 10
million (dlrs NZ 20 million) should be set aside as a special fund
for the use of urban Maori groups.
	   Census figures show more than 112,000 Maori people either do not
know their iwi, or tribe, or for some reason choose not to
affiliate with it.
	   Manukau Urban Maori Authority spokesman Willie Jackson said he
was shocked by the ruling.
	   ``It's like the judge has ignored the modern-day reality,'' he
said. ``Urban Maori people have found their identity with groups
like us.''
	   Jackson said the authority would discuss the prospects of an
appeal with its lawyers, but it was not their first option.
	   `The best thing for us is to get together with the Waitangi
(Maori) Fisheries Commission and maybe negotiate something for all
Maori,'' he said. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
