w1482 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Baseball-ALRou     08-04 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-AL Roundup,0503 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Knoblauch keys Yankees' 14-1 win over Athletics
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   OAKLAND, California (AP) _ Mike Oquist became the first pitcher
to give up 14 earned runs in 22 years, and Chuck Knoblauch homered
twice and drove in a career-high five runs as the New York Yankees
overwhelmed Oakland 14-1 Monday night.
	   Oquist (6-9) set a franchise record for runs allowed and gave up
16 hits in five innings. With the Yankees and Athletics scheduled
to play a doubleheader Tuesday, Oakland saved its bullpen by
sacrificing Oquist, who lost his fourth straight decision.
	   Bill Travers was the last major leaguer to allow 14 earned runs,
according to the Elias Sports Bureau. He did it on Aug. 14, 1977,
in 7 2-3 innings of Milwaukee's loss to Cleveland.
	   Darryl Strawberry and Paul O'Neill also homered as the Yankees
tied their season high by connecting four times. Matt Stairs tied
an Athletics franchise record by homering in his fifth straight
game.
	   Orlando Hernandez (6-3) pitched a three-hitter and struck out
eight in his second complete game. New York won for the 10th time
in 13 games.
 &UR; Mariners 3, Red Sox 1
	   IN Seattle, rookie Shane Monahan's first major league homer, a
two-run shot in the seventh inning, gave Ken Cloude and the Seattle
Mariners a victory over the Boston Red Sox.
	   Monahan, playing in his 20th game with the Mariners, hit a line
drive over the right-field fence off John Wasdin (5-4) to break a
1-1 tie. Wasdin hit Jay Buhner with a pitch to open the inning.
	   Cloude (6-7) won his third straight decision. He gave up five
hits in eight innings. Mike Timlin pitched the ninth for his
seventh save.
 &UR; White Sox 6, Devil Rays 1
	   In St. Petersburg, Florida, James Baldwin continued his
dominance over the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, becoming the first
three-time winner over the expansion team in the Chicago White
Sox's victory.
	   Baldwin (7-4) outdueled rookie Rolando Arrojo (11-8) for the
second time in a week. The Chicago starter had a shutout until Fred
McGriff homered with one out in the ninth.
	   Baldwin allowed eight hits, struck out seven and walked one in 8
2-3 innings. In Baldwin's three victories over Tampa Bay, the Devil
Rays have scored only three runs in 21 1-3 innings and struck out
18 times.
 &UR; Angels 11, Indians 4
	   In Anaheim, California, Tim Salmon capped a five-run second
inning with a three-run homer and Randy Velarde went 3-for-5 and
scored twice as Anaheim beat Cleveland to snap a four-game losing
streak.
	   Velarde was recalled earlier in the day from the minors, where
he was on a rehabilitation assignment after straining his right
forearm. Velarde, who played in only one game last year because of
elbow problems, singled in the first inning for his first hit in
Anaheim since Sept. 25, 1996.
	   Steve Sparks (5-2) gave up three runs and seven hits in 5 1-3
innings. Jaret Wright (9-7) gave up seven runs and five hits in two
innings, the shortest outing of his two-year career.
</TEXT>
