w1491 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-Magsaysay     08-04 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Magsaysay </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former Philippine President Corazon Aquino wins Magsaysay award
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo Available &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Former Philippine President Corazon
Aquino, who helped topple strongman Ferdinand Marcos in 1986 and
inspired struggles against dictatorships worldwide, was named
winner Tuesday of the 1998 Ramon Magsaysay Award for International
Understanding.
	   The awards board cited Aquino for ``giving radiant moral force
to the nonviolent movement for democracy in the Philippines and in
the world.''
	   The award, named for the late Philippine President Ramon
Magsaysay, is considered the Asian equivalent of the Nobel Prize.
	   Aquino is the widow of Marcos' fiercest political rival, Sen.
Benigno Aquino, whose assassination on Aug. 21, 1983, as he
returned from U.S. exile triggered massive street protests that
culminated in a 1986 ``people power'' revolt that ended Marcos' two
decades of strongman rule.
	   The awards board said Aquino then emerged from the shadow of her
late husband to galvanize the fragmented opposition to Marcos.
	   She agreed to run against Marcos in a snap presidential election
in February 1986 but lost in the official count, which was widely
believed to be rigged.
	   Aquino called for civil disobedience to protest the election
outcome. Meanwhile, a group of military officers broke off from
Marcos in a series of events that led to his overthrow.
	   Aquino was swept to the presidency, inheriting an economy in
shambles and a country battered by years of dictatorship.
	   ``Step by step, she dismantled the machinery of dictatorship and
constructed the machinery of democracy: a free press and a new
constitution, then elections,'' the awards board said.
	   Noting that Aquino survived seven coup attempts, the board said
she could not satisfy all expectations of her government, but it
said she accomplished much in restoring the country's democratic
institutions.
	   When her term ended in 1992, Aquino traveled widely to share the
Philippines' non-violent struggle against authoritarianism.
	   Aquino's Magsaysay award is the fifth and last to be announced
this year. The awards board earlier named Phaly Nuon of Cambodia
the winner for community leadership, Thai banker Sophon Suphapong
for public service, Pakistani doctor Adibul Hasan Rizvk for
government service and Chinese Ying Ruocheng for journalism,
literature and creative communication arts.
	   The winners will be honored at the 40th presentation ceremonies
for the awards in Manila on Aug. 31, Magsaysay's birthday. The
popular Philippine president died in a plane crash in 1957.
	   The winners of the awards each receive a certificate, medallion
and dlrs 50,000. 	   
</TEXT>
