<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Building Collapse,0234 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Death toll in building collapse climbs to 14
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS to UPDATE with higher death toll. &QL; 
 &UR; By RAMOLA TALWAR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ Firemen and volunteers scrabbled with their
bare hands Tuesday to search for survivors in the debris of a
collapsed building, discovering more bodies that boosted the death
toll to 14, police said.
	   Rescuers working though the night found 21 people alive in the
rubble of the building, which had been declared structurally
unsound earlier this year. Police feared as many as 15 people were
still trapped inside.
	   Cranes worked under floodlights to remove large chunks of
concrete to clear the way for rescuers to pull out victims. Workers
heard moans and cries for help from under the rubble.
	   The injured were taken to nearby hospitals.
	   The 20-year-old building crumpled with a loud thud Monday night.
Three of its seven stories had been added as a guest house without
authorization from city authorities.
	   Municipal officials said they had ordered residents to vacate
the building several months ago, reportedly after it was seen to be
leaning to one side. The warning was ignored.
	   ``We feared yesterday the toll could have been much higher ....
because of the guest house,'' said Sridhar Joshi, a top civic
official. Many rooms were unoccupied at the time of the collapse. 	   
</TEXT>
