<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Election </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Recount begins for some disputed areas in Cambodia election
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos PHN101-103 &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBIN McDOWELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Cambodia moved a step closer Tuesday
to issuing complete results from last week's parliamentary
election, but a limited recount of some votes seemed unlikely to
satisfy opposition complaints of electoral fraud.
	   The official National Election Committee announced preliminary
final results for four more provinces Tuesday, leaving totals
pending for just three of the country's 23 electoral districts.
	   Co-Premier Hun Sen's Cambodian People's Party has garnered the
highest vote tallies in 17 provinces, the opposition party
FUNCINPEC in two and its ally, the Sam Rainsy Party, in one.
	   A projection by the Committee for Free and Fair Elections in
Cambodia, an independent election monitoring group, gives the
Cambodian People's Party 64 seats, FUNCINPEC 43 and the Sam Rainsy
Party 15 in the 122-seat National Assembly.
	   The opposition parties have alleged widespread irregularities in
voting and ballot-counting for the July 26 poll.
	   In response, the official National Election Committee on Tuesday
began a recount of the votes from three communes in the southern
province of Takeo.
	   The recount was supposed to begin Monday, but election workers
could not find in time the right ballots in the piles of hundreds
of blue official sacks containing votes sent in from all around the
country.
	   Opposition party observers and independent poll watchers were
present for Tuesday's recount. It is not clear whether the election
committee plans any more recounts, or how they might decide which
areas should have them.
	   Sam Rainsy, the most outspoken opposition leader, showed up at
Tuesday's recount and told reporters his party had filed 250
complaints with the committee so far and expected to protest
irregularities in as many as 700 communes, or roughly half the
total nationwide.
	   ``We have very serious reasons to ask for recounts,'' he told
reporters, adding that recounting was neither particularly
difficult nor costly.
	   Sam Rainsy met briefly Tuesday morning with his opposition ally,
FUNCINPEC leader Prince Norodom Ranariddh. He said they agreed to
stand firm in refusing to consider joining Hun Sen in a coalition
government until all their election complaints are addressed.
	   ``No coalition will be discussed before the recount is
completed,'' he said. ``If they do not agree to recounting we will
not agree to discuss anything else. There will be a deadlock.''
	   The opposition parties last week asked that new votes be taken
in disputed precincts if their charges of wrongdoing were found to
be valid, and threatened to boycott the National Assembly if their
complaints were not heeded.
	   Without the opposition's attendance, the assembly is unlikely to
have present the two-thirds of its 122 members needed to conduct
any major business.
	   Hun Sen responded by inviting them to join a coalition
government, but warning that if they carried out their threat not
to attend the assembly, he could confirm a government by lowering
the constitutional minimum for the assembly to meet from two-thirds
to 50 percent plus one. He also said his current government could
simply remain in power.
	   The election was held one year after Hun Sen ousted Ranariddh as
his co-premier in a violent coup d'etat, shattering a tense dual
premiership formed after the U.N.-sponsored elections in 1993. 	   
</TEXT>
