<HEADLINE>
Computer problem paralyzes Japanese bank
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES lede graf with suspension of most transactions; ADDS
bank spokesman comment on planned resumption of service, other
details &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A computer malfunction forced major Japanese lender
Asahi Bank Ltd. to suspend account transactions nationwide Tuesday
at its 353 branches and automatic teller machines, the bank said.
	   But the bank was expected to resume ATM service at 3:00 p.m.
local time (0600 GMT), said spokesman Sagaki Takagi.
	   The computer electronics-related problem, the exact cause of
which remained unknown, paralyzed Asahi Bank's computer system
shortly after 10:00 a.m. local time (0100 GMT), the bank said.
	   While the bank plans to close its walk-in teller windows as
usual at mid-afternoon Tuesday, bank employees will be posted
outside to aid customers with ATM transactions, the spokesman said.
	   The bank will resume normal operations Wednesday morning, he
said.
	   One of Japan's 10 largest commercial banks, Asahi Bank was
formed through the merger of Kyowa Bank and Saitama Bank in 1991. 	   
</TEXT>
