<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Yo-Yo Thefts </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Shoplifting of yo-yos contributes to higher crime rates
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ A recent yo-yo craze is contributing to
juvenile delinquency in Singapore.
	   Yo-yo theft accounted for almost half of all juvenile
shoplifting cases in May, an increase from just over a third of all
cases in April, The New Paper reported Monday.
	   Quoting fresh police statistics, the report said the boom
yo-yo-stealing could be due to the rising popularity of the toys,
which sell for about 12 Singapore dollars (dlrs 7) apiece.
	   Singaporean families are tightening their budgets and cutting
back on frills as the Asian economic crisis hits this affluent
island state. Parents who may once have indulged their children's
craving for the latest yo-yo are now more likely to decline the
request.
	   Yo-yos have taken Singapore by storm this year, in part because
of American yo-yo enthusiast Hans Van Dan Elzen who has put on live
demonstrations in stores and shown off amazing tricks in television
ads.
	   All types of shoplifting accounted for 60 percent of juvenile
crimes through May this year, the report said, and were part of a
general 4.7 percent increase in the crime rate over the same period
last year. 	   
</TEXT>
