<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Queen Mother </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Royals gather for Queen Mother's 98th birthday
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING TO FIX CODING

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Members of the royal family were expected Tuesday
to gather around the Queen Mother Elizabeth, the nation's oldest
royal in history, to celebrate her 98th birthday.
	   Two world wars, the death of her husband, the disappointment of
failed marriages among younger royals, two hip replacements and a
cataract operation _ the mother of Queen Elizabeth II has endured
them all.
	   When Edward VIII abdicated in 1936 to marry American divorcee
Wallis Simpson, the Queen Mother and her beloved husband Bertie _
then the Duke and Duchess of York _ were propelled into unwanted
and unsought sovereignty as George VI and Queen Elizabeth. They
ruled until George VI died in 1952, after 29 years of marriage.
	   As the royal family accelerates its program of modernization in
the wake of the death of Princess Diana in a Paris car crash Aug.
31, the Queen Mother is actively engaged in the life of the nation
and remains for some Britons the favorite royal.
	   The queen, 72, was expected to lead tributes to her mother
Tuesday at a family lunch party at Clarence House, the Queen
Mother's London residence close to Buckingham Palace.
	   The celebrations were scheduled to include a band of the Welsh
Guards marching past her home playing ``Happy Birthday,'' a 41-gun
salute in Hyde Park and a 62-gun birthday salute at the Tower of
London. It was hoped the hugely popular Queen Mother would make an
appearance for well-wishers outside her home.
	   The tabloid Daily Mail marked the birthday of the woman they
called ``Britain's best loved grandmother'' with a double-page
spread of 98 photographs chronicling her life.
	   In wishing her a happy birthday, the tabloid Mirror newspaper
dubbed her the ``pearl in the crown.''
	   Great-grandchildren Prince William, 16, and 13-year-old Prince
Harry were expected to be with her, along with their father, Prince
Charles. The queen, her husband, Prince Philip and her sister,
Princess Margaret were also expected to be with her.
	   After the birthday celebrations, the Queen Mother was expected
to travel to the royal family's Balmoral estate in Scotland for the
family's traditional summer holiday.
	   (er)
</TEXT>
