<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Russia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Korean foreign minister fired for mishandling dispute with
</HEADLINE>
Russia

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ President Kim Dae-jung fired his
foreign minister Tuesday, holding him responsible for what critics
say was a humiliating deal with Russia to end a diplomatic row.
	   The president named Hong Soon-young, 61, a former ambassador to
Germany and Russia, to replace Park Chung-soo as minister of
foreign affairs and trade.
	   At a meeting of foreign ministers in Manila last week, Russia
and South Korea said they had settled a diplomatic row that began
when each expelled spies posing as diplomats.
	   The two foreign ministers, however, differed widely on terms of
the settlement.
	   Russia's Yevgeny Primakov said South Korea agreed to allow the
return of a Russian diplomat expelled from Seoul in retaliation for
Russia's deportation of a South Korean on espionage charges.
	   But Primakov said the South Korean diplomat would not be allowed
to return to Moscow ``because he was caught red-handed'' taking
classified material from a Russian contact.
	   Park at first denied that the Russian would be allowed to return
to Seoul. But two days later, his deputy, Sun June-young,
acknowledged Seoul agreed to ``discuss'' the Russian diplomat's
return so that he could pack his belongings.
	   South Korean news media and other critics called the alleged
deal humiliating. They accused Park and other South Korean
officials of trying to hide a secret deal to avoid embarrassment.
	   The row started July 4, when Russia ordered the expulsion of a
South Korean diplomat in Moscow after he reportedly was caught
accepting classified documents from a Russian contact.
	   The Russian was arrested on treason charges.
	   South Korea retaliated four days later by expelling a Russian
diplomat in Seoul, saying he had engaged in ``activities that go
against his status as a diplomat.''
	   Then, on July 20, South Korea withdrew five more officials from
Russia under an agreement to limit the number of intelligence
agents each country assigns to its diplomatic missions. No
withdrawal was reported from the Russian embassy in Seoul.
	   South Korean officials had hoped that would end the dispute.
	   But when Park and Primakov met on the sidelines of a Southeast
Asia security conference in Manila last week, Russia raised the
issue again and asked South Korea to retract its earlier decision
that expelled the Russian diplomat in Seoul. 	   
</TEXT>
