<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Airport </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cargo handler says not given enough time for airport opening
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ In a detailed report of its problems at Hong
Kong's new airport, the main cargo handler told a government
commission that it was not given enough time to ensure a smooth
opening, news reports said Tuesday.
	   Managing Director Anthony Charter told the commission on its
first visit to the airport Monday that Hong Kong Air Cargo
Terminals was ``under extreme time pressure'' to get its
computerized cargo system running at Chek Lap Kok airport, the Hong
Kong Standard said.
	   Charter told Chairman Woo Kwok-hing that the company's permit to
occupy the new terminal was given only three days before the
airport's opening on July 6, and that much sensitive computer
equipment was left exposed to dust, dirt, and water.
	   Both the government and the cargo handler have come in for
scathing criticism from legislators and businessmen who fear the
problems will further hurt Hong Kong's weakening economy. It is not
clear whether compensation will be offered for losses resulting
from the cargo problems, and if so, by whom.
	   The explanation offered by the cargo company on Monday was among
the most comprehensive given so far.
	   Charter's deputy, Yeung Kwok-keung, was quoted as saying that
the cargo company's computers failed to connect to the airport's
main flight-information system, and received its first message only
on the evening of the first day of operations.
	   By that time, about 600 error messages were logged in the
computer, Charter was quoted as saying.
	   Yeung was quoted as saying that cargo companies compounded the
problems by continuing to send shipments even after being told of
the cargo terminal's problems.
	   The latest government statistics show that gross domestic
product shrank 2.8 percent in this year's first quarter. Worse
figures are expected for the second quarter of the year. The
government has said that the economy is being slowed further by the
cargo problems.
	   Woo said during the visit to the airport that the commission has
received ``several responses'' from foreign experts who were asked
to help in the investigation, the South China Morning Post
reported.
	   The cargo handler has shifted some operations back to its
facilities at old Kai Tak airport, and said last week that it was
slightly ahead of a phased recovery plan.
	   It promised to be up to 100 percent cargo capacity at the new
airport by the end of August. 	   
</TEXT>
