<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Buddhist Temple </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai government cracking down on hilltribe Buddhist temple
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Alleged drug dealing and an
unauthorized statue of Thailand's king had government officials
promising a crackdown Tuesday on a Buddhist temple which shelters
members of the Hmong hilltribe from Laos.
	   Some Hmong have allegedly become deeply involved in amphetamine
trafficking, with reports that gang members have put out murder
contracts on anti-narcotics policemen.
	   Many Hmong worship at Tham Krabok temple in Saraburi, 90
kilometers (56 miles) north of Bangkok. The temple is known for
running a drug treatment program in which herbal remedies are used.
	   Some police and government officials, however, have accused the
temple of sheltering drug dealers.
	   On Tuesday, Interior Minister Sanan Kachornprasart said police
will set up a special drug task force on Aug. 15 to deal with the
problems of the Hmong and the temple.
	   Education Minister Chumpol Silpa-archa cautioned, however, that
the police must take care and treat the temple's clergy with
respect because they have done much good for the community.
	   The Education Ministry oversees the Department of Religious
Affairs. It also oversees the Fine Arts Department, which on
Tuesday ordered the temple to destroy a recently-completed statue
of Thailand's constitutional monarch King Bhumibol Adulyadej.
	   ``Building His Majesty the King's statue requires official
permission and supervision by the Fine Arts Department. Otherwise,
it is lese majeste,'' said an official of the Fine Arts Department,
who spoke only on condition of anonymity.
	   He added that the 16-meter (53-foot) statue violated the
municipality's rule that says statues should not be more than
15-meters (49.5 feet) high.
	   Ordering a statue of Thailand's king, who is revered as
semi-divine by his subjects, to be destroyed, is an unusual
occurrence in Thailand. 	   
</TEXT>
