<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Station Fire </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Arson possible in Singapore fire at center of Malaysia row
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo SIN101

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Authorities said they could not rule out arson
Tuesday as the cause of a fire that erupted inside a train station
at the center of a row with neighboring Malaysia.
	   The small fire in the Tanjong Pagar station bordering the
city-state's financial district was put out by the Civil Defense
Force about 15 minutes after it was reported Tuesday morning, said
government television.
	   The fire broke out about 50 yards (45 meters) from where
Malaysian officers were conducting their country's immigration
formalities against the wishes of the Singapore government.
	   The station was operating normally, with passengers waiting for
the next train as the fire was extinguished.
	   Government television quoted the Civil Defense Force as saying
foul play could not be ruled out. The blaze erupted among wooden
partitions in an unused lounge, burning parts of the room and
bursting windows.
	   The station has been at the center of a simmering dispute
between Singapore and Malaysia over the location of their customs
and immigration checkpoints along the railway line that connects
the two countries.
	   Singapore moved its border post to a checkpoint in the north of
the island on Saturday, despite objections from Malaysia, which
said it preferred to remain at Tanjong Pagar. 	   
</TEXT>
