<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar falls in Tokyo, Japanese stocks finish lower
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Nikkei closing, mid-afternoon dollar and bond
price &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar fell against the yen Tuesday
following warnings by Japanese finance officials that they may
intervene to halt the yen's slide. Tokyo stock prices closed lower.
	   The dollar bought 144.98 yen in mid-afternoon trading, down 0.66
yen from late Monday in Tokyo and also below its late New York rate
of 145.60 yen overnight.
	   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa told a regular news conference
that intervention in the foreign exchange markets is necessary if
currency moves are disruptive. Miyazawa added that similar comments
he made last week weren't meant to imply that intervention to
support the yen was unnecessary.
	   Separately, Haruhiko Kuroda, head of the international bureau of
the Finance Ministry, warned that Japan was prepared to take action
against what he called the ``excessively weak'' yen.
	   The comments combined to push the dollar down from its morning
high of 146.05 yen, traders said.
	   It was Miyazawa's assertion last week that intervention should
occur only when currency moves are disruptive that prompted dollar
buying.
	   But the different emphasis this time, and Miyazawa's suggestion
that he had been misinterpreted previously, helped boost the yen,
traders said.
	   On Monday, the dollar climbed to a seven-week high against the
yen amid a perception that a turnaround in Japan's economy could
take time.
	   Meanwhile, stock prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange continued to
fall as a drop in bank issues was weighing on overall market
sentiment, dealers said.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 141.50 points,
or 0.88 percent, closing at 16,023.58 points. On Monday, the index
shed 213.89 points, or 1.31 percent.
	   Traders remained unsettled because of the volatile exchange
market and an overnight fall of 96.55 points in the Down Jones
industrial average on Wall Street.
	   Domestic institutional investors were among sellers of bank
shares on worries that restructuring of the nation's banking
industry will take a toll on the sector.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section fell 10.63 points, or 0.85 percent, to 1,234.61. The
TOPIX closed down 16.80 points, or 1.33 percent, the previous day.
	   The yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese government
bond fell to 1.210 percent from Monday's finish of 1.225 percent,
driving its price up to 111.73 yen from 111.62 yen. 	   
</TEXT>
