<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Nuclear </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
First nuclear power plant in 10 years to be built in Japan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By KOZO MIZOGUCHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Overcoming public opposition and safety fears,
Japan for the first time in 10 years will build a commercial
nuclear power plant for generating electricity, officials said
Tuesday.
	   After months of discussion, the government's five-member Nuclear
Safety Commission concluded Monday there would be no problem with
the construction and operation of a new nuclear reactor.
	   That move paves the way for Kaoru Yosano, Minister of
International Trade and Industry, to soon give the go-ahead for the
construction of a nuclear power plant in Higashidori, a village in
Aomori Prefecture, or state, in northern Japan, ministry officials
said.
	   Resource-poor Japan last approved the construction of a nuclear
power plant in 1988 in the town of Shika in Ishikawa prefecture,
located 295 kilometers (183 miles), northwest of Tokyo.
	   Under the plans, construction of a boiling light-water type
reactor with an electricity generation capacity of 1.10 million
kilowatts will begin in December, said the officials, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
	   The new plant, located 631 kilometers (391 miles) northeast of
Tokyo and operated by Tohoku Electric Power Co., is slated to start
operations in July of 2005, the officials said.
	   The local assembly in Higashidori adopted a resolution to accept
the nuclear power plant in 1965, but local residents' opposition
delayed it, the Asahi newspaper said.
	   But such opposition has died down considerably in recent years,
the Asahi said.
	   The commission also judged safety will be maintained, even if a
magnitude 6.5 earthquake strikes below the site of a nuclear power
facility, the ministry officials said.
	   A temporary nuclear waste storage facility is currently under
construction at Rokkasho, another town in Aomori Prefecture.
Anti-nuclear activists say that Rokkasho is a dangerous place for
storage because it sits on at least two active earthquake faults.
	   Despite the government's efforts to reduce dependence on
imported oil, safety concerns among local residents regarding
reactors has hampered or delayed plans elsewhere as well.
	   Public concerns increased after the 1986 nuclear accident at
Chernobyl in then-Soviet Ukraine and Japan's first-ever local
referendum, held in the town of Maki, 250 kilometers (160 miles),
northwest of Tokyo. In a first for Japan, citizens in that
referendum decisively rejected a proposal to build a nuclear plant.
	   Also, trust in Japan's nuclear industry has fallen in recent
years following a series of accidents and cover-ups by plant
operators. A fire in March 1997 exposed 37 workers to low-level
radiation in a fuel processing facility.
	   Japan now has 51 commercial nuclear power plants, supplying
about one-third of the nation's electricity, according to
government figures.
 &UR; (km-kgo)
</TEXT>
