</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Cambodia-Election </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai foreign minister says Cambodia must be unified to get aid
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thailand's Foreign Minister said
Tuesday that Cambodia must show it is peaceful and unified before
the international community and Asian countries will resume
development aid.
	   Most countries cut off aid to Cambodia, one of the world's
poorest nations, last July when Hun Sen ousted Prince Norodom
Ranariddh as his co-prime minister in a violent coup d'etat.
	   Cambodia is still tallying up the votes from last Sunday's
national election, only its second in nearly 30 years. The
opposition, led by Ranariddh, has charged Hun Sen, whose party is
leading in the polls, with cheating.
	   The opposition has threatened to boycott a new Parliament unless
an honest recount is conducted.
	   Speaking to reporters on Tuesday, Thai Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan said that Cambodia's neighbors were confident that the
country's king, Norodom Sihanouk, will play a main role in helping
a government form quickly and peacefully.
	   Sihanouk is Ranariddh's father.
	   ``We want to see unity in the country and see it soon so that
the international community and Asians will be ready to help with
development,'' Surin said. 	   
</TEXT>
