<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Climbing Accident, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
French woman injured while climbing Philippine volcano
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with woman to be carried to helicopter, identities of
tourists, nature of woman's injuries, other details; CORRECTS site
where accident occurred &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LEGAZPI, Philippines (AP) _ Strong winds and poor visibility
hampered rescue helicopters Tuesday from reaching a French woman
injured when she fell off a ravine while climbing a volcano,
officials said.
	   Two air force helicopters with paramedics were sent to the
eastern side of the Mayon volcano which Olivia Murell and two
companions had climbed early Monday.
	   Murell, 27, from Paris, suffered cuts in the head and arms and
could not move her left leg when volunteer rescuers and local
residents pulled her out of the ravine early Tuesday, said Rowena
Ondiz, operations chief of the Albay Provincial Disaster Management
Organization.
	   There was no report on whether the two other French tourists _
Bruno Locatilli, 24, and Cristel Ghergovalch, 25, both of
Montpellier, France _ were also injured.
	   The three French tourists had hired a local resident to guide
them up the 2,462-meter (8,125-foot) volcano.
	   Murell slid off a ravine during a flash flood following a heavy
downpour after they became separated from their guide. The guide
later found them about halfway up the slope of the mountain Monday
afternoon and reported the accident to local authorities.
	   Rescue helicopter pilot Lt. Gerald Naldosa said he could not
land at a camp normally used by climbers where the victim was taken
by the rescuers because of dangerous winds and poor visibility and
had to land about two kilometers (one mile) away. Paramedics plan
to carry the woman to the helicopter on a stretcher, he said.
	   Governor Al Francis Bichara said the guide had not been
certified by the local tourism office and the tourists did not
inform local authorities they had planned to climb the volcano,
about 320 kilometers (200 miles) southeast of Manila.
	   Mayon, one of the most active volcanoes in the Philippines, last
erupted in February 1994, killing at least 70 people.
	   After the 1994 eruption, the government declared an area six
kilometers (3.75 miles) around the summit as a permanent danger
zone off limits to tourists and local residents. 	   
</TEXT>
