<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Elections,0498 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mexico's governing party wins two state in more competitive
</HEADLINE>
elections &QL; 
 &UR; Eds:RECAPS pvs &QL; 
 &UR; By KEN GUGGENHEIM &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AGUASCALIENTES, Mexico (AP) _ Despite winning two of three state
elections over the weekend, Mexico's governing party saw its
victory margins shrivel in a display of the country's much more
competitive political scene.
	   Nearly complete preliminary results Monday showed that the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI, lost to the
conservative National Action party in the small north-central state
of Aguascalientes, even though polls showed that most voters liked
the outgoing PRI governor.
	   The three elections are among 10 gubernatorial races this year
that help set the course for the presidential elections in the year
2000.
	   Politicians in the three major parties already are jockeying
publicly for the presidential nomination _ unusual in a country
where party chieftains have traditionally chosen candidates and
frowned on expressions of ambition.
	   ``The PRI was reaffirmed yesterday as the first political force
of the country,'' the party announced in a press release. ``these
are times of high electoral competition in which victories and
defeats should be judged in their fair dimension,'' it added.
	   The PRI's historical dominance of Mexico was underscored by its
winning despite a sharp reduction in the votes it received in
contests against two major rivals.
	   In Veracruz, the party's share of votes slid almost 20
percentage points from the 1992 gubernatorial election, but
businessman Miguel Aleman _ son of a former president _ easily
outdistanced his opponents to win with 49 percent of the vote.
	   Aleman, who united a divided party in Veracruz, has been touted
by supporters as a possible presidential candidate.
	   In Oaxaca, the PRI's share fell almost 30 percentage points. But
Jose Murat won with 48 percent, despite a determined effort by the
leftist Democratic Revolution Party, which wound up with 36 percent
_ 25 points above its 1992 showing.
	   In Aguascalientes, the PRI had won with 74 percent of the vote
in 1992. This year Felipe Gonzalez Gonzalez of National Action
bested the PRI candidate 53 to 36 percent.
	   Gonzalez obviously was not thinking of a national campaign.
``There are three countries,'' he said Monday. ``The center thinks,
the north works and the south rests.''
	   President Ernesto Zedillo said Monday the elections showed the
effectiveness of voting reforms he sponsored soon after taking
office in 1994.
	   ``In a short time we have assisted in a deep and irreversible
transition which has opened a new epoch of transparency, equity and
justice in electoral processes,'' the president told a meeting of
public administrators.
	   The Aguascalientes win helped National Action bounce back from a
damaging loss last month in Chihuahua _ the first state to turn
back to the PRI after having an opposition party governor.
</TEXT>
