r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HongKong-Virus     08-04 0249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Virus </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Deadly virus could reach Hong Kong in one year
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ A microbiology expert says a virus that has
killed more than 50 people in Taiwan may take its time reaching
Hong Kong, and warned against complacency, news reports said
Tuesday.
	   Hong Kong health authorities have been watching closely for an
outbreak of the enterovirus 71.
	   So far, none of the 38 confirmed cases of a strain similar to
the virus found in Taiwan has resulted in death.
	   Paul Chan Kay-sheung, a microbiology professor at the Chinese
University of Hong Kong, was on a team of experts from Hong Kong
that traveled to Taiwan last week to study the virus.
	   Chan said Hong Kong could not afford to relax just because it so
far had managed to escape the level of infection found in Taiwan.
	   The South China Morning Post quoted him as saying that the virus
``will take a year to arrive'' in Hong Kong.
	   The virus, which strikes infants and small children especially
hard, is the latest in a string of worries about health risks in
Hong Kong.
	   Last December, the government halted all live imports of poultry
and ordered all 1.4 million local chickens killed to stamp out the
so-called ``bird flu.'' Then, more than 100 people were admitted to
hospitals after eating deep-sea coral fish contaminated with heavy
metals.
	   Most recently fish and shellfish were declared unsafe when red
tides _ fast-breeding, oxygen-depleting algae _ hit Hong Kong
waters.	   
</TEXT>
