w1570 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-Chinese     08-04 0333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Chinese </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Indonesian president makes new plea for Chinese to return
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ President B.J. Habibie has made a new
plea to frightened ethnic Chinese to return to Indonesia after
fleeing racially charged riots in May, a news report said Tuesday.
	   However, Habibie, who replaced autocratic former President
Suharto after the riots, said he can do no more to get them to
return.
	   ``I have full sympathy for them ... not only full sympathy, I'm
on their side, pro-active. They should trust me,'' Habibie was
quoted as saying by The Asian Wall Street Journal.
	   ``I have condemned that (the riots) already, officially as
president, and I will not let it happen again.''
	   ``I am looking forward for them to come home,'' he said.
	   Ethnic Chinese make up only about 4 percent of Indonesia's 202
million population. However, they dominate commerce and industry
and were targeted by indigenous Indonesian mobs during the riots as
scapegoats for the worst economic crisis in 30 years.
	   Thousands of Chinese fled the violence in which about 1,200
people were killed. Hundreds of Chinese-owned stores and homes were
robbed and burned. Dozens of Chinese women and girls were
reportedly raped by gangs.
	   Habibie has set up inquiries into the causes of the riots and
the rapes and has repeatedly said that it is now safe for Chinese
people to return.
	   ``I have done the utmost I can do (to get them to return). I
cannot go and take my airplane and beg them and kiss them at the
feet. I don't know how to do (that), I cannot,'' the newspaper
quoted him as saying.
	   Analysts say Chinese capital and business expertise are
desperately needed by Indonesia as it grapples with soaring
inflation and mass unemployment.
	   Last month, Habibie raised eyebrows when he was quoted by The
Washington Post as saying the economy will survive even if ethnic
Chinese entrepreneurs don't return because their place will be
taken by other Indonesians.	   
</TEXT>
