w1572 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Hockey-Canucks     08-04 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Hockey-Canucks-Bure,0481 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Canucks face prospect of having to trade Bure
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) _ If Pavel Bure won't play for
the Vancouver Canucks, he might not play at all.
	   The Vancouver star is demanding a trade, but Canucks general
manager Brian Burke said Monday that Bure will have to wait for the
right deal to come along.
	   ``I do not answer to Pavel Bure,'' Burke said. ``My boss' name
is not Bure, it's (owner John) McCaw.''
	   Burke said that Bure has already informed him that he won't be
at camp.
	   ``He's an employee of the Vancouver Canucks and therefore to me
at this point he is no more than an asset. And I today will not
promise to move him,'' Burke said from Nashville, where NHL general
managers are meeting.
	   ``In fact, I'm going to make the opposite promise, that I will
not move him unless I'm offered a deal which makes sense to our
hockey club and improves our hockey club.''
	   Burke's comments came a day after a Vancouver newspaper quoted
Bure's agent Mike Gillis as saying, ``Pavel has told Brian Burke he
will never play for the team again.''
	   So Burke, who as a Vancouver assistant general manager in 1991
drove Bure to the rink for his first practice, has the task of
trying to trade him just over a month after assuming his current
post.
	   ``I spoke with (Bure) last weekend. I had offered to try to help
cure a couple of the problems he cited, and he reiterated that he'd
like to be traded,'' Burke said. ``I said, `Is there anything,
anything at all that I could do or say to make you want to stay in
Vancouver?' And he said, `No.'''
	   Bure, 27, didn't specify his reasons for wanting a trade. But he
reportedly is unhappy with the lack of privacy in Vancouver and the
Canucks' plans to enter a rebuilding stage after the team missed
the playoffs for the second consecutive season.
	   Bure has also been frustrated by numerous contract squabbles
he's had since signing his five-year deal in 1994. Despite
guarantees in his contract, Bure was forced to battle the Canucks
for money they failed to pay him during the NHL lockout that wiped
out half of the 1994-95 season.
	   Bure, the 1991-92 NHL rookie of the year, is a two-time 60-goal
scorer who scored 51 last season. The Russian right winger has one
year left on his contract, which will reportedly pay him over dlrs
8 million.
	   ``The reasons are my own and everyone has personal reasons for
doing things, and I don't really want to discuss them,'' Bure said
of his trade demand. ``I love the fans here and I love the city.
But I really feel it's time to move.''
	   Burke said Bure will face fines and a suspension without pay if
he refuses to play for the team or fails to show up for training
camp.
	   ``If we start the regular season and we haven't made a deal,
then a suspension is not an option, it's going to happen,'' Burke
said.
</TEXT>
