<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Tajikistan-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tajikistan's president brings more opposition figures into govt.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Tajikistan's president has brought four more
opposition figures into the government, part of an ongoing
reconciliation effort following the country's civil war, a news
report said Tuesday.
	   President Emomali Rakhmonov signed a decree Monday installing
leaders from the United Tajik Opposition as the chiefs of various
committees, including precious metals, oil and gas, and emergencies
and civil defense, the ITAR-Tass news agency said.
	   He also appointed an opposition leader to head the Agriculture
Ministry. Rakhmonov plans to fill the posts of vice prime minister
and defense minister with opposition members as well.
	   Under an agreement between the two sides, 30 percent of
government posts to be filled by opposition figures.
	   The secular government and the opposition, which includes
Islamic fundamentalists, signed a peace agreement last year ending
a 5-year civil war. However, there are still tensions between the
two sides.
	   In addition, some warlords have refused to recognize the peace
deal, and have clashed periodically with government forces.
	   (nw/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
