<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Farmers Protest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Farmers begin nationwide protest against grain imports
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo planned &QL; 
 &UR; By MONIKA SCISLOWSKA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Protesting farmers blockaded the city hall
in a northwestern Polish town Tuesday, beginning a planned
nationwide demonstration against grain imports and low prices.
	   Four tractors and a trailer filled with grain jammed the access
road to the building in Goleniow, 520 kilometers (320 miles)
northwest of Warsaw, city employee Mariusz Tarnozek said by
telephone Tuesday morning.
	   According to Tarnozek, a banner on the trailer said: ``We have
grain, who will buy it?''
	   The protesters also blocked the main entrance to city hall,
forcing employees and visitors to use the back door, he said,
adding that business proceeded as usual.
	   Four farmers' unions that represent well over half of the
nation's 4 million farmers threatened Monday to block 250 roads,
several government offices and eight border crossings on Tuesday to
protest grain imports and demand government purchases of their
grain.
	   Agriculture Minister Jacek Janiszewski scheduled a news
conference later Tuesday on grain purchases.
	   The government has promised to triple state purchases of Polish
grain and increase custom fees on grain imports beginning Thursday,
and Janiszewski's news conference was expected to announce those
measures to try to prevent the protest.
	   Polish agriculture remains hobbled by small, poorly equipped
farms unable to compete with larger, more modern farms in Western
Europe. Calls for reforms to consolidate farms and make them more
efficient in preparation for Poland's bid to join the European
Union have been resisted by farmers, who fear losing control of
their land and having to work for others.
	   Farmers have staged a series of protests this year demanding
more government protection. In the latest protest, a few dozen
farmers from the Solidarity union on Monday spilled 1,200 tons of
grain brought by train from Slovakia and Hungary across the rails
at a border crossing.
	   (ms-tsc)
</TEXT>
