<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sri Lanka-Emergency,0266 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sri Lankan government declares emergency
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) _ The Sri Lankan government imposed
emergency rule across the country Tuesday, a move that would allow
President Chandrika Kumaratunga to postpone provincial elections
scheduled for later this month.
	   Military leaders have expressed concern that troops needed to
fight a major campaign against Tamil rebels in the north would have
to be redeployed to secure polling booths.
	   Elections have been scheduled for August 28 in five of the
country's eight provinces.
	   In an executive order, Mrs. Kumaratunga said the emergency was
imposed ``in the interest of public security, the protection of
public order and the maintenance of supplies and services essential
to the life of the community.''
	   Government forces have fought for 15 years against Tamil
guerrillas, who want an independent homeland in northeastern Sri
Lanka for the island nation's Tamil minority. The rebels accuse the
majority Sinhalese of discriminating against the Tamils, whom the
colonial British introduced from the Indian mainland as a source of
labor for tea plantations and other projects.
	   The army and rebels are now locked in a stalemate along a vital
north-south highway.
	   A national emergency had been in effect since the war broke out
in 1983. When Mrs. Kumaratunga took office in 1994, she lifted the
regulations except in the embattled north and east, and in the
capital, Colombo.
	   The new regulations give security forces wide powers to search,
detain and investigate.
</TEXT>
