<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tokyo stocks prices decline for second day, dollar falls
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Wraps up with late dollar, closing bond price, other details &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos TOK102 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Tokyo stock prices declined Tuesday for the second
consecutive day, with major banking issues leading the slide. The
U.S. dollar fell against the yen after three sessions of gains.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 141.50 points,
or 0.88 percent, closing at 16,023.58. On Monday, the index had
shed 213.89 points, or 1.31 percent.
	   Traders remained unsettled because of the volatile dollar-yen
exchange market and an overnight fall of 96.55 points in the Dow
Jones industrial average on Wall Street.
	   The Nikkei index's decline was restrained by buying by public
pension funds in the afternoon, traders said.
	   They said investors sold banking issues on worries that
restructuring of the nation's banking industry will take a toll on
the sector.
	   Losers also included brokerage and real estate stocks and
non-life insurance issues.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section fell 10.63 points, or 0.85 percent, to 1,234.61. It
had fallen 16.80 points, or 1.33 percent, the previous day.
	   Declines outnumbered advances 668 to 403, with 193 issues
unchanged. An estimated 356 million shares changed hands on the
first section, up from Monday's 299 million.
	   In late afternoon, the dollar bought 144.62 yen, down 1.02 yen
from late Monday in Tokyo and also below its late New York rate of
145.60 yen overnight. It ranged between 144.20 yen and 146.05 yen
in Tuesday's trading.
	   In the previous three trading days, the U.S. currency had gained
a total of 4.55 yen to a seven-week high against the yen.
	   Traders said the dollar weakened from its day's high after
Japanese finance officials warned that they would intervene on
currency markets to support the yen if necessary.
	   Haruhiko Kuroda, head of the Finance Ministry's international
bureau, told a regular news conference that Japan was prepared to
take action on what he called the ``excessively weak'' yen.
	   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa also said separately that
intervention in foreign exchange markets is necessary if currency
moves are disruptive. Miyazawa said similar comments he made last
week weren't meant to imply that intervention to support the yen
was unnecessary.
	   But many traders suggested the effect of the latest comments
would be only temporary, and the dollar would climb again soon
because of Japan's gloomy economic outlook.
	   Miyazawa's assertion last week that intervention should occur
only when currency moves are disruptive had prompted dollar buying.
	   The yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese government
bond fell to 1.220 percent from Monday's finish of 1.225 percent,
driving its price up to 111.66 yen from 111.62 yen.
 &UR; (km-dj)	   
</TEXT>
