r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-Trade     08-04 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Trade </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine export growth slows to 12.2 percent in June
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Philippine export growth slowed to
12.2 percent in June despite stronger-than-expected sales of
electronics, the government said Tuesday.
	   The National Statistics Office said exports for the month
totaled dlrs 2.3 billion. For the first six months of the year,
exports rose 18.8 percent to dlrs 13.9 billion, it added.
	   Exports of electronics and components, which accounted for 52
percent of total shipments in June, rose 46 percent from a year
earlier to dlrs 1.2 billion.
	   Garment exports rose 7.4 percent to dlrs 232.3, while exports of
computer inputs and peripheral units rose 9.1 percent to dlrs 148.9
million.
	   While economists had expected a slowdown in overall export
growth, which until a few months ago had been running at more than
20 percent, the robust growth in exports of electronics and
components was a welcome surprise.
	   ``The growth in electronics exports was beyond our expectation.
We were expecting a slowdown because global demand is going down,''
said Joey Cuyegkeng, economist for ING Barings Securities
Philippines Inc.
	   He said the sector appears to be benefiting from the relocation
of foreign electronics manufacturers to the Philippines due to
incentives offered by the country's special economic zones.
	   Despite the slowdown in export growth, Cuyegkeng said the
Philippines is expected to end with a narrower trade deficit by the
end of 1998 due to declining imports.
	   ``Of course this is all due to the slowdown in the economy,''
Cuyegkeng said.
	   The year-old regional financial crisis has taken its toll on
economic activity, resulting in a relatively sharp reduction in
imports. And, while exports have undoubtedly benefited from the
weaker peso, this windfall is expected to taper off over the second
half of 1998 as exporters feel the pressure from a weakening
economy.
	   The government announces imports separately each month.
	   The country's trade deficit shrank 66.1 percent to dlrs 1.60
billion in the first five months of 1998.	   
</TEXT>
