<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru,0407 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Aid agencies struggle to reach Kosovo refugees
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS to KLA sted ALA, Lausa sted Laura, Smonica sted
Monica
 &UR; By ANNE THOMPSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ International aid agencies were
struggling to reach tens of thousands of refugees camped in the
woods of Kosovo province, after Serb attacks forced them to flee
their villages.
	   The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees was planning an aid
convoy Tuesday for ethnic Albanians near Malisevo, a former
stronghold of the secessionist Kosovo Liberation Army, where
thousands of refugees had sought shelter.
	   Serb forces toppled three additional KLA strongholds Monday,
Serb sources said. These included the villages of Lausa, Smonica
and Jablanica. The attacks come days after Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic promised to stop his attack on the KLA.
	   Milosevic also pledged last week to ``personally guarantee''
access for refugee agencies trying to bring aid to displaced ethnic
Albanian civilians. Nevertheless, U.N. refugee official Mons Nyber
said Monday that access had been ``on and off.''
	   Ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs 9-to-1 in Kosovo province, part
of the Serb republic that dominates Yugoslavia.
	   The Kosovo Information Center, close to the ethnic Albanian
leadership said that moderate Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova, who
met with U.S. envoy Christopher Hill Monday, blamed the Serbs for
exacerbating the problem in Kosovo.
	   ``Serb forces kill civilians, burn and destroy settlements and
entire villages and carry out ethnic cleansing,'' Rugova said. He
also demanded ``energetic intervention by the United States and its
allies.''
	   In Washington Monday, the administration of U.S. President Bill
Clinton announced that NATO had approved a plan to use firepower
against Serb forces in Kosovo, warning that another offensive could
trigger a ``humanitarian catastrophe.''
	   Officials at NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium said that a
number of options had been underway for some time, but there was no
military action planned at this stage.
	   There was no immediate word on what would trigger an attack by
NATO. Nor was it clear whether the administration was trying mostly
to unnerve Milosevic by raising the threat again publicly.
	   NATO bombardment helped drive Milosevic into negotiations to end
an ethnic war in Bosnia-Herzegovina in 1995.
</TEXT>
