<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Myanmar-Drugs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 million methamphetamine tablets seized
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   YANGON, Myanmar (AP) _ Narcotics police have seized 5 million
methamphetamine tablets in a truck coming from the Golden Triangle
region, the largest shipment of the drug ever seized in Myanmar,
official newspapers reported Tuesday.
	   Two men, apparently Myanmar citizens, were arrested July 22
after a search at a checkpoint turned up the drugs, broken down
into 25,000 packets, in a secret panel in their vehicle, the
newspapers said.
	   The suspects reportedly confessed that a Thai citizen they had
met near Myanmar's border with China had paid them 2.5 million
kyats (about dlrs 10,000 at unofficial rates) to drive the shipment
to Mandalay, Myanmar's second-largest city.
	   The final destination of the shipment _ five times larger than
the previous record haul seized in June _ was unknown. The drug has
become a scourge in neighboring countries in recent years and,
increasingly, in Myanmar, also known as Burma.
	   Narcotics rings in the Golden Triangle _ where the borders of
Myanmar, Laos and Thailand converge _ traditionally have made and
smuggled heroin, but have been turning to easier-to-make
amphetamines and methamphetamines as a side business.	   
</TEXT>
