<HEADLINE>
Computer problem paralyzes Japanese bank
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with computers restored &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A computer malfunction forced major Japanese lender
Asahi Bank Ltd. to suspend transactions nationwide Tuesday at its
3,499 automatic teller machines and cash dispensers, the bank said.
	   After a five-hour outage, ATM service resumed at 3:37 p.m. (0637
GMT), bank spokesman Hikoyuki Sano said. He declined to say how
many people were affected by the shutdown.
	   During the outage, he said, the bank accepted withdrawals of up
to 100,000 yen (dlrs 700) at teller windows.
	   Overseas transactions, handled by another on-line system, were
not affected by the trouble, he added.
	   Sano said the bank is investigating the cause of the trouble.
	   One of Japan's 10 largest commercial banks, Asahi Bank was
formed through the merger of Kyowa Bank and Saitama Bank in 1991.	   
</TEXT>
