<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iran-Media,0470 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Newspaper director found guilty of insulting Khomeini
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANWAR FARUQI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ The managing director of a weekly newspaper
has been found guilty of insulting the late Iranian leader
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini by publishing a letter critical of his
rule, Iranian newspapers said Tuesday
	   A Tehran court on Monday found Mohammad-Reza Za'eri, of the
weekly Khaneh, guilty of ``insulting the Imam and Islamic
sanctities,'' the papers said.
	   The court did not immediately announce a sentence, they said.
Za'eri was freed on bail of 20 million rials (dlrs 6,600) pending
sentencing.
	   Meanwhile, the Tous daily, a pro-democracy paper, was evacuated
late Monday after receiving a bomb threat from an anonymous caller.
	   No bomb was found, and journalists at Tous later resumed work,
editor Mahmoud Shams said Tuesday.
	   Za'eri was arrested last week after the paper published a letter
in which an anonymous young woman criticized Khomeini, the leader
of the 1979 revolution who is called ``the Imam.''
	   Criticism of Khomeini, who led Iran in the 1980-88 war with
Iraq, has been taboo.
	   But the young woman wrote to the paper: ``When I think of
Khomeini, all that comes to mind are the horrifying sounds of the
midnight bombs that used to fall on Tehran, and the blood of
thousands of innocent young Iranians who died in that war.''
	   She added: ``Do you call me to follow someone who has
transformed Iran into an international terrorist state with his
order to murder Salman Rushdie?''
	   Khomeini ordered Muslims to kill Rushdie for insulting Islam in
his novel ``The Satanic Verses.''
	   On July 27, militants threw a small petrol bomb at the offices
of Khaneh and then called editors to threaten further action if the
paper didn't change its policies. No one was injured in the
incident.
	   Tous, which was evacuated because of the bomb scare, has been at
the center of a power struggle between hard-liners and reformists
inside Iran's Islamic government.
	   Shams, who was assaulted by Muslim militants allied with the
hard-liners earlier this week, said Tuesday that the paper had
received a call Monday evening from a man who said ``there was a
bomb on the second floor of our building which would explode in a
half hour.''
	   Shams said he ordered the paper's 80-odd employees to evacuate
and then called police. Police and a bomb disposal squad arrived
about an hour later but found no explosive device, he said.
	   Tous began as the daily Jameah but was closed down last month by
hard-liners opposed to the reforms of Iran's moderate president,
Mohammad Khatami. The paper then changed its name to Tous and
continued publishing.
	   The authorities then ordered Tous to close but later rescinded
the directive.
</TEXT>
