<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Miners, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian miners ease blockade of power plant in Far East
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS 2 grafs with miners lifting last of the rail blockades in
Siberia, minor editing to trim. &QL; 
 &UR; By ANNA DOLGOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ With coal supplies dwindling, striking miners
eased their blockade Tuesday of the main power plant on the eastern
island of Sakhalin, agreeing to allow enough coal through to keep
the plant operational.
	   The miners, who are demanding eight months worth of overdue
wages, have been blocking railroad approaches to the plant for
nearly two weeks. They agreed that 25 cars carrying about 1,500
tons of coal could go to the plant daily, the ITAR-Tass and
Interfax news agencies reported.
	   But authorities will continue rationing electricity on the Far
Eastern island, the reports said. Homes and factories on Sakhalin
have been getting only between five and six hours of electricity a
day, it added.
	   Sakhalin Deputy Gov. Ivan Malakhov called the protest a
``terrorist'' act, ITAR-Tass said. But his boss, Gov. Igor
Farkhutdinov, disputed the accusation and revoked an earlier threat
to use force to remove the miners.
	   ``No one is going to use force,'' Farkhutdinov was quoted as
saying. ``It is not terrorism; it is an act of despair.''
	   Sakhalin is not connected to Russia's national power grid, so
much of the island is dependent on the plant for electricity. About
650,000 people live on the island.
	   The strike is one of many miners' protests over unpaid wages in
recent months. But the protests have been largely uncoordinated and
in most instances have inflicted only limited damage on the
economy.
	   In a related protest, ambulance workers in the eastern port city
of Vladivostok went on strike Tuesday to demand four months of back
wages.
	   There are usually 30 ambulances on duty, but only four ambulance
teams will stay on the job, and will respond only to calls
involving children or accident victims, ITAR-Tass said.
	   In the Ural Mountains, coal miners from the Chelyabinsk region
were blocking the Argayashskaya power plant, which supplies energy
to nuclear-waste processing enterprise Mayak, the business daily
Kommersant said.
	   Authorities have cut all power to the town of Ozersk, where the
Mayak plant is located, Kommersant said. Civil defense workers have
been sent to the region to ensure the safety of nuclear storage
sites, ITAR-Tass reported.
	   Meanwhile, miners in the Siberian coal center of Kemerovo lifted
all railroad blockades Tuesday, allowing the traffic to pass
unimpeded for the first time in at least a month, ITAR-Tass said.
	   A governmental commission had spent two weeks negotiating with
miners in Kemerovo, and the region's coal companies have begun
paying back wages, the report said.
	   (ad/gm)	   
</TEXT>
