<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Water Scare, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
All Sydney water now safe, health official says
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with water upgrade announced, consumer spokeswoman
comments &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Sydney's water was declared safe for
drinking Tuesday, clearing the way for the city's 3 million-plus
residents to begin drinking straight from the tap.
	   ``We are absolutely clear that the water is safe to drink,'' New
South Wales chief health officer Andrew Wilson said Tuesday after
the entire city was given the all-clear after more than a week of
having to boil water.
	   The culprit was an outbreak of the potentially deadly
microscopic parasites giardia and cryptosporidium. It was a severe
embarrassment for the city that will play host to the 2000 Summer
Olympics.
	   Wilson said the health department would continue to monitor the
number of people reported to be suffering from illnesses related to
water contamination for the next two weeks to ensure the water
scare had not had an impact on people's health.
	   Fear and anger among city residents has continued since the
dangerous parasites were found.
	   ``Opening the tap and drinking water is something we take for
granted, and what has happened with the water makes me understand
what people in Third World countries go through,'' said Sydney
resident Rick Turansky.
	   The health department said there had been no reported cases of
illness from water contamination, but the parasites have an
incubation period of a week or more.
	   The water treatment plant that had spread the parasites has been
cleaned up and the city's water system was flushed with clean
water.
	   By Monday night, 104 suburbs in the west and south of the city,
housing more than 600,000 of the city's 3.7 million people, had
been given the go-ahead to resume drinking tap water.
	   On Tuesday, the all-clear was given for the entire city.
	   Sydney Water board chairman David Hill later announced a U.S.
dlrs 21 million upgrade of the city's water supply.
	   Hill said the board endorsed a series of improvements including
improved water storage controls and daily monitoring of water
filtration outlets.
	   ``They are extensive measures,'' said Hill. ``It is as much as
we possibly could do to ensure that we don't see cryptosporidium
and giardia in drinking water in the future.''
	   A consumer group spokeswoman said public confidence in the water
system had been shattered by the contamination crisis, and that it
would take considerable time for trust to be restored.
	   ``The case of rebuilding will be very high,'' Australian
Consumers Association spokeswoman Mara Bun said.
	   ``Consumers will have to buy unnecessary water filters and
bottled water and the regulators (Sydney Water) will have to
demonstrate that they have regained our trust,'' she said.
	   Bun said she would not be surprised if consumers did not
immediately return to drinking or using tap water.
	   ``It's absolutely understandable; those who have been
comfortable will follow public advice but those who feel cautious
will go out and buy filters and keep taking precautions, and as
time goes by, the public's trust will have to be regained.''
	   Giardia and cryptosporidium are most dangerous to people who
already have weakened immune systems, including those suffering
from AIDS.
	   Cryptosporidium got into the water supply of Milwaukee in 1993,
contributing to the deaths of about 100 people. More than 400,000
others became ill.	   
</TEXT>
