<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Stocks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong share prices close generally higher
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Prices on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange closed
generally higher on bargain-hunting Tuesday, a day after the key
index tumbled 4.8 percent.
	   The Hang Seng Index, the market's key indicator of blue chips,
rose 28.03 points, or 0.3 percent, closing at 7,580.80. On Monday,
the index had slumped 383.43 points.
	   Turnover amounted to 5.14 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs
658 million), up from Monday's 4.74 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S.
dlrs 607 million).
	   Brokers said share prices fell for most of the session following
Monday's government announcement that the territory's economy
shrank by 2.8 percent in the first quarter instead of the 2.0
percent estimated earlier.
	   But a late bout of bargain-hunting pushed the key index into
positive territory.
	   Among gainers, Hang Seng Bank rose 2.60 Hong Kong dollars to
39.30, Swire Pacific ``A'' rose 60 cents to 25.00, Hutchison
Whampoa rose 30 cents to 36.00, and Hong Kong Telecom rose 10 cents
to 14.00.
	   Going against the trend was HSBC Holdings, which fell 1 dollar
to 178.00. HSBC Holdings announced Monday that its net profit fell
16 percent to U.S. dlrs 2.40 billion in the first half of this
year.	   
</TEXT>
