<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Prison Break </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fugitives proving hard to catch in Russia's remote northeast
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Despite police assurances that three fugitives
would soon be caught, the men remained at-large Tuesday, four days
after escaping from a remote prison in Russia's far northeast, a
news report said.
	   Police originally said the escapees would be easily caught
because there is nowhere to hide in the Arctic tundra on the
Chukotka peninsula, which extends into the Bering Sea.
	   But snow, rain, and fog have helped the fugitives elude capture
and police say one of the escapees, a local resident, has extensive
knowledge of the region, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
	   The three men were part of a group of 11 convicts who killed a
police officer and stole a large number of weapons while escaping
from prison Friday and fleeing in two stolen trucks and an armored
vehicle into the tundra near the Leningradsky settlement.
	   Two convicts and two police were killed in a shootout that
followed. One escapee committed suicide and five more were
captured.
	   Law enforcement officials, who have permission to shoot on
sight, said the fugitives would be caught soon because of cold
weather and lack of food, according to ITAR-Tass.
	   (nw/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
