w1662 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-NKoreanSpy     08-04 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-NKorean Spy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Defector accuses North Korea of kidnappings, forgery, drug
</HEADLINE>
production &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos TOK107,108 &QL; 
 &UR; By MARTIN FACKLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A North Korean defector said Tuesday he saw two
kidnapped Japanese working at a spy-training center in the
reclusive country, bolstering allegations that the communist
government has abducted several foreigners since the 1970s.
	   The ex-spy, An Myung-jin, identified the two Japanese as Megumi
Yokota, who vanished from northwest Japan in 1977 at age 13, and
Shuichi Ichikawa, who was 23 when he disappeared in 1978.
	   Tokyo has accused Pyongyang of kidnapping 10 Japanese and taking
them to North Korea, presumably to work as language instructors,
though some groups say the number could be as high as 50. The
allegations, which North Korea denies, are a major sticking point
between the two governments.
	   An said he saw a total of four Japanese, as well as Chinese and
Westerners of unknown nationality. He had no other details on their
identities.
	   He said he vividly recalled seeing Yokota held against her will
at a special spy-training school in North Korea. She had
disappeared while on her way home from school badminton practice.
	   ``Frankly speaking, she was young and pretty. That's why I
remember her,'' the former North Korean agent said at a news
conference in Tokyo.
	   An, who defected in 1993, said abductions were not the only
``crimes'' committed by the North.
	   He said he had seen forged dlrs 100 bills so finely crafted that
they could pass unnoticed through U.S. counterfeit detection
machines, and had seen opium-based drugs that were secretly being
produced for sale in the West.
	   Despite recent efforts to improve relations with the rest of the
world since the collapse of the Soviet bloc, North Korea hasn't
stopped these operations, he said.
	   ``I think such crimes will continue unless the world keeps an
eye on North Korea and blames it,'' said An, who now lives in South
Korea, where he said the government protects him from the North,
which ``dreams about killing me.''
	   North Korea has been regularly sending agents into Japan
disguised as Japanese fishermen to spy on U.S. military bases
there, he said. Some of the Japanese, including Yokota, were seized
after they accidentally stumbled across these agents.
	   Once in North Korea, the foreigners were used at spy schools to
teach agents the languages and customs of their home countries, An
said.
	   The North also stole the abductees' identities, he said. Two
North Korean agents using forged Japanese passports were arrested
for planting a bomb on a Korean airliner that killed all 120 on
board in 1987.
	   An said Japanese have been a favorite target for abduction
because of resentment over their country's colonial rule of the
Korean Peninsula from 1910 to 1945 and Japan's backing of
capitalist South Korea after World War II.
 &UR; (mef-jc)	   
</TEXT>
