<SLUG> BC-Russia-Death Penalty </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian government seeks to abolish death penalty by next April
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The Russian government is committed to abolishing
the death penalty by April 1999, the justice minister said Tuesday.
	   However, it's still not clear if the opposition-led parliament
will go along with the government's wishes.
	   The Justice Ministry has been working on amendments to the
nation's criminal code that would eliminate capital punishment,
Justice Minister Pavel Krasheninnikov said Tuesday.
	   ``We shall meet our international obligations,'' Krasheninnikov
was quoted as saying by Interfax news agency.
	   Russia promised to halt the death penalty when it joined the
Council of Europe in January 1996. Nonetheless, 92 people were
executed that year before President Boris Yeltsin imposed a
moratorium.
	   While Yeltsin is able to introduce many new policies by decree,
the amendments to the criminal code would almost certainly need to
be approved by parliament _ and many members oppose a ban on the
death penalty.
	   With no ban in place, Russian courts have continued handing down
death sentences and about 1,000 people are now on death row,
according to Amnesty International, the human rights group.
	   However, no one has been executed for about two years.
	   (ad/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
