<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Election, 1st-Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Recount begins for some disputed areas in Cambodia election
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS, UPDATES with details of recount; edits thruout &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos PHN101-103 &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBIN McDOWELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ As officials recounted some ballots
from last week's elections, opposition leaders insisted anew
Tuesday that their complaints about electoral fraud be resolved
before they consider joining Cambodian leader Hun Sen in a
coalition government.
	   ``No coalition will be discussed before the recounting is
complete,'' Sam Rainsy said after meeting opposition ally Prince
Norodom Ranariddh early Tuesday. ``We insist on the recount of
ballots to be completed properly.''
	   Hun Sen's Cambodian People's Party is the top vote-getter in 17
of the 20 electoral districts whose results have been announced so
far. Complete preliminary election results should become known
Wednesday, when the last three districts are expected to be
announced.
	   A projection by the Committee for Free and Fair Elections in
Cambodia, an independent election monitoring group, gives Hun Sen's
CPP 64 seats, Ranariddh's FUNCINPEC 43 and the Sam Rainsy Party 15
in the 122-seat parliament.
	   A recount of ballots from three communes in the southern
province of Takeo began at a snail's pace Tuesday, scrutinized by
party observers and independent poll watchers who immediately cried
foul when one of the ballot bags appeared to be missing a report
listing the total number of voters.
	   Sam Rainsy said his party suspects irregularities in as many as
700 _ or close to half _ of the country's communes. He urged
elections officials to speed up their work if they want the new
government to be formed on time. He said he has already filed
complaints about irregularities in about 250 communes.
	   It was not clear whether the election committee planned any more
recounts after the Takeo communes were completed, or how it might
decide which areas require new tallies.
	   The election was held one year after Hun Sen ousted Ranariddh as
his co-premier in a violent coup, shattering a tense dual
premiership formed after the U.N.-sponsored elections in 1993. Hun
Sen hoped the polls would win back his legitimacy in the
international arena and aid lost after his power grab.
	   But the opposition has listed a string of complaints about fraud
and irregularities and has threatened to boycott the National
Assembly when the next session opens Sept. 24 if its concerns are
not met.
	   ``If they do not agree to recounting, we will not agree to
discuss anything else. There will be a deadlock,'' Sam Rainsy told
reporters, adding that recounting was neither particularly
difficult nor costly.
	   Hun Sen said he wants a new government to be formed quickly so
that Cambodia can win back its seat at the United Nations, which
has been left vacant since last year's coup.
	   He also wants Cambodia to be admitted as a full member in the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations, where it now enjoys
observer status.
	   A National Election Committee spokesman apologized Tuesday for
delays in the recounts, saying they resulted from inexperience.
	   Samraing Kamsan denied accusations that the NEC was stalling to
give advantage to Hun Sen's CPP, as has been alleged by members of
the opposition.
	   Hun Sen has warned that if the opposition carried out its threat
not to attend the National Assembly, he could lower the
constitutional minimum for the assembly to meet and confirm a
government from two-thirds to 50 percent plus one.
	   He also said his current government could simply remain in
power.
	   Without the opposition's attendance, the assembly is unlikely to
have present the two-thirds of its 122 members needed to conduct
any major business.	   
</TEXT>
