r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-Flood     08-04 0295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Flood </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
One drowns, one hurt as torrential rain hits Japan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ One man drowned, another was hurt in a landslide
and 10,000 residents evacuated their homes Tuesday as the heaviest
rain in more than 80 years deluged north central Japan, officials
said.
	   Rains as heavy as 97 millimeters (3.8 inches) an hour hit
Niigata prefecture (state) early Tuesday, the hardest downpour
since the Central Meteorological Agency began compiling statistics
in 1914, the agency said.
	   Kiri Kobayashi, 77, drowned after he fell into a ditch and was
washed away on Sado Island, 325 kilometers (201 miles) north of
Tokyo, the Niigata Prefectural Police reported.
	   In Tochio City, just south of the prefectural capital of
Niigata, Ryokitsu Sano, 69, suffered a knee injury when hit by a
landslide.
	   In Sasakami, about 350 kilometers (217 miles) north of Tokyo, an
entire village of 9,700 residents was evacuated when a river
overflowed and broke a dike, a prefectural government spokesman
said. Some 900 others in other villages in Niigata were also
evacuated.
	   Niigata police said two houses were destroyed in landslides, and
12,903 had been flooded by midafternoon Tuesday. Police also
reported landslides at 45 places, 37 cases of road damage, three
bridges washed away and dikes broken in three places.
	   Electricity to 29,000 households in the city of Niigata was cut
off after two transformer substations were flooded, Kyodo News
service quoted local utility officials as saying. Some 12,800
households were still without electricity at midday, it said.
	   Most trains to Niigata city have been suspended.
	   Although rain weakened later Tuesday, the weather agency issued
new warnings of torrential rains and possible floods.
 &UR; (may)	   
</TEXT>
