<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Legislators say Hong Kong should consider deficit spending
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES graf 3 with Hang Seng index closing slightly higher &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ With no relief in sight for Hong Kong's
economy, the territory's largest political party is urging
officials not to dismiss deficit spending to ease the pain of its
struggling citizens.
	   On top of announcements Monday on its gross domestic product,
corporate earnings, layoffs and stock prices, the territory is
bracing for more bad news.
	   The stock market, after plunging 4.8 percent Monday, dropped
another 1.5 percent in early trading Tuesday. It rebounded later,
closing with a slight gain.
	   Monday's string of bad news also included a poor earnings report
by giant HSBC Holdings for this year's first six months, retail
layoffs and new government figures indicating that the economy
contracted more than originally thought in the first quarter of the
year.
	   More poor earnings reports are expected later in the week.
Cathay Pacific, the struggling airline, announces results on
Wednesday. Swire Pacific, which owns 44 percent of the airline and
also is heavily invested in the battered property market, announces
its first-half results on Thursday.
	   Hong Kong has become used to continuous growth in the past
decade. Instead, the economy shrank 2.8 percent in the first
quarter, and officials said Monday that results for the April-June
quarter are likely to be worse. Even in the second half of the
year, there will be no miracle turnaround, Financial Secretary
Donald Tsang said Monday.
	   As a way of maintaining financial discipline, the territory
customarily ties any spending increases to the economic growth
rate.
	   Measures that the government already has taken may lead to a
small deficit this year. Yeung Sum, a senior leader of Hong Kong's
Democratic Party, said the current economic troubles mean there is
likely to be very little growth next year, and little room for
increased spending to help struggling residents.
	   In comments to the South China Morning Post published Tuesday,
he urged the government not to ``blindly follow the rules.''
	   Yeung was quoted as saying the government should be flexible
enough to allow a deficit ``for an exceptional year in order to
meet the rising expectations of the community for livelihood
improvement.''
	   He said the government should reconsider the party's proposal to
return some of the salary and profit tax payments for the 1996-1997
tax year to struggling residents, whose income and investments both
have been hit hard.
	   Unemployment is at a 15-year high of 4.5 percent, and much
higher in some sectors. A union survey released over the weekend
indicated it had reached 17 percent in the retail and department
store sector. Other workers who kept their jobs were facing wage
cuts or freezes.
	   The stock and property markets have fallen dramatically in the
past year, and some analysts estimated the losses have cut assets
of Hong Kong residents by 4 trillion Hong Kong dollars (dlrs 516
billion).	   
</TEXT>
