<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Prosecutor's Trial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former East German prosecutor gets 1 1/2 years for perversion of
</HEADLINE>
justice &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LEIPZIG, Germany (AP) _ A former East German prosecutor was
convicted Tuesday of perversion of justice and wrongful deprivation
of liberty in three cases and given a suspended sentence of 18
months.
	   The state court in Leipzig also ordered Heinz Kurzke, 68, to pay
2,400 marks (dlrs 1,355) to the Buchenwald Foundation for support
of a memorial at the former Nazi concentration near Weimar.
	   Chief Judge Erich Drath said that Kurzke was clearly motivated
by politics when he prosecuted and obtained prison terms for three
East Germans who broke no laws, but only wanted to resettle in the
West between 1985 and 1987.
	   Kurzke said he accepted the verdict and would not appeal, even
though his defense lawyer had asked for a ruling of innocent during
the short two-session trial that opened last Thursday.
	   Since unification in 1990, numerous former East German justice
officials have been convicted of perversion of justice for
heavy-handed decisions against those seeking to flee repression
under East Germany's communists from 1949-1989. Most have received
similar light sentences.
 &UR; (gb-pfg)
</TEXT>
