w1728 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SouthAfrica-Tradition     08-04 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Traditional Doctors </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
S.Africa aims to legitimize traditional healers
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PAUL HARRIS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ Seeking to break a stereotyped
image of witchdocters chanting mumbo-jumbo, lawmakers on Tuesday
said they want to legitimize traditional African healers.
	   A report drawn up by parliamentary committees on social services
and health has recommended setting up a special council to regulate
the thousands of men and women who practice traditional medicine in
South Africa.
	   Aside from giving them medical certificates, proposals include
allowing healers to claim costs from their patients' medical
insurance, developing a code of conduct and establishing a register
of all traditional docters.
	   The planned council would also standardize treatments and prices
and promote training, research and the creation of a medicine data
base.
	   Using traditional medicine is still widespread among South
Africa's black population, especially in rural areas. Government
figures estimate up to 80 percent of South Africans will at
sometime use one of the country's 350,000 healers.
	   Under apartheid traditional medicine was banned, but the
practice did not disappear. Though the laws have not been changed
since 1994's all-race elections ended white rule, traditional
healers are now accepted again by government.
	   ``The report attempts to redress the inappropriate government
policies of the past, which were repressive and dehumanizing,'' the
document said ``Traditional healers were not only dehumanized but
branded as witches.''
	   The report recommends classifying traditional healers into four
types; herbalists, diviners, birth attendents and surgeons _ who
primarily perform in circumcision rituals.
	   Meetings between doctors and government will now take place
later this year and early in 1999, to discuss ways of implementing
the report and drafting legislation.
	   Elsewhere in the world, several other countries have already put
traditional medicine on the same level as Western medical science.
	   In China traditional doctors can go to special universities for
training and hospitals are divided into those who mainly use
traditional methods and those with Western-style doctors.
	    &UR; (ph-tl)	   
</TEXT>
