<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Czech-Havel, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Havel develops pneumonia, irregular heartbeat
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS more background &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) _ President Vaclav Havel suffered
from an irregular heartbeat on Tuesday and has developed pneumonia,
doctors said.
	   A statement from the presidential spokesman did not classify
Havel's immediate condition but said the situation ``is being
worked on intensively.''
	   ``The course of the president's treatment was complicated by
arrhythmia this morning,'' spokesman Martin Krafl said.
	   According to the statement, the beginning of pneumonia was
confirmed by computer tomography.
	   Havel remains in intensive care after undergoing surgery on July
26 to close a colostomy.
	   He ruptured his colon in April while vacationing in the Austrian
Alps. He underwent emergency surgery at the Innsbruck University
Clinic and colostomy was performed.
	   On July 26, a combined Austrian-Czech team of doctors closed the
colostomy in Prague at the president's request. Shortly afterward,
Havel's lungs collapsed briefly, forcing the use of a respirator.
	   Breathing problems and impaired immunity leading to infections
have hindered Havel's recovery.
	   Late Sunday, Havel's temperature shot up to 39 degrees Celsius
(102 degrees Fahrenheit), his heartbeat went up and laboratory
findings indicated a lung inflammation.
	   On Monday, doctors suspected pneumonia developing in the
president's right lung.
	   The 61-year-old president, formerly a chain smoker, has been
hospitalized five times since December 1996, when he had a third of
his lung and a tumor removed.
	   (oh/dc)
</TEXT>
