<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Rwanda-Rebels </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Army says it killed top rebel leader
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HRVOJE HRANJSKI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) _ The Rwandan army has killed a senior Hutu
rebel in northern Rwanda and has put his body on public display,
officials said Tuesday.
	   The man was killed Monday night when the army stopped rebels
from burning down administrative offices in Nyarutovu commune in
the troubled northwestern Ruhengeri region, officials said.
	   Nyarutovu, where the body the man identified as Maj. Mugemana
was put on display, is 50 kilometers (32 miles) northwest of
Kigali.
	   The army described Maj. Mugemana as a ``close bodyguard'' of
former Hutu president Juvenal Habyarimana, whose death in a plane
crash in April 1994 set off the Hutu government-sponsored genocide
in which more than half a million Tutsis and politically moderate
Hutus were killed.
	   The 90-day slaughter ended when Tutsi rebels overthrew the
government. Former members of the Hutu government and military,
many of whom were involved in the genocide, have since been
carrying out attacks inside Rwanda.
	   Hutu rebels have attacked Nyarutovu several times. They are
believed to have a base nearby.
	   The army has claimed a series of victories in the area in recent
weeks, saying it dealt the rebels a serious blow last week by
killing several of its leaders.
	   The Tutsi-dominated army also claims to have made headway on its
battle to win popular support in the predominantly Hutu northwest
and wean residents away from backing the rebels.
	   On Monday, the army said residents of the Rushashi commune in
Rural Kigali prefecture north of Kigali helped capture six rebels
who were believed to have participated in an attack on Sunday that
had left more than 100 dead.
	   The six will be tried, officials said.
	   (hh/dmc)	   
</TEXT>
