<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Zimbabwe-Currency </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Zimbabwe dollar falls 20 percent as economic fears deepen
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ The Zimbabwe Reserve Bank intervened at
the close of business Monday to freeze the exchange rate for the
local currency at 23 to the U.S. dollar.
	   The move came after a day of volatile trading that saw the
Zimbabwe dollar depreciate about 20 percent.
	   ``Speculation against the Zimbabwe dollar had been reflected in
unseasonably high and non-essential volumes of imports,'' the
reserve bank said Tuesday.
	   An International Monetary Fund delegation was due here Tuesday
to review payments of 176 million U.S. dollars in budget support
following President Robert Mugabe's backtracking on economic
liberalization pledges made since 1991.
	   Banks reported importers taking advantage of what they regarded
a temporarily unrealistic rate for the pressured South African Rand
against the Zim dollar.
	   ``This triggered a run on hard currency, particularly U.S.,''
said an executive of a major bank who asked not to be identified.
	   The reserve bank said the pressures led to a further
depreciation of the zim dollar to levels beyond those ``compatible
with economic fundamentals and developments in international
currency markets.''
	   Last mont the bank said the currency had reached a realistic
level of about 18 to the U.S. dollar.
	    &UR; (mh-tl)
</TEXT>
