<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Farmers Protest, 1st Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Farmers hold protests against grain imports
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES in top 5 grafs with roads, buildings blocked in some
places &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo planned &QL; 
 &UR; By MONIKA SCISLOWSKA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Protesting farmers blockaded roads and
government offices in several Polish towns Tuesday in a nationwide
demonstration against grain imports and low prices.
	   The protests were peaceful, with one including music from a folk
group, but they showed the increasing desire by farmers to display
their political muscle as Poland considers widespread reforms
needed to join the European Union.
	   In Goleniow, a town 520 kilometers (320 miles) northwest of
Warsaw, four tractors and a trailer filled with grain jammed the
access road to the city hall, an office worker in the building said
by telephone.
	   According to Mariusz Tarnozek, the worker, a banner on the
trailer said: ``We have grain, who will buy it?''
	   On the main road south from Warsaw, farmers tossed boxes of
potatoes and sacks of grain to halt vehicles and even stood in the
street themselves. No violence was reported, and a folk band played
music at one protest in Biala Podlaska, 120 kilometers (75 miles)
east of Warsaw.
	    &UR; Four farmers', 5th graf
	   (ms-tsc)
</TEXT>
