r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AsianMarkets     08-04 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asian Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian stock markets close generally lower
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Asian stock markets closed generally lower
Tuesday, with the key index in Manila slumping 2 percent to a
five-year low.
	   Traders said the Philippine market continued to be battered by
domestic and regional economic concerns. Shares were also pushed
down by the overnight decline of the Dow Jones Industrial Average,
which fell 96.55 points to 8,786.74.
	   The 30-share Philippine Stock Exchange Index fell 31.63 points
to 1,511.44 _ its lowest close since 1,480.30 on April 2, 1993.
This followed a drop of 64.54 points, or 4 percent, on Monday.
	   Asia's economic crisis has hit Philippine stocks hard, with the
PSE index losing nearly 20 percent since the start of the year.
	   Indonesian shares also tumbled on fears that the Indonesian
government will delay its plan to sell its stake in some
state-owned companies.
	   Dealers also blamed the uncertain political situation in
Indonesia after the government announced plans to investigate some
senior military officers for involvement in the kidnapping of
political activists.
	   The Jakarta Stock Exchange's Composite Index fell 2.9 percent,
or 13.91 points, to 461.350.
	   Share prices in Tokyo closed lower for a second consecutive
session.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 141.50 points,
or 0.88 percent, closing at 16,023.58. On Monday, the index had
shed 213.89 points, or 1.31 percent.
	   Traders said investors sold banking issues on worries that
restructuring of the nation's banking industry will take a toll on
the sector.
	   Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar fell against the yen after three
sessions of gains.
	   In late afternoon, the dollar was trading at 144.62 yen, down
1.02 yen from late Monday in Tokyo and also below its late New York
rate of 145.60 yen overnight.
	   Elsewhere:
	   HONG KONG: Share prices closed generally higher, a day after the
key index tumbled 4.8 percent. The Hang Seng Index rose 28.03
points, or 0.3 percent, closing at 7,580.80.
	   TAIPEI: Share prices closed lower in the wake of overnight
losses on U.S. stock markets. The market's key Weighted Stock Price
Index fell 5.90 points, or 0.07 percent, to 7,593.14.
	   WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed lower, with brokers
saying the local market suffered from falls on the U.S stock
market. The NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 23.03 points, or 1.0
percent, to 2,081.02.
	   SYDNEY: The Australian share market closed moderately higher.
The All Ordinaries Index rose 8.5 points, or 0.3 percent, to
2,682.3.
	   SEOUL: Share prices closed higher in reaction to a strong
Japanese currency Tuesday and recent cuts in local interest rates.
The Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 3.73 points, or 1.1
percent, to 333.20.
	   KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices close generally lower, but
the Composite Index, which tracks share prices of 100 key stocks,
edged up 0.17 point to 386.44.
	   SINGAPORE: Share prices closed mostly lower as last-minute
selling in index-linked stocks drove the benchmark index down. The
Straits Times Industrial Index fell 9.77 points, or 0.9 percent, to
1,064.99.
	   BANGKOK: Thai share prices closed lower on continued concern
over the ailing bank sector. The Stock Exchange of Thailand index
fell 2.85 points, or 1.1 percent, to 258.04.	   
</TEXT>
