<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Fighting,0489 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taliban even closer to Mazar-e-Sharif
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ZAHEERUDDIN ABDULLAH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) _ The Red Cross evacuated the last
foreign aid workers from the northern Afghanistan city of
Mazar-e-Sharif Tuesday, fearing a repeat of the street fighting and
looting that erupted when the Taliban religious militia briefly
held the city last year.
	   Taliban fighters advanced to just 20 kilometers (12 miles) west
of Mazar-e-Sharif, one of their opposition's few remaining
strongholds. Hundreds of residents were reportedly fleeing the
city.
	   The Taliban already controls most of Afghanistan. Bolstered by
recent victories, the extremist Islamic army appears poised to
capture the rest of the country.
	   Taliban troops engaged in minor skirmishes as they advanced
Tuesday, according to Taliban spokesman Abdul Hay Muttayn. He said
the religious militia was now pausing to build bunkers and take
other measures to shore up defenses. It was unclear when the
religious militia would attempt to capture Mazar-e-Sharif.
	   An opposition source in Mazar-e-Sharif who refused to be named
confirmed that Taliban fighters were 20 kilometers (12 miles) to
the west. The source, speaking by satellite phone, said residents
in the region were revolting against warlord Rashid Dostum, a
leader in the fractious anti-Taliban coalition, allowing the
Taliban to advance.
	   Dostum's whereabouts were unclear Tuesday, two days after the
Taliban pushed him out of his stronghold of Shebergan, 100
kilometers (60 miles) west of Mazar-e-Sharif. Taliban spokesman
Muttayn said Dostum's fighters were gathering south of Shebergan in
preparation for a counter-attack, but opposition sources had said a
day before that Dostum had retreated to Hayratan, about 60
kilometers (40 miles) east of Mazar-e-Sharif on Afghanistan's
border with Uzbekistan.
	   Taliban radio reported late Monday that Taliban fighters were
also east of Mazar-e-Sharif, within rocket range of the airport.
	   Red Cross spokesman Michel Schaffner said Mazar-e-Sharif was
calm Tuesday and the airport, which was closed the day before, was
open, allowing a Red Cross plane to land and pick up 11 aid
workers. A Pharmacists Without Borders spokesman said the 11
included three Afghans.
	   The workers were brought to the Pakistani border town of
Peshawar, where Schaffner spoke by telephone.
	   Taliban fighters briefly held Mazar-e-Sharif last May,
retreating after street battles in which hundreds of Taliban
soldiers died. As many as 2,000 Taliban prisoners of war reportedly
were later massacred.
	   Taliban leaders have imposed a strict version of Islamic law in
territory they control. Since capturing the Afghan capital, Kabul,
in 1996, they have barred girls from school and confined most women
to their homes.
	   The anti-Taliban alliance is made up mostly of Afghanistan's
religious and ethnic minorities. 	   
</TEXT>
