<SLUG> BC-China-Dissidents </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China bars Japan-based dissident from entering: report
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ A Japan-based Chinese democracy campaigner has
been barred from returning to China, the latest victim of a policy
of exiling those considered politically undesirable, a rights group
said Tuesday.
	   Wang Tingfang was turned away by Chinese customs agents when he
attempted to cross into China from Hong Kong on Saturday, the
Information Center of Human Rights and Democratic Movement in China
said in a news release.
	   Chinese police had briefly detained Wang and then forced him to
leave the country when he visited his wife and child in Shanghai
July 21, the Hong Kong-based center reported.
	   Wang was attempting to visit his sick father-in-law on both
occasions, it said.
	   The fact customs agents were able to pick out Wang for refusal
proves his name has been included on a ``not permitted entry-black
list,'' the center said.
	   Wang, chairman of the Japan branches of two U.S.-based dissident
groups, is the sixth overseas democracy activist barred entry to
China since April, the center said.
	   China routinely refuses entry to Chinese affiliated with
pro-democracy organizations abroad, though some have successfully
sneaked into the country.
	   Other activists, such as former student leader Wang Dan, have
been released from prison in China on condition they go into exile
abroad, and threatened with further imprisonment if they return.
	   Pro-democracy politicians in Hong Kong, which reverted from
British to Chinese sovereignty last year, have also been denied
entry to China.	   
</TEXT>
