<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Queen Mother, 3rd Ld - Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Royals gather for Queen Mother's 98th birthday
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: UPDATES with Queen Mother's appearance &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Queen Mother Elizabeth, wearing a yellow dress to
match the sunshine of a rare summery day, celebrated her 98th
birthday Tuesday by greeting well-wishers who had camped out to
join the party.
	   As the Band of Welsh Guards marched past, playing a specially
composed Royal Birthday March and then ``Happy Birthday'', the
Queen Mother smiled, waved and acknowledged the 45 bandsmen as she
stood at the gateway of Clarence House, her residence.
	   Children lined up to present bouquets to Britain's longest-lived
royal, who leaned on a cane as she walked to the gate. The sunshine
broke a long spell of clouds and rain in England, which has had wet
and dreary summer.
	   ``I've been looking forward to it more and more each year. It
has become an obsession,'' said Jennifer Hawkins, a 49-year-old
nurse from suburban London who was first in line outside Clarence
House.
	   ``I feel she is the nation's favorite grandmother and an
inspiration to us all,'' said Mrs. Hawkins, who staked out her
place Sunday morning.
	   Alan Rudd, a Londoner who was second in line, said he had been
coming to the birthday celebration for 17 years. ``She is so
special. She is very genuine when she talks to you. She is just a
sweet, dear lady,'' he said.
	   Two world wars, the death of her husband, the disappointment of
failed marriages among younger royals, two hip replacements and a
cataract operation _ the mother of Queen Elizabeth II has endured
them all.
	   When Edward VIII abdicated in 1936 to marry American divorcee
Wallis Simpson, the Queen Mother and her beloved husband Bertie _
then the Duke and Duchess of York _ were propelled into unwanted
and unsought sovereignty as George VI and Queen Elizabeth. They saw
Britain through the dark days of World War II and reigned until
George VI died in 1952, after 29 years of marriage.
	   As the royal family accelerates its program of modernization in
the wake of the death of Princess Diana in a Paris car crash Aug.
31, the Queen Mother is actively engaged in the life of the nation
and remains for some Britons the favorite royal.
	   ``I think it's important for us all to be here so she can see
how she is loved by the public. This is a special day and we want
to show her how much she is loved,'' said Alan Morton, 53, who
traveled from Edinburgh and got in line Monday morning.
	   ``I met her in person when I was four years old during the
Blitz. She came round to reassure people that they did not have to
leave the country. I have been following her ever since,'' said
Terry Hutt, 63, who wore a Union Jack hat.
	   ``I think she is a nice and gentle lady, she always says thank
you and I think that is worth coming for,'' Hutt said.
	   ``This is the highlight of the year for us royalists. It is a
big reunion,'' said Colin Edwards, 57, from Macclesfield.
	   Gill Corbett, 57, from Hucclecote in western England was in line
with her daughter Helen Edwards, 35, and her 5-year-old
granddaughter, Amy.
	   ``I wanted to wish her a happy birthday. I hope she gets some
jelly and ice cream for her birthday tea. I've brought her a
birthday card and some pink flowers as a birthday present,'' said
Amy, who wore a new pink dress for the occasion.
	   Tuesday's party plans included the band of the Welsh Guards
playing ``Happy Birthday,'' a 41-gun salute in Hyde Park and a
62-gun salute at the Tower of London, and lunch with Queen
Elizabeth II and other family members at Clarence House.
	   (er-rb)
</TEXT>
