<SLUG> BC-Congo, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kabila moving against rebellious troops
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with comments from state radio, justice
minister; officials warn of armed response to rebellion. Edits
throughout to conform. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; By KAMANGA MUTOND &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) _ President Laurent Kabila's government
issued an appeal Tuesday for public support against an open revolt
in eastern Congo and a brief armed challenge in the capital.
	   Accusing Rwandan soldiers and armed mercenaries of staging a
rebellion against the government, state-controlled radio quoted
Kabila as vowing to crush the uprising.
	   Kabila convened an emergency cabinet meeting Tuesday to discuss
the government's response to the rebellion in the east and to
earlier gun battles in two military barracks in the capital.
	   ``The government asks Congo's neighbors not to make the wrong
decisions to fight,'' Minister of State for the Presidency Pierre
Victor Mpoyo said in a radio broadcast following the meeting.
	   The comment was aimed directly at neighboring Rwanda, which
Kabila believes is behind the movement against his leadership.
Rwandan mercenaries and Tutsis from the Banyamulenge ethnic group
in eastern Congo played a key role in helping Kabila march to
victory last year over longtime dictator Mobutu Sese Seko.
	   Those same fighters today, however, appear to be moving to get
rid of Kabila.
	   A delicate ethnic and military alliance that helped thrust
Kabila _ a one-time obscure Marxist rebel _ into power 14 months
ago is now unraveling.
	   Rwandan officials on Monday said unrest in Congo's capital and
in the eastern province of North Kivu was an internal matter and
denied any involvement.
	   Congo's Justice Minister Mwenze Kongolo told The Associated
Press that the government was preparing an armed response to the
rebellion in the eastern province of North Kivu.
	   On Monday, military officers said they had seized control of the
province and were vowing to oust Kabila, news reports in
neighboring Rwandan said.
	   The majority ethnic Tutsi population in North Kivu has close
links with Rwanda and Kabila's support and control of the region
has faltered for months.
	   ``They are bandits organized to loot the country,'' Kongolo
said, describing the breakaway leaders in North Kivu.
	   He said Rwandan soldiers had been seen in the towns of Goma and
Bukavu along the border with Rwanda.
	   ``We're telling them to lay down their arms and end this
adventure before we immediately bring in the army,'' Kongolo said.
	   In the capital one day after shots rang out at two military
bases on Kinshasa's west end, loyal troops continued to patrol city
streets and man roadblocks as heightened security left the city
tense. A dusk-to-dawn curfew was still in effect, but life in the
city began to return to normal as abandoned streets began to fill
again with shoppers and merchants.
	   Offices and shops reopened after being ordered closed on Monday.
	   Pre-dawn clashes Monday at two military bases apparently pitted
Kabila's troops against Rwandan mercenaries, who last year helped
the president oust Mobutu Sese Seko. Kabila last week ordered all
Rwandan soldiers to leave the country.
	   Earlier, Kabila sacked James Kabari, a Rwandan Tutsi who had
been the president's top military commander.
 &UR; (var/ids)
</TEXT>
