<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Corruption, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italy extradites official in corruption case, Swiss say
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES lead, 2nd graf with extradition confirmed. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) _ Italy has extradited a local
government official at the heart of Switzerland's biggest
corruption scandal, Swiss authorities said Tuesday.
	   Raphael Huber was handed over to Swiss authorities in the border
town of Chiasso, the Zurich district attorney's office and the
Federal Office of Police Affairs said.
	   In November, Raphael Huber, sentenced by Zurich district court
in 1995 to five years in prison, was arrested on his estate in
Italy.
	   Huber, who was in charge of restaurant permits in the canton
(state) of Zurich, was found guilty of accepting 1.38 million Swiss
francs (then dlrs 1.2 million) in bribes.
	   The court, which tried him in his absence, also ordered him to
repay the money within three months, plus a fine of 200,000 francs
(dlrs 174,000). Huber had been living in Italy since the scandal
came to light in 1991.
	   The court also handed down suspended prison sentences to four
prominent local businessmen.
	   Swiss authorities had issued an arrest warrant only for
Switzerland, giving Huber the opportunity to return on his own.
	   But when Huber failed to appear before an appeals court in
November, the prosecutor announced he had issued an international
warrant. Italian authorities then took him into custody at his
estate near Gaiole.
	   The corruption scandal shocked Switzerland's normally staid
business community. Although Swiss banks are often accused of
accepting dirty money, cases of domestic corruption are rare.
	   Huber was accused of accepting and in some cases demanding money
for restaurant licenses and allegedly used the money for the estate
in northern Italy.
 &UR; (gm)
</TEXT>
