r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-Lawsuit     08-04 0264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Lawsuit </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian Cabinet minister sues media over report on 1996 raid
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ A Cabinet minister has sued a number
of Indonesian media organizations for reporting his alleged
involvement in a raid on the headquarters of an opposition leader
in 1996, a newspaper said Tuesday.
	   Home Affairs Minister Syarwan Hamid, who is an army lieutenant
general, filed the case Monday at police headquarters in Jakarta,
the daily Suara Pembaruan said.
	   It quoted a police spokesman, Maj. Gen. Da'i Bachtiar, as saying
his office is studying the report.
	   Bachtiar refused to specify the number as well as the names of
the media organizations.
	   Newspaper, magazines and television stations have been stepping
up reports on those allegedly behind the raid following
commemorations marking the second anniversary of the incident last
month.
	   On July 27, 1996, a government-backed faction staged a predawn
raid on the headquarters of the minority Indonesian Democratic
Party, which was being occupied by supporters of pro-democracy
leader Megawati Sukarnoputri.
	   Megawati, the eldest daughter of Indonesia's founding President
Sukarno, was ousted from the party in June the same year by a rival
group supported by the government.
	   Her ouster prompted the occupation of the headquarters.
	   Riots broke out after the raid, and at least five people were
killed and more than a dozen reported missing.
	   At the time, Syarwan was the military's chief of staff for
social and political affairs. He has denied involvement in the
raid.	   
</TEXT>
