<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0738 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ The chief U.N. weapons inspector cut short
his trip to Baghdad when talks with Iraq on dismantling Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction collapsed Tuesday. Richard Butler, head
of the U.N. Special Commission, checked out of Baghdad's Al-Rashid
Hotel in the morning and headed to an air base for a flight to
Bahrain. He declined to say what had caused the impasse in Monday's
talks with Iraq's deputy prime minister, Tariq Aziz. On Monday,
Aziz accused Butler of being an American pawn in trying to prolong
the punishing U.N. trade sanctions imposed on Iraq after its 1990
invasion of Kuwait. The sanctions ban air travel and limit the sale
of oil, Iraq's economic mainstay. (IRAQ)
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) _ Congo's capital remained under a curfew
Tuesday and troops loyal to President Laurent Kabila manned
roadblocks throughout the city searching for renegade Rwandan
mercenaries. In eastern Congo, military officers declared a revolt
Monday against Kabila and urged the population to oust the
president. About 14 months after charging victoriously into
Kinshasa, the rebel alliance that carried Kabila to power appears
to be unraveling. Defense officials ordered troops to kill any
Rwandan soldiers found hiding in and around the deserted city.
Pre-dawn clashes Monday at two military bases apparently pitted
Kabila's troops against Rwandan mercenaries, who last year helped
the president oust longtime dictator Mobutu Sese Seko. Kabila last
week ordered all Rwandan soldiers to leave the country. (CONGO)
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ International aid agencies were
struggling Tuesday to reach tens of thousands of refugees camped in
the woods of Kosovo province, after Serb attacks forced them to
flee their villages. The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees was
planning an aid convoy for ethnic Albanians near Malisevo, a former
stronghold of the secessionist Kosovo Liberation Army, where
thousands of refugees had sought shelter. Serb forces reportedly
toppled three additional KLA strongholds Monday, just days after
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic promised to stop his attack
on the rebels. Ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs 9-to-1 in Kosovo
province, part of the Serb republic that dominates Yugoslavia. In
Washington Monday, the U.S. government announced that NATO had
approved a plan to use firepower against Serb forces in Kosovo, but
officials at NATO headquarters said that no military action was
being planned at this stage. (YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO)
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Waterlogged levees along China's flood-swollen
Yangtze River have started to collapse, wreaking death and
destruction on a massive scale, state media said Tuesday.
Torrential rains in southwest Sichuan province also have triggered
flooding that killed at least 20 people, pushing the known death
toll from floods caused by unusually heavy and early summer rains
this year to 1,288. With a tropical storm and another flood tide
expected, the threat mounted of further breaches along the already
weakened levees that protect millions of people and rich farmland
from the Yangtze, the world's third-longest river. A Hong
Kong-based human rights group said 150 soldiers and hundreds of
villagers were swept away when a levee suddenly collapsed Saturday
in the central province of Hubei, and that more than 1,000 people
were believed missing. (CHINA-FLOODS)
	   ADDIS ABABA (AP) _ With a war-induced famine killing hundreds of
people a day, representatives of the Sudanese government and rebels
fighting in southern Sudan have again agreed to put down their
weapons and look for a solution to their 15-year-old civil war. The
government in Khartoum announced a unilateral cease-fire throughout
southern Sudan Monday to let humanitarian relief reach an estimated
1.5 million people threatened by famine. Talks to end the fighting
were set to begin Tuesday. The latest cease-fire expands the scope
of a three-month truce agreed to last month between the government
and the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army in the hardest-hit
southwestern region of Bahr al-Ghazal. The mainly African,
Christian and animist southerners have been fighting the Islamic,
Arabized north since 1983 for greater autonomy. (SUDAN-PEACE TALKS)
</TEXT>
