r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-India-Killings     08-04 0300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Killings,0301 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
19 killed by rival group in Kashmir
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BINOO JOSHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JAMMU, India (AP) _ Unidentified assailants entered a remote
village in the Indian-controlled part of Kashmir and killed 19
people, in what police described Tuesday as a feud between two
groups of separatist fighters.
	   Kashmir police chief Gurbachan Jagat said the victims were all
relatives of a militant known as Imtiaz, who is wanted by police
for alleged acts of terrorism. Details of Monday's killings in the
village of Siala were not immediately clear.
	   Meanwhile, shelling across the India-Pakistan border, which
killed 88 people over the last several days, tapered off Tuesday.
Cross-border gunfire intensified last week when Indian and
Pakistani leaders held inconclusive talks over the disputed
territory of Kashmir.
	   The killings came less than a day after suspected Kashmiri
militants shot dead 34 laborers, most or all of them Hindus, in the
adjoining state of Himachal Pradesh.
	   India and Pakistan have fought two wars over Kashmir, which is
divided between them. Militants in the Indian-controlled part of
Kashmir want to secede or unite with Muslim Pakistan. The Indian
part of Kashmir is the country's only state with an Islamic
majority.
	   Jagat said the suspected militant, Imtiaz, belonged to
Tehrik-e-Jihad, one of several groups fighting for Kashmir's
separation from India. That group is feuding with another group
called Hizbul Mujahideen.
	   In New Delhi Tuesday, Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee told
Parliament the government was taking ``firm steps'' to deal with
militants in Kashmir, the Press Trust of India reported. Opposition
legislators accused the government of failing to protect its
citizens after repeated civilian massacres. 	   
</TEXT>
