<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0796 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 1100 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Asian stock markets closed generally lower
Tuesday, with the key index in Manila slumping 2 percent to a
five-year low. Traders said the Philippine market continued to be
battered by domestic and regional economic concerns. Shares were
also pushed down by the overnight decline of the Dow Jones
Industrial Average, which fell 96.55 points to 8,786.74. The
30-share Philippine Stock Exchange Index fell 31.63 points to
1,511.44 _ its lowest close since April 1993. Indonesian shares
also tumbled on fears that the Indonesian government will delay its
plan to sell its stake in some state-owned companies. In Tokyo, the
benchmark Nikkei Stock Average lost 141.50 points, or 0.88 percent,
closing at 16,023.58. Traders said investors sold banking issues on
worries that restructuring of the nation's banking industry will
take a toll on the sector. Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar fell against
the yen, trading by late afternoon at 144.62 yen, down 1.02 yen
from late Monday. (ASIAN MARKETS)
	   ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) _ Casting himself as a champion of
Caribbean economic rights, Cuban President Fidel Castro wrapped up
a three-island tour that showed his communist island to be a
powerful _ and popular _ influence in the region. Castro received
warm welcomes in Jamaica, Barbados and Grenada, even from past
foes, and won strong support for his demand that the United States
drop its 38-year economic boycott against Cuba. He reciprocated by
attacking Washington's challenge to the European Union's
preferential trade terms for Caribbean bananas _ a benefit seen as
a lifeline for many of the vulnerable island economies. Castro also
blamed the North American Free Trade Agreement, which links the
United States, Canada and Mexico, for allegedly robbing the
Caribbean of more than 100,000 jobs. He pitched his message to the
concerns of tiny nations dangerously dependent on limited sources
of income _ tourism, textiles, bananas, sugar _ and jittery about
the emergence of a single global economy in which they cannot
compete. (CARIBBEAN-CASTRO)
	   DETROIT _ General Motors Corp. could face another ugly
confrontation with the United Auto Workers, this time over its plan
to discard its big Delphi parts business by the end of next year.
The move will further reduce the size of the No. 1 automaker and
mark a drastic shift away from GM's history as a vertically
integrated automaker that made most of its parts and assembled them
into finished cars and trucks. Early next year, the automaker will
offer up to 20 percent of Delphi in a public stock offering, then
turn over the remaining part of the company to GM shareholders. The
announcement was met with a terse UAW statement that implied more
labor problems for the automaker, which settled two crippling
strikes last week. (GM-REORGANIZATION)
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Overcoming public opposition and safety fears,
Japan for the first time in 10 years will build a commercial
nuclear power plant for generating electricity, officials said
Tuesday. After months of discussion, the government's five-member
Nuclear Safety Commission concluded Monday there would be no
problem with the construction and operation of a new nuclear
reactor. That move paves the way for Kaoru Yosano, Minister of
International Trade and Industry, to soon give the go-ahead for the
construction of a nuclear power plant in Higashidori, a village in
Aomori Prefecture, or state, in northern Japan, ministry officials
said. The commission also judged safety will be maintained, even if
a magnitude 6.5 earthquake strikes below the site of a nuclear
power facility, the ministry officials said. (JAPAN-NUCLEAR)
	   CHICAGO _ His attorney has long said that Michael Andreas,
executive vice president of the Archer Daniels Midland Co.,
``doesn't make deals.'' But a retired Japanese executive claimed
otherwise during testimony in the ADM federal price-fixing trial.
Hirokazu Ikeda, formerly of the Tokyo-based Ajinomoto Co. Inc.,
testified that Andreas agreed to put a cap on the amount of the
feed additive lysine that ADM would sell in 1994 during a meeting
in Irvine, California, in October 1993. Andreas, who is on leave
from ADM, is also the son of chairman Dwayne Andreas. He is the
highest-ranking of three current and former ADM executives accused
in the price-fixing trial. Andreas' attorney, John Bray, has said
his client's comments were simply the talk of a cagey competitor
who was trying to figure out how big the worldwide lysine market
was. (US-ADM TRIAL)
</TEXT>
