<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Building Collapse, 1st Ld-Writethru,0371 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Death toll in building collapse climbs to 16
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with higher death toll; ADDS quotes from survivors,
background on three other building collapses. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos BOM101-103 &QL; 
 &UR; By RAMOLA TALWAR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ Firemen and volunteers scrabbled with their
bare hands Tuesday to search for survivors in the debris of a
collapsed building, discovering more bodies that boosted the death
toll to 16, police said.
	   Rescuers working though the night found 22 people alive in the
rubble of the building, which authorities had declared structurally
unsound earlier this year. Police feared as many as 15 people were
still trapped inside.
	   Cranes worked under floodlights to remove large chunks of
concrete to clear the way for rescuers to pull out victims. Workers
heard moans and cries for help from under the rubble.
	   Sobbing relatives searched for missing family members among the
injured being taken to hospitals.
	   ``I was buying medicines when I saw part of the building
crumble, and I ran for my life. By the time I turned around the
whole structure had toppled. It took less than 10 seconds,'' said
Manesh Rai, who was among the first to be discharged after
treatment for minor injuries.
	   Bina Shah spoke of the nightmare of being buried alive for more
than 10 hours.
	   ``I must have blacked out for the most part,'' Shah said. ``I
don't remember much but loud voices and rumbling sounds, I just
remember feeling very scared.''
	   The 20-year-old building crumpled with a loud thud Monday night.
Three of its seven stories had been added as a guest house without
authorization from city authorities.
	   Municipal officials said they had ordered residents to vacate
the building several months ago, reportedly after it was seen to be
leaning to one side. The warning was ignored.
	   ``We feared yesterday the toll could have been much higher ....
because of the guest house,'' said Sridhar Joshi, a top civic
official. Many rooms were unoccupied at the time of the collapse.
</TEXT>
