<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Slayings Arrest, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cambodian officials vow to speed trial of alleged Khmer Rouge
</HEADLINE>
killer &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with comments from Sam Rainsy; ADDS Monday's comments
from Ranariddh; minor edits &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Cambodian justice officials said
Tuesday they are working to speed up the trial of a former Khmer
Rouge guerrilla accused of ordering the killing of three Western
tourists in 1994.
	   Nuon Paet was arrested Saturday in the murders of David Wilson,
29, of Australia, Mark Slater, 28, of Britain and Jean-Michel
Braquet, 27, of France, who were killed after being held hostage by
the guerrillas for about two months.
	   The young Westerners were abducted from a train that had been
stopped by Nuon Paet's guerrillas in the southern province of
Kampot.
	   Justice Minister Chem Snguon said Tuesday he has asked the
provincial court in Kampot, where the three were slain, to transfer
the case to Phnom Penh within the next few days.
	   Nop Sophon, deputy chief of the Phnom Penh court, said that once
he receives the go-ahead, ``we will start handling the case
immediately.''
	   Nuon Paet was arrested in Phnom Penh after the government lured
him to the capital from the former guerrilla stronghold of Pailin
with a bogus offer of a business deal.
	   He is being detained at the capital's dilapidated T-3 prison,
which houses political detainees and other important criminals and
suspects.
	   Although the warrant for Nuon Paet's arrest was originally
issued in Kampot, Cambodian leader Hun Sen said over the weekend
that he wanted the trial held in Phnom Penh ``for security
reasons.''
	   Prominent opposition politician Sam Rainsy, meanwhile,
questioned the timing of Nuon Paet's arrest, just one week after
parliamentary elections.
	   ``Nobody is fooled. Even two of the victims' fathers say they
are not satisfied with the timing or motivation of the arrest,''
Sam Rainsy said.
	   Critics say Hun Sen knew of Nuon Paet's whereabouts for nearly
two years, but only had him arrested Saturday to express thanks to
foreign governments that helped fund and give a stamp of approval
to Cambodia's electoral process.
	   Hun Sen, whose party leads in returns so far, hopes that the
elections will restore legitimacy and aid lost after he ousted
Prince Norodom Ranariddh in a violent coup last July.
	   Ranariddh, Sam Rainsy's partner in opposition, on Monday
described Nuon Paet's arrest as a ``tragic comedy.''
	   ``Why? Because Hun Sen has known for a long time where Nuon Paet
is, but he didn't do anything,'' Ranariddh told reporters.
	   He acted now, Ranariddh said, because he wanted ``to please
Australia, Britain and France'' after the elections.
	   Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said Sunday that
the arrest would play no part in his country's evaluation of the
election process.	   
</TEXT>
