<HEADLINE>
German prince fined for umbrella attack on reporter
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOVER, Germany (AP) _ Prince Ernst August of Hanover has been
fined 90,000 marks (dlrs 50,800) for beating a photographer trying
to snap pictures of him with Princess Caroline of Monaco,
prosecutors said Tuesday.
	   Charges of assault will be dropped if the prince agrees to pay
the fine, to be divided evenly between two charity organizations
and the state of Lower Saxony, a statement from state prosecutors
said.
	   Prosecutors charged the prince beat photographer Karsten
Thuernau repeatedly for seven minutes with an umbrella at his
Pattensen estate, near Hanover, on the night of Jan. 11.
	   Thuernau, who had been waiting outside the estate to take a
picture of the royal couple, was not seriously injured. The prince
had claimed he was not trying to hit Thuernau, but only his camera.
