<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Sudan </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU approves dlrs 49.5 million in aid to Sudan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) - The European Union approved 45 million
European currency units (dlrs 49.5 million) in aid Tuesday for
southern Sudan, where war has threatened hundreds of thousands of
people with starvation.
	   The European Commission, the EU's executive arm, said the money
will help fund the activities of the U.N. World Food Program and
other organizations working to feed people in southern Sudan.
	   ``A combination of drought and escalating conflict has
aggravated the crisis in the region,'' the Commission said in a
statement. ``People are dying in increasingly alarming numbers, and
malnutrition is rampant.''
	   The Commission, citing World Food Program estimates, said
700,000 people need emergency food aid in rebel-controlled areas in
the province of Bahr El Ghazal, compared to 250,000 at the start of
1998.
	   The WFP is ``currently aiming to move a total of 15,000 metric
tons of food a month to aid a target population of 2.4 million in
Sudan,'' the Commission said.
	   The Sudan People's Liberation Army has fought since 1983 for
autonomy for the south's Christian and animist peoples. An
estimated 1.5 million have died in the fighting and consequent
famines.
	   Under pressure from aid organizations, the United Nations and
donor countries, the government and the Sudan People's Liberation
Army rebels agreed in July to a three-month cease-fire to permit
distribution of food.
	   The Commission said the latest aid package brings to 66 million
ecu (dlrs 73 million) the total amount it has spent in humanitarian
aid for Sudan.
	    &UR; (as-ju)
</TEXT>
