r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Singapore-Jehovah'sWi     08-04 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Jehovah's Witness </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore Jehovah's Witness told to violate belief or lose job
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By LAURINDA KEYS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ A Jehovah's Witness, whose beliefs prohibit him
from singing the national anthem or reciting the national pledge,
testified in court Tuesday how superiors ordered him to participate
in those rituals and dissociate himself from fellow believers or
lose his job.
	   ``I was appalled,'' Peter Nappalli, 37, testified as he closed
his case seeking reinstatement to his teaching job at a vocational
institute. ``It was really against every constitutional right that
I have.'' He said the letter essentially was ordering him to
abandon his family, who are also Jehovah's Witnesses.
	   The defendants' case was to open Wednesday and closing arguments
were expected Friday.
	   The first two days were taken up mostly in cross-examination
that seldom focused on constitutional rights, but instead on
whether Nappalli had warned his employers when he was hired that he
would not recite the national pledge or sing the anthem.
	   Defense attorney Tang Khin Wei repeatedly accused Nappalli of
lying about his intentions during his initial job interviews.
	   Nappalli, who supports his family as a tutor, repeatedly
affirmed that he had made his position clear, and that his
employers would have known anyway because he spent his military
service in prison camp for refusing to participate in army
activities.
	   Nappalli, who was fired from his tenured post teaching English
and mathematics in 1994, is suing to get back his job, lost pay, a
clear conduct record and compensation for infringement of his
constitutional rights.
	   Although there is no national law requiring citizens to recite
the national pledge or sing the anthem, the vocational institute
where Nappalli worked for 10 years, and other government-linked
institutions such as schools, have established such internal
requirements.
	   Singapore's constitution guarantees individuals the right to
practice, profess and propagate religious beliefs, but laws
restrict those freedoms.
	   For instance, the Jehovah's Witness denomination is banned from
meeting in groups of more than three people, possessing its own
version of the Bible and other literature, owning land, buying or
selling. It is illegal for adherents of the faith to go door to
door proselytizing.
	   Each year up to 40 young male Jehovah's Witnesses are sentenced
to prison labor camps for refusing to serve in the military,
although they are willing to perform other forms of national
service. Jehovah's Witness elders say there are about 1,400
adherents in Singapore, while some government estimates range up to
2,000.
	   Although it remains legal for Singaporeans to be Jehovah's
Witnesses and profess their faith, Nappalli testified that in
January 1994, he received a letter from the vocational school
saying it ``cannot allow its employees to be associated with any
banned or illegal organization or to participate in their
activities.''
	   ``I should not be forced to give up my religious faith by
threats of dismissal,'' Nappalli said in a sworn affidavit that
constituted part of his testimony. ``My decision to maintain my
faith and job was met with further reprisals designed to force me
to abandon my faith.''	   
</TEXT>
