<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-17th Century Shopping,0434 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Collectors of Rembrandt's time bought art _ and nutmeg graters
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo WX101 &QL; 
 &UR; By CARL HARTMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Collectors with spare cash can pick up tips
from a popular exhibit at the National Gallery of Art that shows
how the newly rich of Rembrandt's time indulged a taste for curios
as well as paintings.
	   Prosperity, scientific discovery and a slew of new artists gave
Dutch collecting a special push in the 1600s. Wealthy burghers
bought and admired almost anything from insect specimens to nutmeg
graters to the world's greatest masterpieces. Some of the same
factors are still at work.
	   Collectors were ``armed with the belief that God had placed man
in the center of the world and had provided him with the means to
achieve unlimited knowledge,'' says the gallery's director, Earl A.
Powell III.
	   Among the items: a collection of paintings of golfers, playing
on ice. Over 300 years ago an unknown connoisseur snagged one in
Holland by Hendrick Avercamp. In the picture, the golfer wears a
big starched and pleated ruff around his neck _ the fashion of the
day _ that appears to be preventing him from keeping his head down.
	   He also appears to be having trouble keeping his tall hat from
falling off as he tries to keep his footing on the ice.
	   ``I'd have told him to relax _ bend the elbows and knees a
little,'' said Matt Kayson, the pro at the East Potomac Golf
Course, which is near the gallery.
	   At least five other painters of the period did golf scenes,
including Rembrandt.
	   The exhibit, called ``A Collector's Cabinet,'' also includes two
paintings that illustrate the helter-skelter look of Dutch
collections of the time.
	   One picture, done partly by Jan Breughel the Elder about 1620,
shows important guests looking over a collection in Antwerp. Nine
elaborately dressed men and women are examining large paintings,
small sculptures, jewelry, atlases, musical and scientific
instruments. There are also five dogs and two monkeys in the
picture, looking a little bored.
	   The other painting is by Jan Breughel the Younger. It has a nude
Venus in it, apparently live, as well as art and curios.
	   Curator Arthur K. Wheelock Jr. said the owners of these
collections are unknown. By the end of the 1600s, the fad of
accumulating almost anything had faded, and collections became more
specialized.
	   _____
	   The exhibit, which was to have closed Aug. 9, has been so
popular that it was extended to Nov. 1. Admission is free.
</TEXT>
