<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Romania-Journalists Sentenced </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Journalists handed one-year jail sentences for alleged libel
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) _ Two journalists have been sentenced to
one year in prison, deprived of civil rights for one year and
ordered to pay damages equal to dlrs 170,000 after a judge sued
them for allegedly libeling her husband, their editor said Tuesday.
	   The journalists, Ovidiu Scultelnicu, 31, and Dragos Stangu, 30
are free pending an appeal, said Toni Hritac, editor-in-chief of
the Monitorul newspaper in Iasi, northeast Romania.
	   On May 27, the two published an article disclosing details of a
meeting of police chiefs in which a police colonel was accused of
ignoring complaints filed by local residents and of amassing wealth
of uncertain origin.
	   Col. Petru Susanu was dismissed after the article appeared and
his wife, a judge, sued for libel. Their daughter is also a judge
and their son-in-law is a prosecutor in Iasi, some 325 kilometers
(203 miles) northeast of Bucharest.
	   In post-Communist Romania, officials are unaccustomed to
criticism in the free-wheeling press. Justice officials are often
suspected to be corrupt. They are accused of delaying some cases
for years while rushing through others in which they have a vested
interest.
	   The journalists said the court in Iasi was biased and asked the
Supreme Court to relocate the trial elsewhere, but the request was
refused, Hritac said.
	   Hritac, speaking by telephone, said the sentence was based on
``vengeance and shows that the justice system is corrupt.''
	   The sentence was passed on July 23, but due to bureaucracy,
Monitorul learned of it only late last week.
	   The journalists were fined 1.5 billion lei (dlrs 170,000), a
fortune in Romania where the average salary is about dlrs 110.
	   (am/rp)
</TEXT>
