<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Taiwan-Airlines </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore Airlines and Taiwan's China Airlines form strategic
</HEADLINE>
alliance &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Singapore's flagship air carrier cemented a
strategic alliance with its Taiwanese counterpart Tuesday,
including the purchase of a substantial stake in Taiwan's China
Airlines.
	   A memorandum of understanding between Singapore Airlines and
China Airlines called for the purchase of between 5 and 10 percent
of China Airlines shares within the next six months, a statement
from the city-state's carrier said.
	   Singapore Airlines deputy chairman and chief executive officer
Cheong Choong Kong said the stake may be increased in the future.
	   ``We see China Airlines as a good investment,'' he said. ``It
demonstrates our faith in the long-term future of the aviation
industry in this region, notwithstanding the present economic
difficulties.''
	   He added that Singapore Airlines will explore joint ventures
with China Airlines in airline-related businesses.
	   Flight schedules will be coordinated for faster and more
convenient connections between the carriers, which will also share
flights on certain routes, the statement said.
	   Singapore Airlines operates 87 aircraft to 76 destinations in 41
countries, while China Airlines operates 52 jetliners serving 46
destinations in 20 countries.
	   The Singapore carrier's group total revenue for fiscal 1997 was
about 7.7 billion Singapore dollars (dlrs 4.5 billion), while China
Airline's operating revenue last year totaled about 55.9 billion
Taiwan dollars (dlrs 1.63 billion).	   
</TEXT>
