<HEADLINE>
Japan's foreign minister to visit Moscow in September
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Japan's new foreign minister plans to visit Moscow
in September, a news report said Tuesday.
	   Masahiko Kamura said he planned to make the trip during a phone
conversation with Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov, the
ITAR-Tass news agency said.
	   Kamura reiterated that Tokyo's policy towards Russia would not
change despite a recent Japanese government shakeup.
	   He said Japan and Russia would work together in line with two
summits held in the last year between President Boris Yeltsin and
former Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto.
	   Despite disagreement over the Kuril Islands, which Russia has
controlled since the end of World War II, relations between the two
countries have improved in recent years.
