<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Cambodia-Refugees </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
First repatriation of Cambodian refugees since election
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ A group of 755 Cambodian refugees left
Thailand's eastern province of Trat to go home Tuesday in the first
voluntary repatriation since Cambodia's election July 26.
	   The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees announced that the
repatriations bring the total of Cambodians who have returned home
overland from Thailand since Oct. 10, 1997, to 7,147.
	   Police escorted the convoy of buses and trucks to the crossing
point of Aranyaprathet and on into Poipet, Cambodia. They will go
home to 11 Cambodian provinces.
	   Some 55,000 Cambodians fled their country after strongman Hun
Sen deposed his co-prime minister, Prince Norodom Ranariddh, in a
coup last year that triggered a new round of warfare.
	   The fighting abated several months ago in preparation for new
parliamentary elections intended to restore stability, prompting
many to return home. Hun Sen's party has apparently won the vote.
	   Many of the refugees who remain in Thailand are family members
of hard-line Khmer Rouge guerrillas who have not made peace with
the government.	   
</TEXT>
