<HEADLINE>
Abacha's security adviser arrested in Nigeria
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ The top national security adviser to the
late dictator Gen. Sani Abacha has been arrested and charged with
widescale fraud and corruption, a Lagos newspaper reported Tuesday.
	   Ismaila Gwarzo, the man who ran Abacha's feared and often
loathed internal security apparatus, was arrested in connection
with a investigation into bank fraud and corruption, Thisday
newspaper reported.
	   His arrest comes about one month after he was fired by Nigeria's
new military leader Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar. Abacha died of an
apparent heart attack in early June.
	   Gwarzo was arrested on Saturday at his Kano home in northern
Nigeria near the border with Niger, Thisday reported.
	   In one instance, Gwarzo is accused of illegally channeling
millions of dollars and British pounds sterling into slush funds
earmarked for pro-Abacha promotion campaigns.
	   Millions more were reportedly set aside to try to finance
Nigeria's way into a permanent seat on the United Nations Security
Council, Thisday reported.
	   Just days before his arrest, Gwarzo's passport was seized.
	   Shortly after Abacha's death he had returned about dlrs 250
million to government coffers, but that failed to halt an
investigation into his alleged corrupt practices.
 &UR; (fa/ids)
</TEXT>
