r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Croatia-Farmers     08-04 0280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Croatia-Farmers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Croatian farmers block roads to protest increased costs
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) _ Facing losses in the sale of wheat crops
to the state, farmers in eastern Croatia blocked a local main road
Tuesday, demanding higher prices for their yield.
	   Meanwhile, in Poland protesting farmers also blockaded roads as
well as government offices in a nationwide demonstration against
grain imports and low prices.
	   As early as 7 a.m., hundreds of angry Croatian farmers, perched
atop tractors or on foot held up traffic, chanting slogans on a
main road in Djakovo, a rich, fertile strip of land some 300
kilometers (188 miles) east of the capital Zagreb.
	   ``After paying value-added tax, the farmer is left with no
profit at all,'' said Antun Laslo, leader of the region's farmers
union at the rally.
	   The government signed a deal with the farmers' union to buy up
wheat crops at 1.10 kuna (17 cents) per kilo last year. But the
agreement did not envision a 22 percent sales tax which was
introduced earlier this year on all goods and services.
	   The farmers are demanding that the government renegotiate the
going price to take into consideration the new tax.
	   They threatened to expand the protest to major highways if a new
accord is not reached. The government has shown no signs of
submitting to the demands.
	   ``At this rate, fields across the region will be bare next
season, as sowing for wholesale can only be carried out at an
absolute loss,'' Laso said.
	   Agriculture is the main income source for the majority of people
in eastern Croatia. The region's grain supply caters largely for
the entire country.
	   (eb/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
