</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0522 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Aid agencies struggle to reach Kosovo refugees
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with U.N. official saying convoy plans on hold due to
fighting, quotes, Serb report echoes claim that three KLA
strongholds overrun Monday, U.S. envoy comments &QL; 
 &UR; By ANNE THOMPSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ International aid agencies were
struggling Tuesday to reach tens of thousands of refugees camped in
the woods of Kosovo province, after Serb attacks forced them to
flee their villages.
	   Fighting stymied plans by the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees to send an aid convoy Tuesday for ethnic Albanians near
Malisevo, a former stronghold of the secessionist Kosovo Liberation
Army, where thousands of refugees had sought shelter.
	   ``We cannot go into a battlefield,'' UNHCR spokesman Kris
Janowski said in Geneva.
	   There were no immediate details on the latest fighting.
	   The Serb Media Center on Tuesday echoed earlier reports that
Serb forces toppled three additional KLA strongholds in the
villages of Lausa, Smonica and Jablanica on Monday. The attacks
come days after Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic promised to
stop his attack on the KLA.
	   Ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs 9-to-1 in Kosovo province, part
of the Serb republic that dominates Yugoslavia.
	   Janowski compared the situation in Kosovo to what happened in
1992 in Bosnia, when Serb forces embarked on a policy of trying to
empty villages of their non-Serb populations.
	   ``If this is an attempt to drive Kosovo Albanians out of Kosovo
... that would be total lunacy,'' Janowski said.
	   U.S. envoy Christopher Hill was headed Tuesday to the
Serb-overrun towns of Orahovac and Malisevo to assess the
conditions for a possible return of refugees.
	   ``If we don't start getting people back to their homes in the
next week or two, we will really have a humanitarian nightmare on
our hands,'' he told reporters.
	   ``I want to see what's out there and in fact I'm not really sure
what I'm going to see.''
	   Moderate Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova, who met with Hill on
Monday, blamed the Serbs for exacerbating the problem in Kosovo.
	   ``Serb forces kill civilians, burn and destroy settlements and
entire villages and carry out ethnic cleansing,'' Rugova said,
according to the Kosovo Information Center. He also demanded
``energetic intervention by the United States and its allies.''
	   In Washington, the U.S. government announced Monday that NATO
had approved a plan to use firepower against Serb forces in Kosovo,
warning that another offensive could trigger a ``humanitarian
catastrophe.''
	   Officials at NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, said that a
number of options had been underway for some time, but there was no
military action planned at this stage.
	   It has never been clear what would trigger a NATO attack. Nor
was it clear whether the administration was trying mostly to
unnerve Milosevic by raising the threat again publicly.
	   NATO bombardment helped drive Milosevic into negotiations to end
an ethnic war in Bosnia-Herzegovina in 1995.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
