<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinian, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Palestinians reject Israeli withdrawal proposal; talks uncertain
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Arafat, Netanyahu quotes &QL; 
 &UR; By SAMAR ASSAD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ The Palestinians rejected an Israeli proposal
to make part of a West Bank withdrawal a restricted ``nature
reserve'' with no Palestinian police presence, leaving it unclear
Tuesday whether the sputtering peace talks would go on.
	   Palestinian Authority President Yasser Arafat said Israeli
negotiators brought nothing new to a Monday night meeting, and that
the Palestinians were ``studying'' whether to continue the talks.
	   Speaking to reporters in the West Bank town of Ramallah, Arafat
said the Israeli proposal was ``very far'' from the existing
Israel-Palestinian agreements or from an American initiative for an
Israeli withdrawal from 13 percent of the West Bank.
	   Arafat's spokesman, Nabil Abourdeneh, called Monday's meeting
``a waste of time.''
	   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, however, told reporters in
Jerusalem that the Israelis had presented ``substantive'' proposals
to the Palestinians that he believed could bring the talks to a
conclusion. ``But they have different calculations on their side,''
he said.
	   Netanyahu and other Israeli officials did not elaborate on the
proposals.
	   Chief Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat and Israeli envoy
Yitzhak Molcho met for several hours Monday night in Jerusalem, but
did not speak to reporters afterward. Erekat briefed Arafat on the
talks late Monday night.
	   After months of stalemate during which the United States failed
to win Israeli backing for a 13 percent withdrawal, Israel and the
Palestinians returned to the negotiating table two weeks ago.
	   Palestinian negotiator Hassan Asfour told The Associated Press
that Israel had proposed that 3 of the 13 percent be land in the
Judean Desert classified as a ``nature reserve,'' over which Israel
would retain overall security control.
	   ``This is rejected by the Palestinians,'' Asfour said. ``Our
position is clear: We were presented with an American proposal in
March, and that is what we stand by.''
	   Asfour said such Israeli proposals would ``lead to the end of
talks ... If the Israeli proposals stay along this line, then there
is no need for further meetings.''
	   A Palestinian official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the Israelis had offered to give the Palestinians civil authorities
in the nature reserve areas _ which he said was meaningless because
no one lived in the desert areas.
	   The Palestinians would not, however, be allowed to have either a
security presence or to build in the area, another official said,
also speaking on condition of anonymity.
	   In Washington, U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin said
Monday that the administration was still hopeful the sides would
continue talks.
	   ``We think they should deal with each other with respect and
confidentiality and a greater sense of urgency, and meet
intensively, so that they can make sure they've done everything
they can to try to reach an agreement. And they also, as we've said
before, need to make tough decisions. But we want specific
proposals on the table that can be dealt with,'' Rubin said.
	   hla
</TEXT>
