<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Teen Addicts </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Amphetamine use rising among Thai teens
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo BK101 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Arrests for illegal drug use in
Thailand have been rising steadily over the past five years, and
law enforcement officials say teen-agers becoming addicted to
amphetamines account for the growing numbers.
	   Drug arrests in Thailand in 1997 totaled 157,400, compared with
113,500 in 1993, according to statistics released Tuesday by the
Office of the Narcotics Control Board, a government agency.
	   Of the 1997 arrests, nearly half were for amphetamines. Although
the statistics did not break down the arrests by age groups, ONCB
officials said amphetamine abuse had spread beyond truckers and
laborers to teen-agers.
	   ``Laborers use it for endurance, while teens take it for a
kick,'' said an ONCB official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
	   ``The most scary thing is that most of these teens have become
part of drug rings and they will drug their school peers and
convince them to join,'' the officer said.
	   A recent study by the Ministry of Education concluded there are
about 50,000 high school students addicted to amphetamines.
	   Amphetamines, called ``ya ba'' or ``madness medicine,'' are the
most popular drug in Thailand. The Thai government has made the
penalties for dealing in amphetamines almost as severe as those for
dealing in heroin.
	   Increasingly, the drug is being manufactured in neighboring
Myanmar, also known as Burma, and smuggled into Thailand.
	   The ONCB official urged schools to try counseling students
discovered to be using amphetamines. Usually, students are
suspended or expelled.
	   The Education Ministry has ordered schools to ask parents to
send their drug-addicted children for treatment. The ministry is
setting up a special committee to deal with drug problems in the
schools.
	   The ONCB's National Narcotics Control Plan for 1997-2000 calls
for more treatment and prevention programs at the community level
to go along with stronger law enforcement.
	   Some educators have suggested random urine tests in schools, but
some civil rights activists oppose them on the grounds that they
would violate students' constitutional rights.	   
</TEXT>
