<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Track-Johnson-Drugs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ben Johnson: I'm not the only bad guy
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Ben Johnson, the Canadian sprinter who was
stripped of his Olympic gold medal in 1988 after testing positive
for drugs, says the recent doping scandals in the Tour de France
and other sports prove he was never ``the only bad guy.''
	   Johnson, who was banned for life after a second positive test in
1993, says athletes in all sports use performance-enhancing drugs
and that there has never been a level playing field.
	   Johnson said the widespread use of drugs in cycling, which was
exposed during the Tour de France, and the recent positive tests of
American sprinter Dennis Mitchell and Olympic shot-put champion
Randy Barnes support his claim.
	   ``The whole world was pointing at me saying I was the big, bad
guy _ the only guy taking substances,'' Johnson was quoted as
saying in an interview in Tuesday's Daily Mail. ``Now they can't
hide from the truth.
	   ``Now the world has seen that no sport is fair, that there is no
level playing field _ that cyclists are at it, Dennis Mitchell and
Randy Barnes, the East Germans, the Chinese, everybody is at it.
	   ``So Ben Johnson is not the only one who was doing it. And I was
never alone. In 1988 I was never alone. The majority at Seoul were
on some substance.''
	   Johnson, 36, claims he was a scapegoat.
	   The times he clocked _ 9.79 seconds for the 100 meters at the
Seoul Olympics and the 9.83 seconds at the 1987 world championships
_ were annulled. The current world record of 9.84 was set by
Canada's Donovan Bailey in 1996.
	   Johnson said he didn't think he could run under 10 seconds
without drugs.
	   ``I would say 10 seconds flat,'' he said, referring to his
fastest possible time without the aid of drugs. ``If you've never
used anything, just come to it natural, that's about my limit.''
	   At the inquiry into Johnson's disqualification from the Seoul
Olympics, Johnson's coach Charlie Francis estimated drugs gave the
sprinter a two-meter boost in the Olympic final.
	   ``I won by that much. So I would have won anyway,'' Johnson
said.
	   Johnson admitted taking drugs after the 1988 scandal but claims
he did so at the instigation of his coach and doctor.
	   He is still appealing his life ban and will appear in a Canadian
court just days before the 10th anniversary of his Olympic
disqualification on Sept. 25.
	   Johnson said he was the victim of a conspiracy to show the sport
was serious about cleaning itself up.
	   ``Somebody was out to get Ben Johnson and succeeded. But the
truth will be revealed very soon,'' he said. ``They had to get rid
of somebody, show they were doing something so they picked me. Then
they say the rest were clean. You saw how true that was last week.
Ben Johnson wasn't the only bad guy. Never was.''
	   Johnson told the Daily Mail he reserved his greatest contempt
for the Americans who were quicker to condemn him than they were to
compete against him.
	   ``So do I think Mitchell and Barnes are the only ones? What do
you think? ''
	   Mitchell was four places behind Johnson in the final at Seoul
but was upgraded to fourth when Johnson was disqualified and his
record thrown out.
	   Mitchell, who won the bronze medal in the 100 at the 1996
Atlanta Games, tested positive for high levels of testosterone
earlier this year and has been suspended by the International
Amateur Atletic Federation pending a hearing.
	   Barnes, the world record-holder in the shot, tested positive for
a testerone-related substance and faces the prospect of a life ban
because it was his second offense.
	   (jp)
</TEXT>
