<HEADLINE>
Thai coffee production expected to drop by 50 percent this year
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ The drought induced by the El Nino
weather phenomenon is likely to halve Thailand's coffee crop for
the 1998-99 season and sharply reduce coffee exports this year,
local newspapers reported Tuesday.
	   Coffee production for the coming crop year is expected to drop
by 40-50 percent from last year's 80,000 tons to 40,000-50,000
tons, the newspaper Krungthep Turakij (Bangkok Business) quoted
Deputy Commerce Minister Paitoon Kaewthong as saying.
	   Exports are expected to total about 10,000 metric tons, compared
to 50,000 tons last year, according to an official at the
Department of Internal Trade under the Commerce Ministry.
	   The official, who asked not to be named, added that local
consumption is around 30,000 tons a year.	   
