<SLUG> BC-Britain-Earns-Oil </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
British Petroleum profits hit by low oil prices
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ British Petroleum PLC said Tuesday its quarterly
profits fell 20 percent to 695 million pounds (dlrs 1.16 billion)
as it suffered the effects of a severely depressed oil market.
	   BP said its pre-tax profits for the three months ending June 30
compared with earnings of 874 million pounds in the same period a
year earlier.
	   Revenues plunged 30 percent to 6.24 billion pounds (dlrs 10.42
billion), from 8.96 billion pounds, BP said.
	   BP's chief executive, John Browne, called the results
``satisfactory,'' under the circumstances. Oil prices had fallen at
one point to their lowest level in more than a decade as OPEC
produced too much while demand in Asia was weakened by its serious
economic crisis.
	   BP said it made an average of dlrs 12.60 per barrel for its
crude oil in the quarter just ended, down sharply from dlrs 18.30
in the same quarter of 1997.
	   BP warned that the global market may stay glutted with oil for
some time, although it predicted that if OPEC sticks with recent
pledges to slash output, prices could recover modestly later in the
year.
	   While BP mentioned OPEC production as a critical factor that has
weakened the market, BP, too, is pumping more oil.
	   The company said its production was up by 8 percent from last
year, with the higher volume helping to shield it against the lower
prices.
	   BP said that for the first six months of the year, its pre-tax
profits came to 1.17 billion pounds (dlrs 1.96 billion), down from
1.83 billion pounds a year earlier.
	   Half-year revenues came to 13.03 billion pounds (dlrs 21.77
billion), compared with 19.24 billion pounds a year earlier.
	   (db-kg)
</TEXT>
