<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Netherlands-Earns-KLM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dutch carrier posts 12 percent profit jump for first quarter
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) _ KLM Royal Dutch Airlines said
Tuesday its net profit for the first quarter of 1998 rose 12
percent to 212 million guilders (dlrs 106 million) but was dented
by Asia's economic crisis.
	   The results for the three months ended June 30 were supported by
a one-off gain, lower costs and improved yields but hurt by
``trading conditions in the Asia-Pacific region,'' the airline
said. It didn't elaborate.
	   KLM said the net profit figure didn't include subsidiary
Martinair, and that operating profit would have risen 15 percent to
285 million guilders (dlrs 142.5 million) if it had.
	   Overall operating income rose 5.2 percent to 262 million
guilders (dlrs 131 million), at the low end of analysts'
expectations.
	   The net profit includes a gain of 47 million guilders (dlrs 23.5
million) from KLM's sale of its 26 percent stake in Dutch
transportation company Frans Maas NV.
	   That gain was largely offset by the loss of earnings from U.S.
partner Northwest Airlines, in which KLM has sold its financial
stake. In the first quarter of 1997, Northwest had boosted KLM's
net profit by 56 million guilders (dlrs 28 million).
	   Looking ahead, KLM said it expects an improvement in operating
income in the fiscal year ending March 1999.
	   The Amsterdam-based airline said its forecast assumes stable
global economics and that the labor situation doesn't deteriorate
at Northwest, which remains a KLM partner. Northwest pilots are
threatening to strike at the end of the month in a contract
dispute.
	   KLM on Tuesday didn't reiterate a recent forecast by Chairman
Leo van Wijk that net earnings are expected to get a double-digit
boost this year.
	   (dj/bk)
</TEXT>
