<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Storm </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tropical storm Otto batters Taiwan, kills one
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Tropical storm Otto battered Taiwan
Tuesday, triggering landslides that killed one person.
	   Police said a man died in a landslide in southern Chiayi, where
the storm dumped 300 millimeters (12 inches) of rain in a 12-hour
period. Chiayi is 300 kilometers (180 miles) south of Taipei.
	   Weathermen warned of further floods and cave-ins in the area,
where five people were killed last month by a 6.2 magnitude
earthquake.
	   In nearby Nantou, the storm flooded rivers and landslides
blocked road traffic. Hundreds of tourists and villagers were
stranded in the mountainous area, police said.
	   At 6 p.m. (1000 GMT), Otto, packing winds of 90 kilometers per
hour (54 mph), was crossing the Taiwan Strait toward the Chinese
mainland, the Central Weather Bureau said.
	   The storm uprooted trees and destroyed fruit and other crops
islandwide, causing damage estimated at 13 million Taiwan dollars
(U.S. dlrs 370,000), the Agriculture Council said.
	   More than 20,000 households suffered a blackout on the offshore
Green and Orchid Islands. Domestic air flights and train services
were suspended, officials said.
	   The storm was expected to hit the southern Chinese coast early
Wednesday.	   
</TEXT>
