w1901 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Poland-FarmersProtest 2ndLd-Writethru   08-04 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Farmers Protest, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government hopes import reforms will halt major farmers' protest
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with government announcement, reaction;
adds details &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo planned &QL; 
 &UR; By MONIKA SCISLOWSKA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Protesting farmers blockaded roads and
government offices in several Polish towns Tuesday in a nationwide
demonstration against grain imports and low prices.
	   The government called the protest, the largest this year by
farmers, a surprise and said it would proceed with previously
announced plans to purchase Polish grain and put a quota on
imports.
	   ``This is more a political activity than a defense of the
farmers,'' Deputy Prime Minister Janusz Tomaszewski told a news
conference.
	   The protests were mostly peaceful, with one including music from
a folk group, but they showed the increasing desire by farmers to
display their political muscle as Poland considers widespread
reforms needed to join the European Union.
	   Some 500 farmers with tractors and heavy farming equipment
blockaded 20 roads and also some town halls across the nation,
according to national police spokesman Pawel Biedziak.
	   In Goleniow, 520 kilometers (320 miles) northwest of Warsaw,
four tractors and a trailer filled with grain jammed the access
road to the city hall, an office worker in the building said by
telephone.
	   According to Mariusz Tarnozek, the worker, a banner on the
trailer said: ``We have grain, who will buy it?''
	   On the main road south from Warsaw, farmers tossed boxes of
potatoes and sacks of grain to halt vehicles and even stood in the
street themselves. Some minor pushing and punching between irate
drivers and protesters occurred.
	   Other places were peaceful, such as Biala Podlaska, 120
kilometers (75 miles) east of Warsaw, where a folk band played as
farmers blockaded the city hall.
	   Four farmers' unions that represent well over half of the
nation's 4 million farmers organized the demonstrations to protest
grain imports and demand government purchases of their grain.
	   Tomaszewski called the protests a ``great surprise to the
government,'' which he said would carry out previous decisions to
protect farmers. On Thursday, he said, the government would
introduce import quotas on grain and start purchasing Polish grain.
	   Agriculture Minister Jacek Janiszewski, sitting next to
Tomaszewski, said the government also would offer state subsidies
to companies buying Polish grain beginning Aug. 15.
	   He said the government planned to buy 1.5 million tons of grain
this year, with prices equal to dlrs 150 per ton of wheat and dlrs
105 per ton of rye. According to the Agriculture Ministry, farmers
currently get about dlrs 147 per ton for wheat and dlrs 88 per ton
for rye.
	   Janiszewski said he hoped the new prices and subsidies would
halt grain imports. If not, he said, the government might consider
increasing import taxes or banning imports, as demanded by farmers,
as a last resort.
	   Polish agriculture remains hobbled by small, poorly equipped
farms unable to compete with larger, more modern farms in Western
Europe. Calls for reforms to consolidate farms and make them more
efficient in preparation for Poland's bid to join the European
Union have been resisted by farmers, who fear losing control of
their land and having to work for others.
	   Tuesday's protest was the largest of a series held by farmers
this year, including one Monday in which 1,200 tons of grain
brought by train from Slovakia and Hungary was spilled across the
rails at a border crossing.
	   (ms-tsc)
</TEXT>
