<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Cartoonist </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkish cartoonist begins serving sentence for insulting republic
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) _ A cartoonist for a pro-Kurdish daily has
begun serving a sentence of three years and four months in prison
for insulting the Turkish republic, his paper reported Tuesday.
	   A warrant was issued for Dogan Guzel, of the daily Ozgur Gundem,
following his recent conviction for calling the state ``villain''
though his cartoon character, Kirik, in four separate strips. He
was picked up Friday night.
	   The Paris-based international journalists organization Reporters
Sans Frontieres called for Guzel's release, saying the cartoonist
was exercising his right to express his opinions.
	   Around 30 Turkish journalists are serving prison terms for their
writings, according to another press organization, the New
York-based Committee to Protect Journalists.
	   (sf)
