<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Fighting, 1st Ld-Writethru,0576 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taliban head off counterattack, even closer to Mazar-e-Sharif
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Taliban claiming to have captured Saripul. Edits
throughout to conform. &QL; 
 &UR; By ZAHEERUDDIN ABDULLAH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) _ The Taliban religious army launched a
preemptive strike Tuesday, saying they captured a town from
Afghanistan's opposition and headed off an attack that could have
slowed their advance on a key northern city.
	   Taliban spokesman Abdul Hay Muttayn said his fighters took the
town of Saripul, about 100 kilometers (60 miles) southwest of the
key city Mazar-e-Sharif, after a one-hour battle. Muttayn said his
opponents, who had retreated to Saripul after losing their
stronghold of Shebergan on Sunday, had been regrouping for a
counterattack.
	   Muttayn had no details on causalities or captives, and there was
no independent confirmation of his report.
	   If the claim were true, it would be one more in a series of
victories that has bolstered the Taliban, who already controls most
of Afghanistan. The extremist Islamic army appears poised to take
the rest of the country.
	   The Red Cross evacuated the last eight foreign aid workers
Tuesday from the northern Afghanistan city of Mazar-e-Sharif,
fearing a repeat of the street fighting and looting that erupted
last year when the Taliban religious militia briefly held the city,
one of their opposition's few remaining strongholds.
	   Hundreds of residents were reportedly fleeing the city.
	   Taliban troops engaged in minor skirmishes Tuesday as they
advanced to 20 kilometers (12 miles) west of Mazar-e-Sharif,
according to Taliban spokesman Muttayn. He said the religious
militia was now pausing to build bunkers and shore up defenses. It
was unclear when the religious militia would attempt to capture
Mazar-e-Sharif.
	   An opposition source in Mazar-e-Sharif, who refused to be named,
confirmed Taliban fighters were 20 kilometers (12 miles) to the
west. The source, speaking by satellite phone, said residents in
the region were revolting against warlord Rashid Dostum, a leader
in the fractious opposition coalition, allowing the Taliban to
advance.
	   Dostum's whereabouts were unknown Tuesday.
	   Taliban radio reported late Monday that Taliban fighters were
also east of Mazar-e-Sharif _ just 40 kilometers (25 miles) away,
within rocket range of the airport.
	   Red Cross spokesman Michel Schaffner said Mazar-e-Sharif was
calm Tuesday and the airport, which was closed the day before, was
open, enabling a Red Cross plane to land and pick up 11 aid workers
from organizations including Doctors Without Borders, Pharmacists
Without Borders and Save the Children. A Pharmacists Without
Borders spokesman said the 11 included three Afghans.
	   The aid workers were brought to the Pakistani border town of
Peshawar, where Schaffner spoke by telephone.
	   Most international organizations pulled their workers out of
Mazar-e-Sharif after the chaos there last year.
	   Taliban leaders have imposed a strict version of Islamic law in
territory they control. Since capturing the Afghan capital, Kabul,
in 1996, Taliban officials have barred girls from school and
confined most women to their homes.
	   The anti-Taliban alliance is made up mostly of Afghanistan's
religious and ethnic minorities. The factions occasionally turn on
each other, weakening their ability to fight the Taliban.
</TEXT>
