<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-East Europe-Heat Wave </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Heat wave sweeps Eastern Europe
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Incorporates BC-Hungary-Heat Wave, BC-Ukraine-Heat Wave &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos Planned &QL; 
 &UR; By MIHAELA ARMASELU &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) _ Eastern Europe is sizzling from a
three-week-old heat wave that has reportedly claimed at least 20
lives in Romania, buckled streetcar tracks in Hungary and smashed
temperature records across the region.
	   Temperatures soared past the 40-degree Celsius mark (104
Fahrenheit) again Tuesday in the southern Balkans region, suffering
through its worst heat wave in half a century.
	   How hot is it?
	   So hot that journalists found Serb forces in Yugoslavia's
troubled Kosovo province heating their baked beans by setting the
cans on the fiery metal surface of armored personnel carriers.
	   In Bucharest, where the mercury has hit at least 36 degrees (97
F) every day since the first half of July, some 2,500 people have
called the capital's emergency services in the past four days and
15 ambulances are on heat patrol.
	   Hospitals in the city of 3 million said they are crowded with
people who suffered strokes, heart attacks, sunstroke or have
fainted in the scorching heat.
	   Residents are plunging into the city's fountains, the dirty
Dambovita River and lakes to keep cool.
	   Bucharest's mayor, Viorel Lis, is sending the city hall staff
home at lunch time every day to avoid any heat-related accidents,
and has urged other employers to do the same.
	   Wheat and corn and sunflowers around the capital have been burnt
by the heat.
	   In Sarajevo, one-time host of the Winter Olympics, the Bosnian
Federation health ministry was recommending people stay indoors
from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. because of the high temperatures.
	   In Belgrade, Yugoslavia, several dozen people fainted on the hot
sidewalks Monday on the hottest Aug. 3 in 111 years _ 39 Celsius
(102 Fahrenheit) in the shade.
	   In poverty-stricken Albania, where it was 42 (108) in the
capital Tirana on Tuesday, anxious mothers were taking their babies
to hospitals in high numbers for fear of health problems.
	   Croatia's renowned beaches weren't offering much relief from the
record-breaking heat _ the Adriatic Sea was a warm 26 to 28 degrees
Celsius (79 to 82 Fahrenheit).
	   In the Hungarian capital Budapest, public pools have standing
room only and a streetcar line suspended operations Monday when the
tracks along one stretch buckled.
	   A 77-year-old heat record for Aug. 3 was broken Monday when the
official temperature reached 36.7 degrees Celsius (98 Fahrenheit).
It was even hotter in downtown Budapest _ 40 (104 F) or higher.
	   ``We just can't work _ we have three fans going and it is still
35 (95 F) degrees in the office,'' said Melinda Kis, a secretary at
a travel agency.
	   Ukraine, which usually has mild summer weather, also was
affected, with record highs of 40 Celsius (104 Fahrenheit) in the
southern cities of Mykolayiv and Kherson.
	   A break in the weather is coming _ but not for long. Attila
Nadrai, head of Hungary's National Meteorological Service, said a
cool front is expected by Wednesday, but the forecast for the
region next week calls for more heat.
	   (ma/am/buros/dc)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-East Europe-Heat Wave; CT:i; 
