<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Middle East Business Briefs </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Iran, Bahrain, Lebanon, Kuwait and Jordan &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ The Jordanian government and banks are to
blame for the profound recession in the local construction
industry, the president of the Jordanian Engineers Association said
Tuesday.
	   Construction activity has declined for a third consecutive year
and the total area of sites around the country is 16 percent below
the figure in the first half of 1997, Hosni Abou Ghida told The
Associated Press.
	   ``The volume and size of construction projects have dropped
sharply, and the number of engineering offices has been negatively
affected, because the government and banks do not support Jordanian
construction companies,'' Abou Ghida said.
	   He revealed that 60 percent of the construction under way was
being carried out by non-Jordanian companies with the backing of
foreign banks and the government.
	   Abou Ghida declined to speak about why investors preferred
foreign construction companies. However, the government is
encouraging foreign investment and it is known that foreign
investors tend to engage construction companies with whom they are
already familiar.
	   Abou Ghida said that 32 new engineering firms had registered
their offices with the association this year, but 48 offices had
closed, resulting in a decline of 16 registered firms.
	   As for engineers, he said 1,233 were registered as out of work
while 933 had jobs.
	   He appealed to the government and banks to support local firms.
	   ____
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ Iran and five Asian states plan to build a
multi-purpose satellite, the official Islamic Republic News Agency
reported Tuesday.
	   China, Pakistan, Mongolia, Thailand and South Korea will
cooperate with Iran to manufacture the satellite, which will be
used for telecommunications and monitoring, the agency quoted an
Iranian Deputy Communications Minister as saying.
	   The satellite will cost dlrs 20 million, the deputy minister
said. Construction will begin soon and the satellite should be
launched by 2001.
	   ____
	   KUWAIT (AP) - Some 100 local and foreign companies have applied
to rent space in Kuwait's first free-trade zone, suggesting the
project will be successful, the Al-Qabas newspaper said Tuesday.
	   The zone's manager, Juhail al-Juhail, is very pleased with the
high demand for a project whose first phase will open in October,
the newspaper reported.
	   Al-Juhail said the zone at Shuwaik Port, just west of Kuwait
City, will offer facilities for storage, light industry and
offices.
	   The government has contracted a private firm, The National Real
Estate Co., to build and manage the zone for 20 years. It is hoping
the zone will attract foreign capital and boost the private sector.
	   Kuwait wants to develop the private sector of its economy, which
depends heavily on oil and government spending.
	   ____
	   MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) _ The total assets of Bahrain-based
offshore banking units fell 1 percent to dlrs 71.4 billion in the
first quarter of this year, the island's Central Bank reported
Tuesday.
	   However, total commercial bank assets increased 2.6 percent in
the first quarter to dlrs 11.29 billion, the Bahrain Monetary
Agency said.
	   BMA, as the central bank is known, did not explain the
movements.
	   Bahrain is the offshore banking center of the Middle East. There
are about 47 offshore banking units and 19 commercial banks
operating from the tiny Gulf state.
	   ____
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Lebanon might become the regional center
for growing the potatoes used by the McDonald's fast-food chain,
Agriculture Minister Shawki Fakhoury said in remarks published
Tuesday.
	   The minister said such a role depends on a plan to start potato
plantations in eastern Lebanon's Bekaa Valley with 300 kilograms of
seeds imported from the United States, The Daily Star quoted
Fakhoury as saying.
	   The sowing of the seeds will begin in October, coinciding with
the opening of McDonald's first Lebanese branch in Beirut, the
minister said.
	   To open the branch, the government has allowed McDonald's to
import some 400 tons of potatoes.
	   McDonald's is scheduled to open a second branch in Beirut by the
end of the year.
	   The minister did not say where Lebanon might sell its American
species of potatoes, but McDonald's has branches in Egypt and
Jordan.
	   McDonald's is the latest of several fast-food chains to open in
Lebanon since the end of the 1975-90 civil war.
	   ____
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Foreign workers in Lebanon have been
ordered to buy insurance policies before they apply for work
permits, newspapers reported Tuesday.
	   Labor Minister Assad Hardan said the insurance policies must
cover health care, accident compensation, deportation fees and
repatriation of the body in case of a worker's death, An-Nahar and
other newspapers reported.
	   The minister said workers would have to buy policies offering at
least dlrs 2,500 for a minor or permanent physical handicap caused
by an accident. For more serious accidents and illnesses, the cover
should offer the worker at least dlrs 2,500 per accident and up to
dlrs 5,000 per year.
	   There are more than one million foreign workers, mainly Syrians,
in Lebanon, which has an estimated population of 3.2 million.
 &UR; am-jah-de-hd-jbm
</TEXT>
