w1918 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-SexAbstinenceRa     08-04 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> Group warns of American culture of sex at rally in Tokyo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AP Photos
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JOJI SAKURAI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ With thumping rap, folk singalongs and multilingual
banners, the U.S.-based Pure Love Alliance brought its message to
Japan Tuesday in a rally urging sexual abstinence and warning
against America's culture of sex.
	   About 500 advocates of sexual purity from the United States,
Japan, South Korea and Europe gathered in pouring rain in a park
near the Tokyo's Harajuku district, a favorite of young people, to
promote chastity and fidelity within marriage.
	   ``American culture is infiltrating the world, promoting the
spread of things like prostitution and pornography,'' said
24-year-old Tricy Sincavage, who flew in from the United States to
join the tour. ``Our aim is to help clean things up.''
	   The alliance, made up of students celebrating their virginity
and members of church groups from around the world, plans to hold
four more rallies and marches around Japan, then move on to South
Korea to complete its 1998 tour.
	   The growing number of Japanese schoolgirls who are turning to
prostitution and the country's booming sex industry, which includes
telephone dating clubs that are often fronts for prostitution, were
part of the reason the group came to Japan, organizers say.
	   ``More and more families are breaking up and Japan needs to
return to purity,'' said 42-year-old Pure Love member Masakazu
Irie. ``Japan must realize the mistakes of the sexual revolution.''
	   The alliance gained attention last year when it led 500 people
claiming to be virgins on a 25-city tour in the United States,
saying it wanted to end what it calls the stigma of virginity.
	   Many of the group's members are followers of the Unification
Church of the Rev. Sun Myung Moon.
	   Not everyone was convinced that the throng of demonstrators
wearing pink visors and ``pure love'' T-shirts had a message Japan
wanted to hear.
	   ``I don't know what they're talking about,'' said 40-year-old
Eichi Sasaki, who sells fried noodles from a booth in the park.
``Japan said no to sex before marriage at the turn of the century,
but not any more.''	   
