<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Tobacco </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Southern Chinese boom town to ban tobacco ads
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ The capital of booming southern China's Guangdong
province will ban all cigarette ads and product promotions by Aug.
25, the official China Daily reported Tuesday.
	   Billboards, bar signs, umbrellas, balloons and other giveaways
bearing cigarette brand names will be banned in Guangzhou city,
complementing a nationwide ban on print and broadcast cigarette
advertising, the paper said.
	   ``The municipal government expects the city to become a modern
metropolis without cigarettes,'' the paper quoted an unidentified
city official as saying.
	   But the Municipal Bureau of Industry and Commerce challenged the
ban and said ads and promotions remain legal for the time being,
the paper said.
	   China has some 320 million smokers, and its smoking rate of 60
percent for men is among the highest in the world.
	   The government relies on cigarette taxes and profits for about
10 percent of its revenues, but says smoking-related fires and
health care cost more than tobacco brings in. In recent years,
smoking has been prohibited in planes, trains, theaters,
restaurants and public buildings.	   
</TEXT>
