<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Political Change </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Powerful Yorubas vote to support Nigeria's democracy plan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Delegates attending a conference of
leading ethnic Yorubas voted to support the ruling military's
proposed plan to hand power back to civilian leaders, a spokesman
said Tuesday.
	   The meeting, described as the largest gathering of Yoruba
officials in three decades, took place at the plush Premier hotel
in the southwestern city of Ibadan on Monday.
	   Hundreds of politicians, academics and traditional leaders
attended the conference which was convened to discuss whether
Yorubas would endorse the new military junta's transition process.
	   ``All Yorubas will participate fully in the ensuing political
process that will lead to the termination of military rule,'' said
Abraham Adesanya, the group's spokesman.
	   The question of whether the Yorubas would boycott the new
junta's transition process has been looming ever since the death in
detention of Nigeria's most famous political prisoner Moshood
Abiola.
	   Yorubas activists have led opposition to military rule in
Nigeria.
	   Abiola, a Yoruba, was jailed by Abubakar's predecessor Gen. Sani
Abacha after declaring himself president in 1994. Abiola was the
presumed winner of 1993 presidential elections that Abacha
annulled.
	   The group's decision is a considerable boost for Abubakar, who
has received cautious praise for his policies since taking control
of the country.
	   Abubakar has promised to release all political prisoners and to
usher in civilian rule next year after elections in which all
Nigerians would be free to participate.
	   (fa-ad/ids)
</TEXT>
