w1927 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Iraq 6thLd-Writethru   08-04 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq, 6th Ld-Writethru,0763 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Butler blames Iraq for collapse of disarmament talks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: COMBINES urgent series, CHANGES overline, RAISES possible
consequences, INSERTS comment from British foreign secretary,
TRIMS. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos staffing &QL; 
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ The chief U.N. weapons inspector left
Baghdad on Tuesday after the collapse of talks on dismantling
Iraq's weapons of mass destruction collapsed.
	   Richard Butler, head of the U.N. Special Commission, told
reporters on arrival in nearby Bahrain that the impasse stemmed
from a demand by Iraq's chief negotiator, Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz, that the country be given a clean bill of health on its
weaponry.
	   ``Tariq Aziz demanded that I tell the Security Council that Iraq
is clean now,'' Butler told The Associated Press. ``I told him that
I cannot fulfill your demand because I don't have the evidence.''
	   Butler continued: ``After I said that to him, Aziz replied,
`Then we can't talk any further.'''
	   They were Butler's first comments on why the talks, which lasted
six hours on Monday, had failed.
	   Iraq has stepped up the pressure on the United Nations to lift
trade sanctions imposed after Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait. The
U.N. sanctions ban travel to and from Iraq and limit the sale of
oil, Iraq's economic mainstay.
	   But the security Council has said that the sanctions will not be
lifted until U.N. inspectors certify that Iraq has eliminated its
weapons of mass destruction.
	   Western reporters were barred from covering Butler's departure
from the Habbaniya air base outside Baghdad. But the official Iraqi
News Agency quoted him as saying that the U.N. Security Council
would have to decide how to deal with the situation.
	   ``It is imperative not to overdramatize the situation,'' INA
quoted Butler as saying. ``I will refrain from using the word
crisis.''
	   He added: ``I am sure the council will strive to find a solution
and determine what the next step should be.''
	   Butler said in Bahrain that he would report Thursday to the
Security Council.
	   It was unclear if the latest impasse would trigger another
military crisis. Earlier this year, the United States and Britain
sent warships to the Gulf after Iraq refused to open presidential
sites to U.N. inspectors.
	   That crisis was defused by an agreement brokered in February by
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
	   Last month, Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein gave a nationally
televised speech saying that the sanctions must be lifted this year
_ the first time he had set a deadline.
	   Government officials said that Saddam was expected to convene
his Revolutionary Command Council later Tuesday to assess the
situation.
	   Within hours of Butler's departure, representatives of Iraqi
trade unions demonstrated outside the U.N. offices in Baghdad. A
petition to Annan pledged ``the protection of people's interests
... by all means in the face of the illegal American-British
plots.''
	   In London, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said in a
statement that ``the Iraqi government's antics'' were thwarting the
U.N. inspectors' work.
	   ``We would like to see the sanctions lifted as soon as
possible,'' it added. ``But progress depends entirely on the
Iraqis.''
	   Iraq insists it has eliminated its proscribed weapons, but
Butler has said he still has reservations about Iraq's chemical and
biological weapons programs and long-range missiles.
	   On Monday, Aziz accused Butler of being an American pawn for
trying to prolong the sanctions.
	   Aziz told reporters that Butler was ignoring the country's
progress in eliminating its weaponry and, instead, focusing on
``minor issues which make no sense from the angle of disarmament.''
	   ``Since this is the wish of the American administration to
perpetuate the situation, to prolong the current situation, to keep
the sanctions on the people of Iraq. ... as long as this is the
American wish, you (Butler) are serving the American policy,'' he
said.
	   This theme was echoed Tuesday by Al-Qaddisiya, the daily of
Iraq's armed forces.
	   ``Eight years of unfair sanctions are enough.'' the paper said.
``Butler and his men have to prove that they are U.N.
professionals, not obedient tools of America. ... Otherwise, Iraq's
patient people will continue a `jihad' (holy war) and will not
allow more years of sanctions. Enough is enough.''
	   The paper did not suggest what action the country planned,
saying only that ``the peoples strategy is jihad until the
sanctions are lifted.''
</TEXT>
