r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Malaysia-Banks     08-04 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Banks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malaysia announces fund to strengthen banks
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Malaysia's central bank on Tuesday
announced mechanisms to strengthen the country's ailing banks in
hopes that increased lending would spur economic growth.
	   Bank Negara said a special agency with initial funds of 1.5
billion ringgit (dlrs 375 million) would act as a strategic
investor in selected banks and encourage them to merge.
	   Bank Negara stressed that the fund was created as a pre-emptive
measure ``to recapitalize the domestic banking institutions to
healthy levels to enable them to increase their resilience and
enhance their ability to generate new lending.''
	   The agency, known as The Special Purpose Vehicle, will be run by
the central bank's assistant governor, Mohamad Daud Haji Dol Moin.
	   Malaysia recently adopted a strategy of strengthening its
debt-ridden banks so they could begin to lend money again to
companies reeling from the effects of Asia's economic turmoil.
	   This is part of a larger plan introduced last month to shore up
the economy by promoting spending and reviving many of the
expensive projects that were shelved last year at the onset of the
Asian currency and stock market crisis.
	   Part of the new plan, to raise money by selling bonds overseas,
received a setback recently when Moody's and Standard and Poor's
downgraded Malaysia's ratings.
	   On Tuesday, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad criticized the
downgrade as a scheme to ``scuttle our bonds.''
	   ``The moment they hear that we are trying to recapitalize our
banks, they drop our credit ratings,'' Mahathir said at a public
meeting in the southern city of Johor Baru.
	   ``They do this to prevent us from helping our banks to
recover,'' he said. ``They are trying to destroy our economy.''
	   Mahathir urged Malaysians to keep their money in banks and buy
local goods to boost the economy.
	   ``Put your money in banks and not under your mattresses,'' he
said.
	   He accused the International Monetary Fund of wanting to control
Malaysia's banks and reiterated that Malaysia does not need support
from the international lending agency.
	   ``We can still stand on our own feet. There is enough to eat,''
Mahathir said.
	   Bank Negara said the government would play a minimal role in
financing the banking agency, which would be funded primarily from
bond issues and foreign lenders.
	   Malaysia's once booming economy is slipping into recession, with
forecasts of contraction of up to 2 percent in 1998, a sharp plunge
from 7.8 percent economic growth in 1997. The currency, the
ringgit, has depreciated 40 percent against the U.S. dollar since
last July.	   
</TEXT>
