<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Kurds </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kurdish rebel group accuses rival of killing local leader
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ One of the main Kurdish groups in northern
Iraq on Tuesday accused a Turkish rebel faction of killing one of
its local leaders by booby-trapping his house.
	   Delshad Miran, a spokesman for the Kurdistan Democratic Party,
said KDP leader Khalid Tawfiq and his family were killed in the
explosion on Saturday.
	   He blamed fighters from the Kurdish Workers Party of Turkey.
	   The KDP, which shares control over the enclave with the
Patriotic Union of Kurdistan, has been fighting the PKK. PKK
fighters carry out attacks on Turkey from their bases in northern
Iraq.
	   Miran, reached in London by phone from Cairo, accused the PKK of
planting explosives in Tawfiq's house in Dohuk, some 60 kilometers
(40 miles) south of the Turkish border. Tawfiq headed the KDP
branch in Dohuk.
	   The blast killed Tawfiq, his wife and four children, Miran said.
	   ``This is a heinous and terrorist crime against our party and
our people,'' Miran said.
	   The KDP has been helping the Turkish army in its campaigns to
try to shut down PKK bases in Iraq.
 &UR; sn-eap
