<SLUG> BC-India-Building Collapse, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0380 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Death toll in building collapse climbs to 21
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES 1-3rd grafs with the death toll rising to 21 and
another 21 hospitalized. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos Available
 &UR; By RAMOLA TALWAR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ Firemen and volunteers scrabbled with their
bare hands Tuesday to clear debris from a collapsed building,
discovering more bodies that took the death toll to 21, police
said.
	   In an overnight rescue mission, 22 people were taken out alive
from the rubble of the building, which had been declared
structurally unsound earlier this year. All but one were
hospitalized, mostly with head injuries.
	   Police feared 10 others may still be trapped inside.
	   Cranes worked under floodlights to remove large chunks of
concrete to clear the way for rescuers pulling out victims. Workers
could hear moans and cries for help from under the rubble.
	   Sobbing relatives searched for missing family members among the
injured who were being rushed to nearby hospitals.
	   ``I was buying medicines when I saw part of the building crumble
and I ran for my life. By the time I turned around the whole
structure had toppled. It took less than 10 seconds,'' said Manesh
Rai, who was among the first to be discharged after treatment for
minor injuries.
	   Others like Bina Shah spoke of the nightmare of being buried
alive for more than 10 hours.
	   ``I must have blacked out for the most part. I don't remember
much but loud voices and rumbling sounds, I just remember feeling
very scared,'' Shah said.
	   Earlier, officials feared a higher number of casualties, as it
was unclear how many people were inside the building when it
crumpled with a loud thud Monday night.
	   Three floors of the 20-year-old building's seven stories were
unauthorized by the Bombay city authorities and had been added on
as a guest house.
	   Municipal officials said they ordered residents to vacate the
building several months ago, reportedly after it was noticed to be
leaning toward one side. The warning was ignored.
	   ``We feared yesterday the toll could have been much higher ...
because of the guest house,'' said Sridhar Joshi, a top civic
official. Many rooms were unoccupied at the time of the collapse.
</TEXT>
