<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-England-South Africa-Security </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cricket authorities employ soccer hooligan control tactics
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LEEDS, England (AP) _ Cricket fans at the fifth test between
England and South Africa starting at Headingley Thursday will be
subjected to the same security tactics as those used to control
soccer hooligans.
	   The Western Terrace at Headingley, which accommodates 6,000
spectators, has been the scene of trouble in previous years and
West Yorkshire police have pinpointed the area for extra security.
	   Police will use plain-clothed ``spotters'' with knowledge of
known local hooligans and video surveillance equipment _ the first
time such tactics have been used at a test cricket match in
England.
	   Inspector David Boyle, who is supervising police security at the
five-day match, said he would use methods developed by the National
Football Intelligence Unit to combat unlawful behavior in the
crowd.
	   ``There is increasing evidence that people are attending in
order to extend their football xenophobia within cricket,'' Boyle
said Tuesday.
	   ``We have seen this in the wearing of football strips, the
football banners in the crowd and the organized chanting which has
been seen at cricket.
	   ``(there is) the possibility that people involved in football
violence are coming to cricket.''
	   Headingley was the scene of an attack on Australian player Tim
Zoehrer by a spectator after an Ashes match in 1993, while a pig's
head was paraded around the crowd during the Pakistan tour in 1992.
	   An alcohol ban will be placed on the Western Terrace, while
restrictions will be imposed in other areas of the ground.
	   A ban on outrageous costumes imposed during the third test
between England and South Africa at Old Trafford will be repeated
at Headingley.
	   (jp)
</TEXT>
