<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Activist Slain,0268 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Opposition activist's body found in western Mexico
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ The body of an opposition activist has been
found in the western state of Guerrero two weeks after he was
kidnapped, newspapers reported Tuesday.
	   Leaders of the leftist Democratic Revolution Party, known as the
PRD, blamed state police for the kidnapping and death of Pedro
Romero Macedo. Police had no public comment on the case.
	   Romero Macedo had been active in an anti-corruption group that
accused the mayor of Tlachapa, a member of the rival Institutional
Revolutionary Party, of diverting more than 2 million pesos, or
dlrs 224,700, from the local government.
	   Macedo disappeared on July 22. PRD members found his decomposing
body Monday in ditch near Cacamicua, a village within Tlachapa
municipality.
	   Martin Mora Aguirre, secretary-general of the PRD's state
committee, blamed state police, noting that the Tlachapa police
chief had told the party members days ago to stop looking for
Romero Macedo because surely ``he should already be dead in a
ditch,'' Mexico City papers reported.
	   PRD members have asserted they are the targets of a harassment
campaign by the ruling party, known as the PRI, in Guerrero state.
Several PRD members have been detained by police in Guerrero in
recent months.
	   The PRD also claims scores of its activists in Guerrero have
died in political violence over the past decade. Officials say the
incidents were common crimes, not political ones.
	   The PRD is one of Mexico's three major parties and is the PRI's
main rival in Guerrero.
</TEXT>
