<SLUG> BC-Poland-Name Game </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former Radio Free Europe workers fight for freedom, at least in
</HEADLINE>
name &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Another freedom fight has erupted in
Poland, at least in name.
	   Former Polish employees of U.S.-sponsored Radio Free Europe are
battling their previous employer over the use of the network's
name, associated by Poles with freedom and democracy, a daily
newspaper reported Tuesday.
	   The U.S. corporation protested the use of its trademark by the
former employees of its Polish division, who wanted to name their
publishing company with the Polish translation of Radio Free
Europe, according to the Rzeczpospolita report.
	   When the state licensing agency agreed with the Americans,
saying the U.S. group invented and promoted the name, the Poles
decided to lodge an appeal.
	   They said the U.S. corporation registered the name only in its
English version, the newspaper reported. If the logic of the
licensing agency were followed, they argued, then the Polish
magazine ``Czas,'' which means ``Time,'' also would have to change
its name, according to the newspaper.
	   The licensing agency's appeal body decided Monday to expand its
panel to decide the matter on an unspecified date.
	   (bp-tsc)
</TEXT>
