<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Finally Summer </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
It took three months, but summer comes _ finally _ to Britain
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MARA BELLABY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ When Fabrizio Pellizzetti moved here from his
native Italy four weeks ago, friends warned him he would miss the
sun and balmy skies. How right they were.
	   Even in a country known for its gray, overcast days, this summer
has tested Britons' resilience, as they awoke day after day to
clouds and the hint of rain.
	   But Tuesday, all that seemed to be changing _ or at least people
chose to believe it was _ as forecasts called for the sudden
appearance of sunny days and temperatures in the mid-80s through
the weekend in most of the country.
	   Office workers in London drank their midday pints outside at
sidewalk tables, and women strolling through an open-air market
marched straight past the heavier clothes, drawn optimistically to
the halter tops and summer dresses.
	   The sun worshippers weren't the only ones loosening their ties
and rolling up their sleeves. Gardeners, golfers and resort-goers
also were expected to take advantage of the break in the weather.
	   ``The sun comes out and people are here within minutes,'' said
Helen Derrin, assistant manager of Clifton Nurseries in London.
	   The phone started ringing nonstop at the Stockley Park Golf
Course in Middlesex, with golfers eager to reserve tee-off times
for the weekend, operations manager Neil Munro said.
	   And the resort towns of Blackpool and Brighton were gearing up
for the arrival of tourists eager to be near the water now that the
sun was shining.
	   Balmy Tuesday proved that there is nothing like a blue sky and
the prospect of a few unblemished summer days to raise British
spirits. It even makes the past few months forgivable.
	   ``I don't think this summer's been too bad,'' said Jake Sale,
32, of Bedford, putting a cheery spin on a gloomy summer that might
only be possible when the sun is shining.
	   Pity, however, the poor souls in the country's northern reaches
and in Scotland, who still face the threat of rain and clouds in
the days ahead.
	   Leave it to Nathan Powell of the Meteorological Office to break
the bad news.
	   ``Unfortunately,'' Powell said, as gently as possible, ``it is
not going to be lovely everywhere.''
	   (mb-kg)
</TEXT>
