w2330 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Iraq 8thLd-Writethru   08-04 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq, 8th Ld-Writethru,0686 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Butler: Iraq refusing to hold further disarmament talks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Annan's comments in 11th graf; Edits 17th graf to
conform &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos staffing &QL; 
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraq is refusing to hold further
disarmament talks with the United Nations, the chief weapons
inspector said Tuesday, leaving uncertain the future of the U.N.
program to eliminate Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
	   Richard Butler, head of the U.N. Special Commission, said he
will brief the U.N. Security Council on Thursday on Monday's failed
talks with Iraq's chief negotiator, Deputy Prime Minister Tariq
Aziz.
	   Butler said the impasse resulted from Aziz's demand for a UNSCOM
certification that Iraq has dismantled all its illegal weapons,
including chemical and biological arms and long-range missiles.
	   ``I told him that `I cannot fulfill your demand because I don't
have the evidence,''' Butler told The Associated Press in Bahrain,
where he arrived Tuesday from Baghdad en route to New York.
	   Butler continued: ``After I said that to him, Aziz replied,
`Then we can't talk any further.'''
	   Butler's political adviser, Gustavo Zlauvinen, said Aziz also
refused to accept a work schedule aimed at increasing the pace of
weapons inspection work.
	   The Iraqi position was the ``main reason why we had to cut short
our trip in Baghdad. The talks were getting nowhere,'' he told AP.
	   Zlauvinen said a lot more work needs to be done to get a clearer
picture of Iraq's weapons capability.
	   Until UNSCOM certifies that Iraq is free of weapons of mass
destruction, the U.N. Security Council will not lift economic
sanctions imposed after Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait. Iraqi
troops were evicted by the United States and its allies in the 1991
Gulf War.
	   In Washington, White House spokesman P.J. Crowley said Saddam
Hussein should not hope for an end to the sanctions until Iraq
complies with its obligations.
	   In New York, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said the next
step will be determined by Butler's report to the Council.
	   Iraq's latest stand threatens to bring to a halt UNSCOM's
seven-year search for the illegal weapons, a mission often
disrupted by confrontations between Iraqi and U.N. officials.
	   However, the official Iraqi News Agency quoted Butler as saying
earlier the problem has not become a crisis. ``It is imperative not
to overdramatize the situation,'' Butler was quoted as saying.
	   Still, experts think that the Iraq-U.N. relationship is in
trouble.
	   ``Confrontation is looming, definitely,'' Tim Trevan, who served
on the U.N. inspections team from 1992 to 1995, was quoted as
saying on BBC radio.
	   Earlier this year, the United States and Britain sent warships
to the Gulf after Iraq refused to open presidential sites to U.N.
inspectors.
	   That crisis was defused by an agreement brokered in February by
Annan.
	   After that, U.N.-Iraq tensions appeared to be easing until a
U.S. military lab reported in June that it found traces of deadly
VX nerve gas on fragments of Iraqi missile warheads it tested.
	   Iraq had claimed that although it developed VX, it never put the
chemical on missiles.
	   Zlauvinen, Butler's adviser, said the discovery of VX showed
Iraq's biological weapons program continues to have ``many
loopholes.''
	   ``It's still a big mess,'' he said.
	   On Monday, Aziz accused Butler of deliberately prolonging the
sanctions at the behest of the United States.
	   He said Butler is focusing on ``minor issues which make no sense
from the angle of disarmament.''
	   In London, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook rejected Aziz's
statement.
	   ``Iraqi claims that UNSCOM is haggling over minor details are
patently absurd,'' Cook said in a statement, adding that UNSCOM has
confirmed ``Iraqi weaponization'' of VX nerve gas.
	   But Iraq's frustrations with the sanctions are also evident.
	   Last month, Saddam said in a nationally televised speech that
the sanctions must be lifted this year _ the first time he had set
a deadline.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
