<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Zimbabwe-Currency, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Zimbabwe dollar falls 20 percent as economic fears deepen
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with increased rediscount rate,
closing exchange rates, stock exchange index fall; ADDS quotes &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ The Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe raised its
rediscount interest rate 3.5 percent, but the country's currency
continued to slide on foreign exchange markets.
	   Bank Governor Leonard Tsumba held an emergency meeting Tuesday
of heads of commercial and merchant banks, in which he blamed them
and speculators for the slide, according to a banker who was
present and who asked not to be named.
	   Monday's volatile trading saw the Zimbabwe dollar depreciate
about 20 percent.
	   Last week the Zimbabwe dollar was trading at 18.8 for one U.S.
dollar. It had slid on foreign exchange markets to 25 to 27
Zimbabwe dollars per U.S. dollar by close of trading Tuesday.
	   ``This unhappy state of affairs has been largely self-inflicted,
due to intemperate political rhetoric ... and the unrealistic
assumption by the Reserve Bank that Zimbabwe could substantially
overvalue its currency relative to its major trading partners,''
Nick Swanepoel told the annual congress of the Commercial Farmers'
Union. Swanepoel is retiring as president of the 4,500-member
group.
	   The industrial index on Zimbabwe's stock exchange fell 216.97
points on Tuesday.
	   The crisis was believed to have been triggered by a rush of
demand by importers, who feared shortage of funds for pre-Christmas
imports, coupled with a threatened five-day national strike by
trade unions, poor commodity prices and possible withdrawal of
International Monetary Fund budget support.
	   The Reserve Bank raised its rediscount interest rate Tuesday 3.5
percent to 35 percent.
	   John Makamure, economist for the Zimbabwe National Chamber of
Commerce, predicted a wave of bankruptcies.
	   ``Many of our members are bleeding already,'' he said. ``They
will certainly not sustain any further increases in interest rates.
It will not resolve the problem in the long term.''
	   An IMF delegation was due to review payments of 176 million U.S.
dollars in budget support following President Robert Mugabe's
backtracking on economic liberalization pledges made since 1991.
	   (mh-aos)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Zimbabwe-Currency, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
