<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Czech-Havel, 5th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Havel reported stable after morning crisis
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. RECASTS and UPDATES with fresh quotes. &QL; 
 &UR; By ONDREJ HEJMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) _ Ailing Czech President Vaclav
Havel was reported in stable condition late Tuesday, after doctors
used electroshocks to restore his heart function.
	   During the two-hour long crisis early Tuesday, Havel's heart
rate soared to 200 beats per minute, due to blood poisoning caused
by pneumonia. Doctors had to apply electroshocks to stabilize it.
	   ``Now the president is stable, his fever is down,'' Ilja Kotik,
head of Havel's medical team, told a news conference later Tuesday.
	   Doctors described the president's condition early in the day as
``temporarily critical,'' but denied speculations that Havel's life
had been in danger at any time.
	   ``This was not a case of clinical death, because his blood
circulation did not stop,'' Kotik said, describing the event as
paroxysmal tachycardia and fibrilation.
	   On July 26, Havel underwent a long-planned abdominal surgery to
close a colostomy, an operation complicated by pneumonia he
developed Monday.
	   ``The cause of the crisis was a septic state he got into as we
tried to cure his lungs,'' said Miroslav Cerbak, coordinator of the
team.
	   The 61-year-old president, a former chain smoker and veteran of
Communist jails, has suffered from chronic bronchitis for years.
	   He has been hospitalized five times since December 1996, when a
third of his lung and a cancerous tumor were removed.
	   ``You can never rule out a relapse (of irregular heartbeat)''
Kotik said, but added Havel's current condition gave enough ground
for an optimistic prognosis.
	   According to doctors Havel was awake late Tuesday, his heart
function was normal and the president was able to communicate
through written notes.
	   ``I feared for him all night, and this morning too, but now it
seems to me he's doing better,'' the hospitalized president's wife,
Dagmar, told reporters after leaving his bedside Tuesday afternoon
at Prague's military hospital.
	   Havel served as president of Czechoslovakia for three years
after the 1989 anti-Communist revolution. He has served another
five years as president of the Czech Republic, after the federation
broke up on Jan. 1, 1993.
	   This January, he was narrowly reelected as Czech president for
his second and final five-year.
	   Assuming no further complications, doctors estimated Havel will
need at least six to eight weeks before he is able to return to
office.
	   (oh/me) 	   
</TEXT>
