<SLUG> BC-Russia-Deserters </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: More than 6,000 Russian deserters surrender to authorities
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ More than 6,000 Russian army deserters gave
themselves up to to military prosecutors during the first six
months of this year, a news agency reported Tuesday.
	   Many of the 6,187 deserters who surrendered to military
authorities did so under a ``Deserter Come Home'' program that was
launched in March and offered leniency to those who gave up.
	   Desertion has become an increasingly grave problem for Russia's
military. Morale is low in the armed forces, conditions are
frequently bleak and hazing has caused numerous deaths.
	   According to the ITAR-Tass news agency, 4,832 of the deserters
who surrendered were pardoned, including 3,300 who left their units
because of hazing.
	   (ml)
</TEXT>
