<HEADLINE>
Moldovan prime minister discusses economic, border issues in
</HEADLINE>
Ukraine &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: ADDS two new bottom grafs with details &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) - A Moldovan delegation headed by Prime
Min-sdFr Yon Chubuk met Tuesday with Ukrainian officials to discuss
border demarcation and economic issues.
	   Ukrainian premier Valery Pustovoitenko, who conferred with
Chubuk, called neighboring Moldova Ukraine's strategic partner but
said economic relations between the two former Soviet republics
should be intensified.
	   He noted that trade turnover between the two nations this year
has been decreasins, focused on the
demarcation of mutual borders, the future of resorts and
sanitariums built by then-Soviet Moldova in Ukraine, plans to build
an oil terminal on the joint border and Moldova's debt for
Ukrainian electricity, estimated at dlrs 11 million.
	   The sides agreed that Moldova would receive a small area of
Ukrainian territory to build an oil terminal in exchange for a
section of the road connecting the Ukrainian cities of Odessa and
Izmail and partly running through Moldova, Pustovoitenko said after
the talks.
	   Moldova and Ukraine also would work on preparing a 10-year
economic cooperation treaty, he said.
	   (sms/ml)
