<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cycling-Riders Return </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Festina riders return in first race since Tour drama
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: will be led with second round. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) _ Three Swiss cyclists in the Festina
team expelled last month from the Tour de France made a low-key
return to the road Tuesday in the Cross-Lausanne event.
	   Spectators sparsely lining the streets of this lakeside city
applauded Alex Zuelle, Laurent Dufaux and Armin Meier, among 25
riders taking part in the evening race.
	   They cheered and clanged cowbells as the Festina riders set off
over the 6.85 kilometer (4.26 mile) course, some of it over the
cobblestones of Lausanne's old town.
	   Festina was thrown off the Tour because its riders were said to
have taken the hormone EPO. Zuelle, Dufaux and Meier were among
those who later admitted taking the drug.
	   Dufaux's name had been painted on the road at the arrival, and
banners along the route welcomed the rider.
	   Tour de France winner Marco Pantani of Italy, racing in a yellow
jersey, won the first of two time trials over the uphill course in
12 minutes 28 seconds, with a 45-second advantage over
Switzerland's Pascal Richard.
	   Also taking part was Colorado's Bobby Julich, third in the Tour.
Julich finished third in Tuesday's first round, 48 seconds behind
Pantani. Dufaux was fourth.
 &UR; (gm)
</TEXT>
