<SLUG> BC-Congo, 5th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kabila moving against rebellious troops
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. LEADS with battles in eastern towns and western village
of Kitona. ADDS fresh quotes. Edits throughout to delete old
material and UPDATE throughout. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; By KAMANGA MUTOND &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) _ Troops loyal to President Laurent Kabila
battled with rebellious Tutsi fighters Tuesday at opposite ends of
the country in an uprising aimed at toppling the president's
14-month-old regime.
	   Gunfire was reported in the eastern town of Bukavu near the
border with Rwanda, said aid workers based there. A provincial
official told The Associated Press that the rebels were in control
of the town, although some reports indicated fighting there
continued.
	   Banyamulenge Tutsis and Rwandan soldiers led the uprising
against Kabila, accusing him of widespread corruption and
government mismanagement.
	   In the southwestern village of Kitona, where rebel gunmen forced
a hijacked private airplane to land, fighting was reported at the
town's main military base, a government spokesman said.
	   It was unclear who was in control of the base in Kitona, but
Kabila has vowed to crush the uprising and called on his supporters
for help.
	   ``Be assured we will take weapons to swiftly end this
rebellion,'' Cabinet minister Pierre Victor Mpoyo said on state
radio, quoting Kabila.
	   The vice governor of South Kivu province, Benjamin Serukiza said
the Tutsi rebels had taken control of much of the province,
including Bukavu and its airport.
	   ``At the moment a large portion of the province is under the
control of the army which is hostile to Kabila's regime,'' Serukiza
said in a telephone interview.
	   Kivu region is divided into three provinces, including North
Kivu, South Kivu and Maniema.
	   In the city of Goma, gunmen hijacked a private airplane and
ordered the pilot to fly to the military base in Kitona near the
Atlantic coastline on the opposite side of the country, said
Kabila's spokesman Yerodia Abdoulaye Ndombasi.
	   The hijacking was led by Banyamulenge ethnic fighters.
	   The Congolese airplane owned by the private airline CAL touched
down in Kitona about 225 kilometers (140 miles) southwest of
Kinshasa, said Ndombasi.
	   He gave no other details concerning the hijacking during a brief
announcement broadcast on state television.
	   Kabila convened an emergency cabinet meeting Tuesday to discuss
the government's response to the rebellion in the east and to
earlier gun battles in two military barracks in the capital.
	   ``The government asks Congo's neighbors not to make the wrong
decisions to fight,'' Mpoyo said in a radio broadcast following the
meeting.
	   The comment was aimed directly at neighboring Rwanda, which
Kabila believes is behind the movement against his leadership.
Rwandan fighters and Banyamulenge Tutsis played a key role in
helping Kabila march to victory last year over longtime dictator
Mobutu Sese Seko.
	   Those same fighters today, however, appear to be moving to get
rid of Kabila.
	   A delicate ethnic and military alliance that helped thrust
Kabila _ a one-time obscure Marxist rebel _ into power 14 months
ago is now unraveling.
	   ``Kabila has been very aggressive against his neighbors of
late,'' said Rwandan chief of staff Gen. Kayumba Nyamwasa. ``So
today is Rwanda's turn.''
	   He denied Rwanda was involved in the mutiny, but warned that the
rebellion included some of the best soldiers in Kabila's army.
	   The rebel forces may ``push up to Kinshasa,'' he said, adding
``It depends on how effective they will be.''
	   Congo's Justice Minister Mwenze Kongolo said the government was
preparing an armed response to the rebellion in Kivu region.
	   The ethnic Tutsi population in the area has close links with
Rwanda, while Kabila's support and control of the region has
faltered for months.
	   ``We're telling them to lay down their arms and end this
adventure before we immediately bring in the army,'' Kongolo said.
	   In the capital one day after shots rang out at two military
bases on Kinshasa's west end, loyal troops continued to patrol city
streets and man roadblocks.
	   A dusk-to-dawn curfew was still in effect, but life in the city
began to return to normal as abandoned streets began to fill again
with shoppers and merchants.
 &UR; (var/ids) 	   
