<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Parachutists Killed </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Authorities open criminal investigation into fatal parachute
</HEADLINE>
accident &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Authorities in northern Russian have opened a
criminal investigation into an accident in a skydiving training
class in which four teen-agers are believed to have died, a news
agency reported Tuesday.
	   The teens were carried by strong winds last Friday into Lake
Onega, a large lake in the Russian republic of Karelia. One drowned
when she became tangled in her parachute lines, and three others
remain missing and are presumed dead, the ITAR-Tass news agency
said.
	   Divers have been searching the bottom of the lake, but
authorities said the area involved is so vast that the bodies are
unlikely to be found anytime soon.
	   Yuri Ivukov, the chairman of Karelia's emergencies department,
blamed a sports club for the deaths, saying trainers had neglected
elementary safety rules. However, no charges have been filed.
	   ``The jumpers were absolutely unprepared,'' Ivukov said. ``Young
men and women sky-dived for the first time in their lives. They had
studied it on the ground for only four hours.''
	   The young people involved in the jumps ranged in age from 15 to
17, ITAR-Tass said.
	   (ml)
</TEXT>
