<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Greece-Fires, 2nd-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
State of emergency declared in forest fire area near Athens
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with premier cutting short vacation, some fires dying
down, others under control, no pickup.
 &UR; AP Photos XATH103-7

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ Authorities declared a state of emergency
in areas near Athens on Tuesday as more than 1,000 firefighters and
soldiers battled a huge forest fire raging for a second day.
	   Evidence suggested the blazes could be the work of arsonists,
officials said.
	   Premier Costas Simitis cut short his vacation on an Aegean Sea
island and flew back to the capital to assess the situation and
coordinate efforts to extinguish the blaze, which at midday had
branched off in various directions.
	   By evening, only a few of the fire's fronts were still ablaze.
The majority around the foot of Mount Pendeli, about four
kilometers (2 1/2 miles) northeast of Athens' northern suburbs, had
either died down or were under control.
	   Efforts had been hampered by gale force winds reaching 74
kilometers an hour (46 mph), which grounded firefighting planes and
Chinook helicopters dispatched to help battle the blaze around the
village of Anthousa, about three kilometers (1.8 miles) east of
Athens. That fire had died down by nightfall, authorities said.
	   Residents and volunteers assisted 650 firefighters and 500
soldiers with 30 fire trucks battling the fire, which was rekindled
during the night after being brought under control.
	   The blaze reportedly damaged several houses and a German World
War II cemetery and led to the evacuation of a convent, a military
hospital and a home for disabled children. A children's summer camp
also was severely damaged.
	   The fire began late Sunday at the foot of Mount Pendeli.
	   Local officials have said anonymous telephone callers on Sunday
threatened to burn local forests. Fire brigade and police radio
frequencies were jammed Monday by callers shouting obscenities and
reporting fires far from the actual blazes.
	   ``There was an attempt to terrorize firefighting forces and
cause anxiety,'' said Public Order Minister Giorgos Romeos.
	   No injuries due to the fires were reported. Blazes in the
Pendeli area in past years have left much of the mountainside a
landscape of charred stumps.
	   A separate large fire broke out near the southeastern seaside
resort suburb of Lagonisi. No houses or hotels were threatened, and
it also had died down by evening.
	   In another brush fire, flames had threatened some ancient sites
including the small amphitheater at Epidavros, about 60 kilometers
(35 miles) southwest of Athens, media reports said.
	   Two weeks ago, three firefighters and a volunteer firefighter
were killed battling a blaze that scorched the eastern edge of
Athens.
	   Wildfires are common during the hot and dry summers in Greece.
But this season has been called one of the most devastating in
decades, with fires burning daily for the past month.
	   (eb-bm/pq)	   
</TEXT>
