<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Kohl Interview, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede Bonn
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Chancellor Helmut Kohl says he expects to be re-elected &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with color, background on Free Democrats. &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN MADER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Unfazed by recent polls that show his
Christian Democrats trailing, Chancellor Helmut Kohl said Tuesday
that he expects to win his fifth consecutive election in September
but acknowledged it'll be a tight race.
	   The outcome, Kohl told RTL television in a traditional summer
interview from his Austrian vacation spot, will be decided in the
last weeks of the campaign.
	   ``I am sure that we will win the election,'' said Kohl, smiling
broadly while seated at a old wooden picnic table with two network
moderators. ``I think that the decision will be made in the last
four weeks, and there is still a lot of movement left.''
	   Recent polls show that two-thirds of Germans expect a change in
government after Sept. 27 elections. The edge is going to the rival
Social Democrats, leading polls with 41 percent to the 37 percent
for the Christian Democrats and its allied Christian Social Union
(CSU).
	   Kohl said his party and the CSU ``don't have a single vote to
spare.''
	   But Kohl said he expects high voter turnout, upwards of 80
percent, to help his conservative coalition by making it more
difficult for smaller rival parties to get the 5 percent they need
to enter parliament.
	   In another tacit acknowledgment of a tight race, Kohl urged
supporters of the current government to vote for either his party
or the CSU rather than for the third partner in the ruling
coalition, the small, market-oriented Free Democratic Party.
	   The Free Democrats have in the past played kingmaker when no
party has a clear majority, and ruled with the Social Democrats
before helping bring Kohl to power. Some members have openly said
the party should again consider allying the Social Democrats after
the Sept. 27 election.
	   ``Whoever wants the policies of this government with this
chancellor to continue must vote for the Christian Democrats and
the Christian Social Union,'' Kohl said. ``The Free Democrats must
create their own votes, and they must consider what methods they
will use.''
	   If he wins re-election, Kohl said any new government would
include Finance Minister Theo Waigel, the CSU party leader.
	   Last summer while Kohl was vacationing, Waigel agitated the
chancellor by suggesting he wanted a new job, the foreign ministry,
perhaps.
	   This summer, he's busy stumping for Kohl. On Tuesday, Waigel
released a sweeping fiscal plan extending to the year 2010 and
repeated that Kohl's coalition is ready to implement its tax reform
plan on Jan. 1 if it wins re-election.
	   ``Unlike the opposition we have a law draft complete,'' Waigel
said.
	   The Social Democrats last year blocked Kohl's plan to cut the
rate of private income taxation to between 15 percent and 39
percent from a current range of 26 percent to 53 percent.
	   While Kohl broke off his vacation for the television interview,
Schroeder interrupted his for a 24-hour trip to Washington, where a
photo opportunity with President Clinton and a foreign policy
speech at Georgetown University Wednesday could help boost his
stature as a statesman.
	    &UR; (cb-gb-im)
</TEXT>
