w2408 &Cx1f; wstm-
u b &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Italy-CoolingOff     08-04 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Cooling Off </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Relentless heat convinces Italians to _ finally _ try air
</HEADLINE>
conditioning &QL; 
 &UR; By VANIA GRANDI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ The way a lot of Italians talk about air
conditioning you'd think it was some kind of dangerous germ. Many
believe it causes sore throats, stiff joints _ even pneumonia.
	   But weeks of sizzling weather appear to be breaking down this
deeply entrenched aversion.
	   Rome air conditioning merchants say sales shot up nearly 40
percent compared to last summer.
	   ``I am not saying we're working 24 hours a day. But I haven't
had a weekend off for three months,'' said Franco Consumati, who
installs the units for the Rome store GMC.
	   Consumati said a lot of his clients are still wary about air
conditioning. Some people still think they cause colds and other
ailments; others won't put their children in the path of the cold
air.
	   ``When I made my 84-year-old grandmother let me install air
conditioning for her, she made such a fuss about how bad it was,''
said Consumati. ``Now she gets mad at me if I don't go over to
check it on the first hot day.''
	   It's so hot _ temperatures well above the seasonal norms at
consistently over 90 F (33 C) _ that everyone is talking about how
to beat the heat.
	   One expert appearing on state TV said it's fine to dunk your
feet in a fountain _ but using air conditioning is a no-no. A list
of hot-weather ``dos'' and ``don'ts'' in Corriere della Sera
newspaper had air conditioning in the ``don't'' category.
	   But people aren't listening to the experts. They just want to
get cool.
	   Italians may also be snapping up air conditioners because of a
change in how they spend their summers. In the past most fled to
the seaside or mountains when it got hot; Rome used to be a ghost
town in August.
	   But not all businesses close for a long summer vacation these
days, which means some people have to work instead of play. And
with rising unemployment, others simply can't afford to get away.
	   Many stores were caught unprepared and didn't order enough units
from the factories. Now they're stuck because the factories close
in August, Italy's near-sacred vacation month.
	   ``A lot of people came in this week asking for air
conditioners,'' said Teresa Verdeoliva, a clerk at the store I.T.C.
``But I couldn't sell them anything because we've run out.''
	   (vg-cph)
</TEXT>
