w2413 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Iran-Missile     08-04 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iran-Missile </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iran: New missile a tool to defend the Muslim world
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ A new medium-range missile that Iran test
fired last month is meant to defend the Muslim world and other
oppressed countries, a senior military commander said Tuesday.
	   Experience has shown that Muslims' pacifism has only made
enemies more aggressive, Brig. Gen. Mohammad Bagher Qalibaf said in
an interview with the official Islamic Republic News Agency.
	   However, Iran does not seek war and strengthening its defenses
is only aimed at deterring enemies, Qalibaf was quoted as saying by
IRNA.
	   Qalibaf is the commander of the air wing of the Islamic
Revolutionary Guard Corps, a separate force in the military with a
strength of about 120,000 men.
	   Qalibaf's comments are the first time that Iran has indicated a
religious motive for developing the Shahab-3 missile, whose range
of 1,300 kilometers (800 miles) makes it capable of hitting Israel
and U.S. troops stationed in Saudi Arabia.
	   Iran is staunchly opposed to any peace with Israel and calls for
its annihilation. It also backs guerrilla groups fighting Israeli
troops in South Lebanon.
	   Qalibaf said Shahab-3 is the product of an ambitious arms
development program that Iran launched during the 1980-88 war with
Iraq.
	   He rejected claims by the United States that Russia helped Iran
build Shahab-3.
	   ``The West's sensationalism and propaganda ... come at a time
when the West possesses 95 percent of the enriched plutonium in the
world enough for producing 60,000 bombs and warheads,'' IRNA said,
quoting Qalibaf.
	   He said the first Iranian-made missile was completed in February
1984.
	   On Sunday, Qalibaf disclosed that the Shahab-3 ballistic missile
is 16 meters (53 feet) long and can travel at a speed of 7,000
kilometers (4,320 miles) per hour, carrying a one ton warhead. Its
cruising altitude is 250 kilometers (155 miles) above sea level.
	   The United States says Iran is working on a long-range missile
that could be deployed in two to five years, and has pledged to
redouble its efforts to curb the transfer of technology Iran needs
to develop it.
	   But Iranian President Mohammad Khatami said Saturday that his
country is determined to continue strengthening its armed forces,
regardless of international concern.
	   Iran had virtually no arms industry under the U.S.-supported
shah because Washington supplied nearly all of Iran's defense
needs. The shah was ousted during the 1979 Islamic revolution.
	   Iran claims it is nearly self-sufficient in arms now. Since
1992, it has unveiled its own tanks, armored personnel carriers,
missiles, and even a fighter plane.
 &UR; vj
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Iran-Missile; CT:i; 
