<HEADLINE>
Arazi thrown out of Dutch Open
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: updates with later matches &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) _ Moroccan Hicham Arazi was thrown
out of the Grolsch Open tennis tourney Tuesday for unsportsmanlike
conduct at 7-6 (11-9), 1-5 against Swede Magnus Norman.
	   Arazi had already been warned by the umpire twice for throwing
his racket, as he grew increasingly angry with himself for making
errors in the second set of this first-round match.
	   When he several times deliberately hit the ball wildly out of
bounds in an apparent attempt to throw the second set, he was given
a third warning and an automatic disqualification.
	   Arazi, ranked 42 in the world, will forfeit his prize money and
may be fined by the ATP tour administration.
	   Top-seeded Slovakian Karol Kucera met unexpectedly tough
resistance from 75th-ranked Russian Marat Safin, but struggled
through to the last 16 with a 6-2, 3-6, 7-6 (7-5) win.
	   Safin peppered the decisive tiebreaker with unforced errors to
trail 6 points to 3.
	   The 18-year-old Russian saved the first two match points but
netted a backhand volley to lose after 2 hours 6 minutes.
	   But this dlrs 500,000 clay court event lost two more seeds in
the first round.
	   Argentinian qualifier Mariano Zabaleta sprayed angled winners
all around the court and retrieved acrobatically to upset the No. 2
seed Felix Mantilla of Spain, 7-6 (7-2) 6-2.
	   And 66th-ranked Czech Jiri Novak ousted Italian fifth seed
Andrea Gaudenzi in straight sets 6-3, 6-2.
	   But Czech No. 8 seed Slava Dosedel advanced against Argentinian
Mariano Puerta, 7-6 (7-5), 6-1.
	   (sc)	   
