<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinian, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede JERUSALEM
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Israel still hopeful though Palestinians reject its offers &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: AMs RECAST. UPDATES throughout with fresh comments, Netanyahu
meeting on prisoner release; CHANGES byline &QL; 
 &UR; By DAFNA LINZER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said
Tuesday that Israel has offered proposals aimed at pleasing both
sides and hoped the Palestinians would consider the ideas and
continue talks over the scope of a West Bank troop withdrawal.
	   After a series of direct negotiations, the Palestinians rejected
Tuesday an Israeli idea which altered the size of a withdrawal set
out in an American peace plan and did not schedule further talks.
	   The Palestinians had threatened to walk away from the sessions
if no acceptable ideas were presented at a meeting Monday between
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators.
	   But Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat was cautious Tuesday not to
rule out future meetings. Although he said Israeli negotiators
brought nothing new to Monday's meeting, the Palestinians were
``studying'' whether to continue the talks.
	   The sides have been haggling over an American initiative which
calls for Israel to withdraw from 13 percent of the West Bank. The
Palestinians accepted the plan but the United States failed to get
Israeli support for it, and sent the sides back to negotiate
directly a little over two weeks ago.
	   Netanyahu however said his negotiating team had offered up
thoughtful ideas and that an agreement was still within reach.
	   ``I think there has been substantive discussions. There are some
ideas that the Palestinians have brought up, and we took a thread
or two and tried to weave them together to proposals of our own
which we presented yesterday,'' Netanyahu told reporters.
	   Israel wants to see ``an intensive, serious and discreet set of
negotiations for the completion of an agreement,'' Netanyahu said.
	   But Arafat said the Israeli offer was ``very far'' from the
existing Israel-Palestinian agreements or from the American plan.
	   Palestinian negotiator Hassan Asfour said Israel had offered to
withdraw from 10 percent of the West Bank and turn the remaining 3
percent into a nature reserve where Israel would retain overall
security control and the Palestinians would be forbidden to build.
	   ``This is rejected by the Palestinians,'' Asfour said. ``Our
position is clear: We were presented with an American proposal in
March, and that is what we stand by.''
	   ``If the Israeli proposals stay along this line, then there is
no need for further meetings,'' Asfour said.
	   Arafat's spokesman, Nabil Abourdeneh, called Monday's
negotiating session ``a waste of time.''
	   In Washington, U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin said
Monday that the administration was still hopeful the sides would
continue talks.
	   Meanwhile, Netanyahu was expected to face pressures from members
of his inner Security Cabinet at a meeting Wednesday to discuss
options in the talks. Ariel Sharon, a powerful minister in
Netanyahu's right-wing coalition is against turning over more than
9 percent of West Bank land, saying it would harm Israel's
security.
	   Netanyahu is also considering a Palestinian request to release
120 Palestinian prisoners held by Israel, a request several of his
ministers have said they oppose.
 &UR; dl 	   
</TEXT>
