<SLUG> BC-Sports-Basketball-Worlds-Notebook, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIBA: Low attendance hurting sport's image
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with new material. CHANGES byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By HOWARD FENDRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ Sparse attendance at the World Basketball
Championship is hampering the sport's image, the world governing
body said Tuesday.
	   ``We are the No. 1 indoor sport, but you don't get that
impression when there are 2,000 people in stadiums that seat
18,000,'' FIBA spokesman Florian Wanninger said. ``The atmosphere
in arenas is important for our image, which is why have not been
too happy.''
	   While local organizing committee officials would not release
complete attendance figures, they did acknowledge that games not
involving Greece are averaging less than 2,000 per day. Several
games have had fans in the hundreds.
	   Preliminary round games have been played at the 18,000-seat
Olympic arena and the 14,000-seat Peace and Friendship arena.
	   Rims reverberate loudly on missed shots. Timeout huddles are
hardly private _ fans 30 rows up can listen in.
	   ``We are disappointed so far,'' Wanninger said. ``We knew in
advance, and it has been verified, that Greek people love their
team but not necessarily basketball. We have had very good games in
front of 500 spectators. That's a pity.''
	   Local officials, who have tried to boost attendance by selling
tickets at newspaper kiosks around Athens, blame the lack of
interest on the absence of the Dream Team, the group of NBA stars
dropped by USA Basketball in June because of the league's ongoing
labor dispute.
	   The last major sporting event hosted by Athens, last summer's
World Athletics Championships, was also plagued by slow attendance.
	   Officials attributed that to the exodus of Athenians to islands
during August, when temperatures top 38 degrees Celsius (100 F)
daily in the city.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   LET'S GET PHYSICAL: &LR;  Some of the American players are finding it
tough to adjust to the grinding style of international play.
	   ``They set picks that snap your neck,'' said Jimmy King, who
helped Michigan's Fab Five reach two U.S. NCAA college title games.
``You have to be alert.''
	   The United States has one of the smaller lineups among those
teams in the running for medals, but has managed to hold its own
under the boards by sending waves of players at the basket. It
out-rebounded its first five opponents by a 36-30 average.
	   ``It's a more physical game,'' coach Rudy Tomjanovich said.
``Our guys just have to keep banging and banging down low.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	   STATS: &LR;  Puerto Rico's burly center Jose Ortiz is the only player
averaging double figures in both points (16.8) and rebounds
(tournament-best 10.6). The 6-foot-10 (2.07-meter) Ortiz once
played for the NBA's Utah Jazz.
	   The leading scorer is Spain's Alberto Herreros, who upped his
average to 20.5 points per game after pouring in 27 against the
United States Monday night and the same total against Lithuania
Tuesday. Lithuanian forward Arturas Karnisovas, a Seton Hall
product, is next with 18.2.
	   Michael Hawkins of the United States and Argentina's Marcelo
Milanesio share top assists honors at 4.2 per game. Hawkins has
dropped off considerably after registering 10 assists, a record for
an American at a world championship, in an opening-game win over
Brazil.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   REBOUNDS: &LR;  Karnisovas led Lithuania with 20 points in Tuesday's
86-80 overtime loss to Spain, but failed to score in the last 6:31
of regulation or the extra period. With 14:53 left in regulation,
he knocked heads with Spain's Ignacio De Miguel, causing a cut that
was heavily bandaged. ... By registering a 61-60 upset Monday,
Italy became the first squad other than a U.S. Dream Team to defeat
Yugoslavia since it was allowed to rejoin international competition
in 1995.
	   (cl-hjf)
</TEXT>
