<SLUG> BC-India-Killings, 4th Ld-Writethru,0530 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cross-border firing resumes in Kashmir
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS to lede with exchange of gunfire by Indian and
Pakistani armies, killing four people on both sides. &QL; 
 &UR; By BINOO JOSHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JAMMU, India (AP) _ Indian and Pakistani gunners pounded each
other's positions for the sixth straight day Tuesday, killing at
least four people and raising the overall death toll to 92 on both
sides of the disputed frontier in Kashmir.
	   India and Pakistan blamed each other for targeting civilian
areas. Both sides used heavy mortar and artillery fire.
	   India and Pakistan have fought two wars over Kashmir, which is
divided between them. Militants in the Indian-controlled part of
Kashmir want to secede or unite with Muslim Pakistan. The Indian
part of Kashmir is the country's only state with an Islamic
majority.
	   Meanwhile, unidentified assailants attacked a remote village in
the Indian-controlled part of Kashmir and killed 19 people, in what
police Tuesday described as a feud between two groups of Muslim
guerrillas fighting a separatist war in the Himalayan territory
since 1989.
	   Kashmir police chief Gurbachan Jagat said the victims were all
relatives of a militant known as Imtiaz, who is wanted by police
for alleged acts of terrorism.
	   Jagat said the suspected militant belonged to Tehrik-e-Jihad,
one of several groups fighting for Kashmir's separation from India.
	   In another attack, suspected separatists shot three Hindus at
point-blank range early Tuesday in the southern Kashmir district of
Udhampur, police said. Before fleeing, the rebels burned seven
homes in the Hindu village of Balmatkote, 200 kilometers (125
miles) northeast of Jammu, the state's winter capital.
	   The latest killings came a day after suspected Kashmiri
militants shot dead 34 laborers, most or all of them Hindus, in the
adjoining Indian state of Himachal Pradesh.
	   An Indian Defense Ministry statement said two civilians and a
soldier were killed by Tuesday's artillery and mortar fire.
	   Another 10 people, including two army officers, six soldiers and
two civilians, were injured in the firing, the statement said.
	   Pakistani military sources, on customary condition of anonymity,
said one Pakistani civilian was killed and four were injured on
their side of the border.
	   Indian officials said nearly 20,000 people living close to the
border shifted to safer towns. Nearly 150 houses have been
destroyed in three Indian villages.
	   Cross-border gunfire intensified last week when Indian and
Pakistani leaders held inconclusive talks about Kashmir.
	   In New Delhi, Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee told
Parliament on Thursday that the government was taking ``firm
steps'' to deal with militants in Kashmir, the Press Trust of India
reported. Opposition legislators accused the government of failing
to protect its citizens after repeated civilian massacres.
	   Apparently referring to the stalemate over Kashmir, Vajpayee
suggested freezing contentious issues with Pakistan and
concentrating on other problems to help normalize relations _ an
idea Pakistan has rejected in the past.
</TEXT>
