<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinian-Economy,0450 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israel points to brightening picture for Palestinian workers
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo &QL; 
 &UR; By LAURA KING &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   EREZ CROSSING POINT, Gaza Strip (AP) _ In a major turnaround,
Israel has not closed its borders to Palestinian workers once this
year, Israel's liaison with the Palestinians said Tuesday.
	   The Israeli official, Maj. Gen. Yaacov Orr, said that and other
steps in recent months mark a fundamental shift in Israel's
dealings with Palestinian workers, whose earnings from jobs in the
Jewish state are crucial to the Palestinian economy.
	   ``It's a question of opening a window, and then a door,'' Orr
told reporters at the checkpoint between Israel and the Gaza Strip.
``A stronger Palestinian economy is good for Israel.''
	   In the early 1990s, more than 100,000 Palestinians worked in
Israel. But that number has been sharply curtailed in recent years
in response to terror attacks by Islamic militants.
	   Palestinians with jobs in Israel make up only about 20 percent
of the territories' work force, but their wages represent up to 40
percent of total Palestinian earnings.
	   For the past several years, Israel's frequent sealing off of
Gaza and West Bank cost the Palestinian economy millions of dollars
in lost income and export revenues. The territories were closed for
93 days in 1996 and 62 days last year.
	   In 1998, however, the only closures have come on national
holidays when Palestinian workers would not have been on the job in
Israel anyway, Orr said.
	   The closures of previous years were generally in response to
suicide bombings or serious civil unrest in the Palestinian lands.
Orr said this year, Israel has deliberately refrained from closures
even when it was worried about potential security threats.
	   ``It's a calculated risk, but it builds the future life between
our societies,'' he said.
	   The last suicide bombing in Israel was 11 months ago, and the
last major closure was in response to it.
	   Depicting a brightening jobs picture, Orr cited measures
including the issuing of travel permits to 18,000 Palestinian
merchants and business people; permission for about 5,000 workers
to stay overnight in Israel; a small increase in truck traffic in
and out of the territories, and the building of a new Israeli
customs compound to expedite Palestinian exports from Gaza.
	   Palestinians, however, say any improvements must be seen in
light of the severity of restrictions. Fewer than 60,000 of the
nearly 3 million Palestinians in the territories have permission to
travel to Israel, and unemployment is rampant in the West Bank and
Gaza.
</TEXT>
