<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bermuda-Canadian Slaying,0231 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nov. 23 trial set in Bermuda murder of Canadian
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HAMILTON, Bermuda (AP) _ A Bermudan court has set a Nov. 23
court date for a man charged with killing a Canadian teen-ager who
was vacationing on the island.
	   Justis Smith, 19, faces murder charges in the death of
17-year-old Rebecca Middleton of Belleville, Ontario, on July 3,
1996.
	   The trial date was set Monday by Bermuda Supreme Court Judge
Austin Ward.
	   Prosecutors' key witness is Kirk Mundy, who is already serving a
five-year sentence as an accomplice in Middleton's murder.
	   Mundy pleaded guilty in October 1996 in exchange for testimony
against Smith, but Smith's trial was delayed because prosecutors
claimed they later found evidence that Munday also participated in
the killing.
	   The government tried to bring new charges against Mundy, but on
July 6 the British Privy Council, the supreme court for former
British colonies in the Caribbean, rejected prosecutors' request to
try him again.
	   According to testimony at Mundy's previous trial, the two men
picked up Middleton as she waited for a taxi in the early morning
hours after attending a party.
	   Her body was found later along a road. She had been sexually
assaulted and stabbed several times. Mundy claimed Smith killed
Middleton after he walked away from the two.
</TEXT>
