<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Jane's-Myanmar Artillery </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jane's: Myanmar barters rice for artillery pieces
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Myanmar bartered rice for 20 artillery pieces from
North Korea earlier this year, Jane's Defense Weekly reported
Tuesday.
	   The respected military magazine said the deal was the first
direct arms sale since the two countries broke off diplomatic
relations in November 1983, a month after North Korean agents
bombed a South Korean presidential delegation at Rangoon's Martyrs'
Mausoleum. Nineteen people died including four South Korean Cabinet
members.
	   Quoting Rangoon-based diplomatic sources, Jane's said China has
been trying to promote reconciliation between North Korea and
Myanmar, also known as Burma, since last year.
	   The magazine said it was unclear whether the 133 mm towed
artillery pieces involved in the deal were made in North Korea or
Russia. The value of the deal was unknown, it said.
	   ``In either case, China may have played a role in brokering the
agreement,'' Jane's said.
	   (eml-rs) 	   
