w2447 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sudan-PeaceTalks     08-04 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Peace Talks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New round of talks opens to end 15-year civil war in Sudan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ABEBE ANDUALEM &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) _ The definition of what constitutes
southern Sudan and the role of the Muslim religion in that region
topped the agenda as representatives of the Sudanese government and
rebels sat down Tuesday to a new round of peace talks.
	   Government and rebels from the Sudan People's Liberation Army,
whose 15-year civil war has ravaged Sudan and created a famine that
is claiming hundreds of lives a day, are at odds over the
definition of the area to vote on self-determination and Khartoum's
demand for theocratic rule throughout Africa's largest nation.
	   In May, both sides agreed in principle to hold an
internationally supervised referendum on possible independence for
southern Sudan _ but they did not agree on the territory involved.
	   The SPLA has been fighting government troops since 1983 for
greater autonomy for the largely African, Christian and animist
south from the Islamic, Arabized north.
	   More than 1.5 milion people have died due to the fighting and
resultant famines.
	   The talks are held under the auspices of the regional
Inter-Governmental Authority on Development, a six-nation body that
seeks to mediate conflict.
	   Chairing the talks on behalf of IGAD, Kenyan Foreign Miister
Bonya Godana said he hoped ``the contentious issue of the
separation of state and religion, which has been obstructing the
peace process, will be resolved once and for all in a manner
satisfactory to both sides.''
	   Godana said administrative arrangements that would precede a
referendum have yet to be worked out.
	   The parties also disagree on what exactly constitutes southern
Sudan for purposes of the referendum.
	   The SPLA wants to include Southern Kordofan and Southern Blue
Nile provinces, as well as the eastern Nuba Mountains.
	   The two provinces were included in northern Sudan at the time of
independence from British-Egyptian rule in 1956.
	   Sudanese Foreign Minister Mustafa Ismail and Riak Machar, a
former SPLA commander who recently joined the government side, are
heading Khartoum's delegation to the talks.
	   SPLA commander Salva Kir heads the rebel delegation.
	   On Monday Khartoum announced a unilateral, indefinite and
cease-fire in all southern Sudan to allow humanitarian relief to
access the estimated 2.4 million famine victims in the region.
	   The U.N. World Food Program is currently dropping 9,500 tons of
food to the starving and hopes to raise that number to 15,000 tons
in August, in the largest current aid operation in the world.
	   The cease-fire annoucement Monday expanded the scope of a
three-month truce agreed to last month between the government and
the SPLA in the hardest-hit southwestern region of Bahr al-Ghazal.
	   An SPLA official on Monday dismissed the announcement as
pre-talk maneuvering.
	   But British Foreign Office Minister Derek Fatchett, who helped
mediate the original three-month cease-fire, welcomed the
announcement.
	   ``I hope this declaration will also help to facilitate the peace
negotiations on the Sudan ... It is crucial that both sides should
respect the cease-fire and negotiate seriously in Addis Ababa to
bring this long-running conflict to an end,'' he said in a
statement issued in London.
	   (aa/dmc/sl)	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sudan-Peace Talks; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
