<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-House Explosion, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Presumed gas explosion destroys apartment house in Berlin
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with signs of life from room where 13-year-old old boy
is believed buried. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos BER101-102,107 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BERLIN (AP) _ A suspected natural gas explosion destroyed an
apartment house in Berlin early Tuesday, and rescue workers said as
many as nine people may have been buried in the rubble.
	   Among those missing was 13-year-old Sven Tornow, whose parents
and grandparents watched the rescue efforts in tears. Rescue
workers using sonar equipment said they detected signs of a
heartbeat and breathing from the back room where the boy was
believed buried.
	   His father was at work at the time of the blast and his mother
already in a new apartment that the family had planned to move into
on Friday.
	   An elderly couple was also known to be buried under the 7-meter
(23-foot) high pile of debris, and six other residents were
unaccounted for.
	   Rescuers managed to pull a 33-year-old man from the rubble
shortly after the blast and another resident of the four-story
building got out on her own; neither was seriously injured.
	   Almost 12 hours after the blast, no fatalities had been found.
	   Hundreds of police and firefighters searched for signs of life
with dozens of dogs and devices that can detect body heat and
sound.
	   Fire chief Alfred Broemme said the work would continue for at
least a day.
	   He blamed natural gas for the explosion, which ripped the house
off its foundation and sent a huge cloud of dust over the Steglitz
neighborhood. Police, however, were still investigating.
	   Residents of surrounding buildings were temporarily evacuated as
a precaution.
	    &UR; (pfg-gb-im)
</TEXT>
