<HEADLINE>
Guerrilla attacks kill dozens as inauguration nears
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with higher death toll and additional
details on attacks &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo BOG101 &QL; 
 &UR; By JARED KOTLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ Bidding a violent farewell to outgoing
President Ernesto Samper, Colombians rebels have killed 26 people
this week in a show of strength ahead of peace talks with his
successor, authorities said.
	   The attacks by the leftist Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia and the National Liberation Army, killed at least 14
police officers, two secret service members and an unspecified
number of army troops and civilians.
	   The attacks by the two largest rebel groups, which took place in
14 of Colombia's 32 provinces, wounded more than 40 people.
	   A police spokesman said the overall death toll was at least 26,
but the figure apparently did not include a rebel attack Tuesday
which the army says killed seven soldiers guarding a hydroelectric
facility near Medellin, the country's second-largest city.
	   There was no word on rebel casualties.
	   The latest guerrilla onslaught follows weekend attacks by the
National Liberation Army, or ELN, which killed eight people and
included the abduction of a ruling party senator. The assaults
raised doubts about the sincerity of the group, which last month
pledged to scale back kidnappings and attacks on civilians as a
gesture to improve the climate for peace.
	   But in a Tuesday press conference President-elect Andres
Pastrana, who takes office Friday, called the guerrilla upsurge ``a
farewell for the current government'' and vowed to push ahead with
plans to make peace with both groups.
	   Defense Minister Gilberto Echeverri said the guerrillas were
making a show of force in order to obtain leverage in eventual
negotiations.
	   During Samper's term, the rebels gained militarily while largely
shunning peace talks, saying the government was illegitimate. The
guerillas have been fighting for power since the 1960s.
	   Police said the rebels have kidnapped six police officers in
central Antioquia province and had apparently seized 22 army
soldiers in combat in southern Guaviare province, a major
coca-producing region. An army spokesman said he could not confirm
the soldiers' abduction.
	   Rebels also kidnapped two small-town mayors and destroyed four
police stations, the police reported
	   The attacks late-Monday and early-Tuesday began with a bomb
explosion at a secret police barracks in the northern city of
Cucuta which killed two police officers, and a car-bomb explosion
at an army base in Medellin that killed a soldier, authorities
reported.
	   Five civilians and a police officer were reported killed in a
rebel assault late-Monday in Cordoba, a town in northern Bolivar
province.
	   Rebel attacks against army bases in the oil-producing Putumayo
region, bordering with Ecuador, ended Tuesday morning with two
soldiers killed, army chief General Mario Hugo Galan reported.
	   Other rebel actions Tuesday included an attack on an
anti-narcotics police in Guaviare province, reportedly killing two
police officers, and an assault on the Pacific port of Buenaventura
which local authorities said killed three police and a civilian.
</TEXT>
