<HEADLINE>
Russian miners ease blockade of power plant in Far East
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th graf, `Sakhalin Deputy ...,' to
UPDATE with remarks by interior minister; ADDS 2 grafs to UPDATE
with plans for Vorkuta protest, air traffic controllers' strike;
EDITS to tighten. &QL; 
 &UR; By ANNA DOLGOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ With coal supplies dwindling, striking miners
eased their blockade Tuesday of the main power plant on the eastern
island of Sakhalin, agreeing to allow enough coal through to keep
the plant operational.
	   The miners, who are demanding eight months worth of overdue
wages, have been blocking railroad approaches to the plant for
nearly two weeks. They agreed that 25 cars carrying about 1,500
tons of coal could go to the plant daily, the ITAR-Tass and
Interfax news agencies reported.
	   But authorities will continue rationing electricity on the Far
Eastern island, the reports said. Homes and factories on Sakhalin
have been getting only between five and six hours of electricity a
day, it added.
	   Sakhalin Deputy Gov. Ivan Malakhov called the protest a
``terrorist'' act, ITAR-Tass said. But his boss, Gov. Igor
Farkhutdinov, disputed the accusation and revoked an earlier threat
to use force to remove the miners.
	   ``No one is going to use force,'' Farkhutdinov was quoted as
saying. ``It is not terrorism; it is an act of despair.''
	   Interior Minister Sergei Stepashin was quoted by Interfax as
saying he sympathized with the strikers, but warned that police
``naturally will act consistent with the law.''
	   Sakhalin is not connected to Russia's national power grid, so
much of the island is dependent on the plant for electricity. About
650,000 people live on the island.
	   The strike is one of many miners' protests over unpaid wages in
recent months. But the protests have been largely uncoordinated and
in most instances have inflicted only limited damage on the
economy.
	   In other developments Tuesday:
	   _ Ambulance workers in the eastern port city of Vladivostok went
on strike to demand four months of back wages.
	   _ Coal miners in the Chelyabinsk region were blocking the
Argayashskaya power plant, which supplies energy to nuclear-waste
processing enterprise Mayak, the business daily Kommersant said.
Civil defense workers were sent to the region to ensure the safety
of nuclear storage sites, ITAR-Tass reported.
	   _ Miners in the Siberian coal center of Kemerovo lifted all
railroad blockades, allowing the traffic to pass unimpeded for the
first time in at least a month, ITAR-Tass said. Coal companies have
begun paying back wages after a government commission spent two
weeks negotiating with the miners.
	   _ In the coal-mining city of Vorkuta, a group of miners said
they would begin a sit-in demonstration in the central square
beginning Wednesday, ITAR-Tass said.
	   _ The union of Russian air traffic controllers said it would go
on strike Sunday to demand back wages and the resolution of various
other issues, Interfax reported.
	   (ad/gm/ml)
</TEXT>
