<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Czechs, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Retransmitting to fix writethru sequence
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Kohl, Kinkel criticize Czechs on remarks about exiled Germans &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with reaction from Czech vice premier, background on
Zeman comments. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Chancellor Helmut Kohl slammed Czech
Premier Milos Zeman on Tuesday for comparing Germans exiled from
his nation after World War II to radical rightists and communists.
	   ``It is totally unfathomable how a government chief can use such
an absurd and completely unacceptable formulation of words,'' Kohl
told RTL television from his vacation retreat in Austria. ``Either
the man doesn't know what he's talking about or he is using it for
domestic politics.''
	   Zeman's vice premier, Egon Lansky, said told the Czech
Republic's CTK news agency late Tuesday that the ``Czech government
is not going to comment on positions taken by German politicians,
based on totally wrong interpretation of the premier's words.''
	   The dispute arose last month when Zeman spoke out against having
Sudeten Germans as members of a German-Czech dialogue forum,
comparing that to having Czech radical-rightists or communists on
the panel.
	   Zeman noted that panel member Franz Neubauer, leader of a
Sudeten German group, was opposed to the 1997 German-Czech
declaration aimed at easing tensions between the countries, as were
the Czech Republic's Communist and Republican parties.
	   The forum, set up under the declaration, is aimed at reconciling
the two neighbors following decades of hard feelings caused by Nazi
occupation during the World War II and the subsequent expulsion of
some 2.5 million Germans from the Sudetenland region of
then-Czechoslovakia.
	   ``When we finally meet, I will tell him that if that's the
policy of good neighbors, to criticize a group of people who bore
special suffering, like his people suffered under the Germans, you
can't expect that we'll be good neighbors,'' Kohl said.
	   In an interview with the Cologne-based Stadt-Anzeige, Foreign
Minister Klaus Kinkel was a bit more diplomatic than the
chancellor.
	   ``The continuing criticism from certain Czech government
representatives is unnecessary, unfathomable and not helpful,'' the
newspaper quoted Kinkel as saying.
	   But he also said that ``certain shrill comments from Germany,''
also contributed to the dispute.
	   (gb-cb-im)
</TEXT>
