<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Conde </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Spanish prisons system approves weekend leave for banker Conde
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ The government Tuesday agreed to let the
once high-flying banker Mario Conde, convicted of embezzlement, out
of jail two weekends per month.
	   The limited furlough was approved by an eight-member panel at
the Alcala-Meco prison outside Madrid.
	   It is there that Conde is serving a term of four years and two
months for defrauding the Banco Espanol de Credito, known as
Banesto, of 600 million pesetas (dlrs 4.3 million) while he ran the
bank. He began serving the term in late February.
	   A spokeswoman for the National Prison Directorate said the
panel's decision was a routine one for a case such as Conde's,
involving a non-violent crime with a relatively short sentence and
good behavior by the inmate.
	   Conde can choose which weekends he wants to get out on leave,
she said.
	   With his slicked-back hair and jet-set friends, Conde was for
many a garish symbol of the get-rich-quick mentality that
characterized much of the Spanish business community in the 1980s.
	   Now Conde lives alone in an 11-square-meter (120-square-foot)
prison cell, the spokeswoman said. Amenities include a personal
computer, but Conde cannot connect with the Internet, for example.
	   ``He does not have that much access to the outside world,'' she
said.
	   Since December, Conde and 10 other former directors and
associates of Banesto have been on trial on other charges --
misappropriating funds, forgery and price rigging. If convicted,
they face maximum jail sentences of 44 years.
	   dw 	   
</TEXT>
