w2494 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Angola-UNEnvoy     08-04 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Angola-UN Envoy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN peace envoy meets veteran UNITA leader Savimbi in highland
</HEADLINE>
stronghold
 &UR; By CASIMIRO SIONA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LUANDA, Angola (AP) _ A senior U.N. envoy met with veteran
Angolan rebel chief Jonas Savimbi Tuesday, on the fifth day of an
emergency mission to avert a return to civil war.
	   Lakdhar Brahimi refused to comment on his talks with Savimbi _
the undisputed leader of the former rebel movement UNITA.
	   UNITA, a Portuguese acronym for the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola, fought a two-decade civil war against the
government before a U.N.-brokered agreement in 1994 sealed a
tenuous peace.
	   Brahimi's arrival in Angola last Friday was prompted by signs
that the peace process was on the point of collapse, including the
massacre of 100 civilians in a remote village and reported military
buildup on both sides.
	   UNITA's refusal to relinquish control of its rural strongholds
in compliance with the 1994 accord was at the heart of Tuesday's
conversation, UNITA spokesman Horacio Junjuvili told reporters.
	   Savimbi ``reiterated UNITA's position that we will only abandon
the sensitive areas when our political space is guaranteed,''
Junjuvili said, alleging government hostility.
	   UNITA's Secretary-General Paulo Lukamba said that unlike UNITA,
the government was not committed to peace. ``It takes two to
tango'' he said, according to the Portuguese news agency Lusa.
	   On Monday President Jose Eduardo dos Santos assured Brahimi that
his government was committed to the full implementation of the 1994
accord and blamed UNITA for the rising tension.
	   An estimated 500,000 people were killed and many thousands more
maimed by land mines in Angola's conflict, which was fueled by Cold
War geopolitics.
	   Brahimi flew some 300 kilometers (180 miles) southeast of Luanda
to meet Savimbi at his highland headquarters in one of UNITA's
controversial strongholds.
	   After whisking past reporters at Luanda airport awaiting his
return, Brahimi disappeared into talks with diplomats from the
United States, Russia and Portugal, the so-called ``troika'' of
states monitoring the peace process.
	   He was due to give a press conference on Wednesday before
leaving Angola for a tour of neighboring states whose leaders are
close to either Savimbi or Dos Santos.
	   (cs/jt/dw)
</TEXT>
