<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cycling-Riders Return, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Festina riders return in first race since Tour drama
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with second round, Zuelle comment, CORRECTS
number of riders who started to 24 sted 25 in 2nd graf. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) _ Three Swiss cyclists in the Festina
team expelled last month from the Tour de France made a low-key
return to the road Tuesday in the Cross-Lausanne event.
	   Spectators lining the streets of this lakeside city cheered Alex
Zuelle, Laurent Dufaux and Armin Meier, among 24 riders taking part
in the evening race.
	   The crowd was sparse at first but spilled into the streets for
the decisive second of two time trials over the 6.85 kilometer
(4.26 mile) course.
	   Fans cheered and clanged cowbells as the Festina riders set off
over the uphill route, some of it over the cobblestones of
Lausanne's old town.
	   Tour de France winner Marco Pantani of Italy, racing in a yellow
jersey, won both rounds. His overall time was 24 minutes 37
seconds, 1 minute 24 seconds ahead of Colorado's Bobby Julich, who
finished third in the Tour. Switzerland's Pascal Richard was third.	   Festina was thrown off the Tour because its riders were said to
have taken the hormone EPO. Zuelle, Dufaux and Meier were among
those who later admitted taking the drug.
	   ``I'm relieved, because I know now the public is behind me,''
Zuelle told reporters after Tuesday's first round.
	   Local rider Dufaux's name had been painted on the road at the
arrival, and banners along the route welcomed the Festina riders.
	   Dufaux finished fourth, Zuelle 11th and Meier 17th.
	   Lausanne is home to cycling's world body, the International
Cycling Union (UCI), and the International Olympic Committee. Both
have convened meetings this month to discuss the doping issue.
 &UR; (gm)
</TEXT>
