<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Natural Gas,0345 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
French, U.S. companies win natural gas contracts in Mexico
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ A consortium made up by Gaz de France, its
Mexican unit Mexigas and Mexican construction company Bufete
Industrial SA won bidding Tuesday to distribute natural gas in the
state of Mexico.
	   Similarly, Consorcio Energeticos de Mexico formed by Mexico's
Grupo Diavaz, Controladora Comercial e Industrial and U.S.-based
Lone Star Gas International, was awarded the contract to distribute
the fuel in Mexico City, also known as the Federal District.
	   The Mexican capital was divided into two zones for natural gas
distribution, the Federal District zone and the Cuautitlan-Texcoco
zone. The latter covers 28 suburban communities in the adjacent
state of Mexico.
	   Hector Olea, president of the Energy Regulatory Commission, said
Gaz de France won the concession in the Cuautitlan-Texcoco zone
with a bid of dlrs 1.088 per gigacalorie, to reach 374,698 users
after five years.
	   The Gaz de France consortium bid a maximum yield cap of dlrs
1.986 per gigacalorie for Mexico City so the permit was awarded to
the second lowest bid.
	   According to the regulations, bidders can only win one
distribution zone.
	   Olea said Consorcio Energeticos de Mexico bid a maximum yield
cap of dlrs 2.4233 per gigacalorie to reach 439,253 users after
five years.
	   Gas Natural Mexico, of Spain's Gas Natural SDG-Repsol, didn't
win any concession.
	   The permits carry a five-year exclusivity clause. The winners in
each zone will purchase existing distribution infrastructure in the
region owned by Diganamex, a subsidiary of the state monopoly
Petroleos Mexicanos.
	   Mexigas said its consortium plans to invest dlrs 1.2 billion
over the next 10 years in the state of Mexico distribution system.
Revenues from the distribution and marketing of gas in the area are
expected to exceed dlrs 1.8 billion.
	   Planned engineering, procurement and construction services will
total more than dlrs 400 million in the first five years.
</TEXT>
