<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cycling-Doping-Switzerland,0204 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swiss cycling federation calls for single set of doping rules
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BERN, Switzerland (AP) _ The Swiss cycling federation said
Tuesday it has called on the sport's international governing body
to recommend punishments against cyclists who take drugs.
	   Federation president Hugo Steinegger said it was unacceptable
that each national federation had to decide its own sanctions, and
said he expected clear guidelines from the UCI.
	   The call from the Swiss Cyclists and Motorcyclists Federation
comes as the International Cycling Union (UCI), the sport's world
body, prepares for a ``brainstorming conference'' this week between
its top officials, cyclists and team managers to examine the issue
of doping.
	   It comes in the wake of the drug scandals which dogged this
year's Tour de France, where the Festina team was expelled because
its riders were said to have taken the hormone EPO.
	   Swiss team members Alex Zuelle, Laurent Dufaux and Armin Meier
were among those who later admitted taking the drug.
	   Later Tuesday, Zuelle, Dufaux and Meier are expected to take
part in the Cross-Lausanne invitational event, their first race
since the Tour de France. 	   
</TEXT>
