<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq, 9th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Saddam approves `measures' to shake off sanctions
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Saddam approving steps; statement &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos staffing
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ President Saddam Hussein Tuesday approved
``a series of measures'' aimed at shaking off U.N. sanctions
following the collapse of disarmament talks with weapons
inspectors, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
	   The decision was taken at an emergency meeting of the powerful
Revolutionary Command Council and the ruling Baath party, chaired
by Saddam, the official news agency said.
	   ``The meeting adopted a series of measures that will be
announced soon,'' INA said without saying what those steps are
likely to be. It also said a national debate on confronting the
sanctions will begin immediately.
	   The developments came after chief U.N. weapons inspector Richard
Butler left Baghdad Tuesday, saying Iraq is refusing to conduct
further disarmament talks.
	   The Iraqi stand has thrown into uncertainty the future of the
U.N. program to eliminate Iraq's arsenal of mass destruction such
as biological and chemicals arms and long-range missiles.
	   INA said the Iraqi leadership will continue its meetings ``to
adopt further needed measures to protect Iraq's national interests
and put an end to the injustice imposed on it.''
	   Iraq claims it has destroyed all its illegal weapons and has
nothing more to reveal. But until Butler's U.N. Special Commission,
a large group of international weapons experts, certifies that, the
Security Council cannot lift the sanctions.
	   UNSCOM has repeatedly said that Iraq still needs to disclose a
lot of information about its weaponry.
	   The widely disparate stands led to the collapse of Butler's
talks Monday with Iraq's chief negotiator, Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz.
	   Aziz demanded that UNSCOM give it a clean bill of health on its
weapons program.
	   ``I told him that I cannot fulfill your demand because I don't
have the evidence,'' Butler told The Associated Press in Bahrain,
where he arrived en route to New York. ``After I said that to him,
Aziz replied, `Then we can't talk any further,''' Butler said.
	   Butler's political adviser, Gustavo Zlauvinen, said Aziz also
refused to accept a work schedule aimed at increasing the pace of
weapons inspection work.
	   ``The talks were getting nowhere,'' he told the AP.
	   The sanctions were imposed after Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait,
which led to the 1991 Gulf War.
	   In Washington, State Department spokesman James Rubin called
Iraq's refusal to hold more talks ``disturbing.''
	   Saddam has ``shot himself in the foot'' by mishandling a chance
to end the sanctions, he said. ``Iraq has only harmed itself,'' he
said.
	   Iraq's latest stand threatens to bring to a halt UNSCOM's
seven-year search for the illegal weapons, a mission often
disrupted by confrontations between Iraqi and U.N. officials.
	   In New York, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said the next
step will be determined after Butler reports to the Council on
Thursday.
	   However, INA earlier quoted Butler as saying the problem has not
become a crisis. ``It is imperative not to overdramatize the
situation,'' he was quoted as saying.
	   Still, experts think that the Iraq-U.N. relationship is heading
for trouble.
	   ``Confrontation is looming, definitely,'' Tim Trevan, who served
on the U.N. inspections team from 1992 to 1995, was quoted as
saying on BBC radio.
	   The previous crisis was over Iraq's refusal to allow weapons
inspectors into Saddam's palaces, bringing the country close to
being attacked by U.S. and British forces. Iraq relented in a Feb.
23 accord with Annan.
	   After that U.N.-Iraq disputes appeared to be easing until a U.S.
military lab reported in June that it found traces of deadly VX
nerve gas on fragments of Iraqi missile warheads it tested.
	   Iraq had claimed that although it developed VX it never put the
chemical on missiles.
	   Zlauvinen, Butler's adviser, said the discovery of VX opened key
issues while Iraq's biological weapons program continues to have
``many loopholes.''
	   ``It's still a big mess,'' he said.
	   The INA statement issued after the RCC meeting reiterated Iraq's
old accusation that Butler, an Australian, is a U.S. puppet.
 &UR; vars/lb/vj 	   
</TEXT>
