<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iran-Missile,0363 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iran: New missile a tool to defend the Muslim world
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ A new medium-range missile that Iran tested
last month is meant to defend the Muslim world and other oppressed
countries, a senior military commander said Tuesday.
	   Brig. Gen. Mohammad Bagher Qalibaf's comments are the first time
that Iran has indicated a religious motive for developing the
Shahab-3 missile, whose range of 1,300 kilometers (800 miles) makes
it capable of hitting Israel and U.S. troops stationed in Saudi
Arabia.
	   Iran is staunchly opposed to any peace with Israel and calls for
its annihilation. It also backs guerrilla groups fighting Israeli
troops in South Lebanon.
	   In an interview with the official Islamic Republic News Agency,
Qalibaf said experience has shown that Muslims' pacifism has only
made enemies more aggressive. But he added that Iran does not seek
war and strengthening its defenses is only aimed at deterring
enemies.
	   Qalibaf is the commander of the air wing of the Islamic
Revolutionary Guard Corps, a separate force in the military with a
strength of about 120,000 men.
	   Qalibaf said Shahab-3 is the product of an arms development
program that Iran began during the 1980-88 war with Iraq.
	   He rejected claims by the United States that Russia helped Iran
build the missile.
	   ``The West's sensationalism and propaganda ... come at a time
when the West possesses 95 percent of the enriched plutonium in the
world _ enough for producing 60,000 bombs and warheads,'' Qalibaf
said.
	   On Sunday, Qalibaf disclosed that the Shahab-3 ballistic missile
is 16 meters (53 feet) long and can travel at a speed of 7,000 kph
(4,320 mph) carrying a one-ton warhead. Its cruising altitude is
250 kilometers (155 miles) above sea level.
	   The United States says Iran is working on a long-range missile
that could be deployed in two to five years, and has pledged to
redouble its efforts to curb the transfer of technology Iran needs
to develop it.
	   But Iranian President Mohammad Khatami said Saturday that his
country is determined to continue strengthening its armed forces,
regardless of international concern.
</TEXT>
