<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Track-DN Galan,0458 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sunny day could see records fall at DN Galan, athletes say
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ED McCULLOUGH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) _ A late afternoon breeze chased away
dark clouds and intermittent rain, raising athletes' hopes for
sunshine, fast times and possible world records at Wednesday's DN
Galan Grand Prix.
	   ``The hotter it is, the better I run,'' sprinter Ato Boldon of
Trinidad said at a Tuesday news conference. Last year, he won the
100- and 200-meter races in the meet at Stockholm's 1912 Olympic
Stadium.
	   ``It's going to be very fast, very fast,'' predicted Maurice
Greene of the United States. He finished second to his training
partner and friend, Boldon, in both events last year. ``He got
lucky,'' Greene said with a laugh.
	   This year's field once again is crowded with champions in their
prime, aging record holders and rising stars, each dreaming of
breakthrough performances.
	   ``When I put the spikes on my feet and step on the track ... I
know I am very fast ... and I don't worry about anyone else,'' said
Algeria's Noureddine Morceli, the world record holder and Olympic
gold medalist in the mile.
	   Wilson Boit Kipketer of Kenya said, ``I feel in my mind that I
can run a sub 8-minute'' time in the 3,000-meter steeplechase.
	   While several seconds off the world record of 7:55.72, that
still would be the best time ever in the stadium, where 83 world
records have been set _ more than at any other.
	   Some of the dozens of athletes competing in 18 events have had
their best moments at Olympic Stadium. Javelin thrower Steve
Backley of Great Britain had a world record throw in 1990.
	   He was a teen-ager then and ``throwing came easily,'' he
recalled. Then came the injuries, and training and competitions
became more like work than fun.
	   Still, nearly a decade later, ``I'm probably better now than I
was then, and I'm throwing further,'' Backley said. He'd like to
add an Olympic gold medal to the silver (1996) and bronze (1992)
already in his collection.
	   ``That's the one that's missing,'' he said. ``It's always the
medals that count, if you ask the athletes.''
	   Another veteran, sprinter Merlene Ottey of Jamaica, got a little
testy when asked, yet again, whether she's finally contemplating
retirement.
	   ``I was ranked No. 2 in the world last year, so that wasn't a
good reason to quit,'' she snapped, adding she feels energized by
competition from America's Marion Jones, top ranked last year in
the 100 meters.
	   ``Marion, running well, brings out the best in me,'' said Ottey,
37, who is posting faster times these days than when she swept
first place in each of her two previous entries in the DN Galan,
way back in 1989 and 1991. 	   
</TEXT>
