<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Iraq </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With BC-Iraq
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Netanyahu says Israel following events in Iraq closely

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said Tuesday
that Israel is closely monitoring events in Iraq which announced it
was cutting off talks with the United Nations over weapons
inspections.
	   ``The entire world is worried about this question,'' Netanyahu
told reporters. ``We, like everyone else, are watching this thing
carefully and we know what to do.''
	   Until the U.N. Special Commission certifies that Iraq is free of
weapons of mass destruction, the U.N. Security Council will not
lift economic sanctions imposed after Iraq's 1990 invasion of
Kuwait, which led to the Persian Gulf War.
	   Iraq fired 39 Scud missiles with conventional warheads at Israel
during the 1991 war.
	   In February a wave of panic swept the Israeli public when the
chief U.N. weapons inspector said that Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein
could wipe out Tel Aviv with biological weapons.
	   A recent missile test by Iran has also received prominent media
coverage in Israel. At a meeting of the Israeli legislature's
Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee, Netanyahu revealed new
information about the Shahab-3 missile, which is capable of
reaching Israel, Israel TV reported.
	   According to the report, Netanyahu said the missile can propel
itself for 100 seconds before its motor burns out and that Iran is
planning to assemble a fleet of the missiles.
 &UR; dk-dl 	   
</TEXT>
