r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Afghanistan-Fighting 2ndLd-Writethru   08-04 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Fighting, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0461 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taliban readies for attack on opposition stronghold
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS with new details. TRIMS. &QL; 
 &UR; By ZAHEERUDDIN ABDULLAH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) _ The Taliban religious army said they
launched a preemptive strike Tuesday capturing a town from
Afghanistan's opposition in preparation for an advance on the key
northern city of Mazar-e-Sharif.
	   Taliban spokesman Abdul Hay Muttayn said his fighters took the
town of Saripul, about 100 kilometers (60 miles) southwest of
Mazar-e-Sharif, after a one-hour battle Tuesday. Taliban radio
later reported its troops were in full control of the surrounding
province, also called Saripul.
	   Muttayn said the opposition, which had retreated a few
kilometers (miles) south to Saripul after losing their stronghold
of Shebergan on Sunday, had been re-grouping for a counterattack.
	   The reported Taliban victory headed-off the counterattack, which
could have slowed its march on Mazar-e-Sharif, one of the
opposition's few remaining strongholds.
	   The Taliban already control most of Afghanistan and appear
poised to take the rest of the country. Their leaders have imposed
a strict version of Islamic law in territory they control. Since
capturing the Afghan capital, Kabul, in 1996, Taliban officials
have barred girls from school and confined most women to their
homes.
	   The anti-Taliban alliance is made up mostly of Afghanistan's
religious and ethnic minorities. The factions occasionally turn on
each other, weakening their ability to fight the Taliban.
	   The Red Cross evacuated the last eight foreign aid workers from
Mazar-e-Sharif to neighboring Pakistan Tuesday, fearing a repeat of
the street fighting and looting that erupted last year when the
Taliban briefly held the city. Hundreds of residents were
reportedly fleeing the city.
	   Most international organizations had pulled their workers out of
Mazar-e-Sharif last year.
	   Taliban troops engaged in minor skirmishes Tuesday as they
advanced to 20 kilometers (12 miles) west of Mazar-e-Sharif,
according to both the Taliban and an opposition source in
Mazar-e-Sharif who refused to give his name.
	   Muttayn said the Taliban was now pausing to build bunkers and
take other measures to shore up defenses. It was unclear when it
would attempt to capture Mazar-e-Sharif.
	   Taliban radio reported late Monday that Taliban fighters were
also east of Mazar-e-Sharif _ just 40 kilometers (25 miles) away,
within rocket range of the airport.
	   The opposition source said local residents were revolting
against warlord Rashid Dostum, a leader in the fractious
anti-Taliban coalition, allowing the Taliban to advance.
	   Dostum's whereabouts were unclear Tuesday.
</TEXT>
