<SLUG> BC-Angola-UN Envoy,0193 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN peace envoy meets UNITA leader Savimbi
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LUANDA, Angola (AP) _ A senior U.N. envoy met with Angolan rebel
chief Jonas Savimbi Tuesday, on the fifth day of an emergency
mission to avert a return to civil war.
	   Lakdhar Brahimi refused to comment on his talks with Savimbi _
the leader of the UNITA rebel movement.
	   UNITA fought a two-decade civil war against the government of
the former Portuguese colony before a U.N.-brokered peace agreement
in 1994 brought a tenuous halt to the fighting.
	   Brahimi's arrival in Angola last Friday was prompted by signs
that the peace process was close to collapse.
	   UNITA's refusal to give up its rural strongholds in compliance
with the 1994 accord was at the heart of Tuesday's conversation,
UNITA spokesman Horacio Junjuvili said.
	   Savimbi ``reiterated UNITA's position that we will only abandon
the sensitive areas when our political space is guaranteed,''
Junjuvili said.
	   On Monday, President Jose Eduardo dos Santos assured Brahimi
that his government was committed to the full implementation of the
1994 accord and blamed UNITA for the rising tension.
</TEXT>
