<HEADLINE>
East Timor talks begin at United Nations
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan launched
talks on the troubled territory of East Timor on Tuesday, meeting
with the foreign ministers of Portugal and Indonesia.
	   U.N. special envoy for East Timor Jamsheed Marker is chairing
talks this week aimed at brokering a peace deal for East Timor,
ruled by Portugal for centuries before Indonesia invaded in 1975.
	   Marker, who has spent years searching for a peace deal, helped
prepare a U.N. working paper which cites promises for reform by
President B.J. Habibie as reason for optimism.
	   In a gesture of good will, Habibie withdrew about 400 of 12,000
Indonesian troops from the territory last week. Another 600 are
scheduled to leave this month.
	   Discussion at this week's meeting is expected to be dominated by
an offer from Habibie to grant a form of autonomy, but not outright
independence, to East Timor, a half-island territory about 2,000
kilometers (1,200 miles) east of Jakarta.
</TEXT>
