w2652 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Lithuania-AmberRoom     08-04 0218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lithuania-Amber Room,0218 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Searchers for Amber Room find cache of metal buried in seabed
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VILNIUS, Lithuania (AP) _ Searchers for the Amber Room, a
long-lost Russian treasure, were investigating a cache of metal
buried in the seabed off Lithuania's coast on Tuesday.
	   A crew of German treasure hunters has been combing a beach near
the town of Preila for months in hopes of discovering the czarist
Russia treasure, which disappeared during World War II.
	   The searchers this week detected a large amount of metal buried
about 20 meters (65 feet) offshore. On Tuesday, they were building
a watertight enclosure at the site to help with the search.
	   The Amber Room, a series of ornate panels, were a gift to
Russia's Peter the Great from Prussian Emperor Friedrich Wilhelm I.
	   The Nazis took the panels from Leningrad, now St. Petersburg, in
1941 and the German government claims they were destroyed during
the 1945 Soviet invasion of Konigsberg, now the Russian enclave of
Kaliningrad. Moscow has long insisted that the Nazis hid the
treasure.
	   The treasure hunters have been following leads provided by an
80-year-old former area resident who says he saw Nazi officers
carrying mysterious boxes off a warship in 1944 and then burying
them along the shore near his home.
</TEXT>
