<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0698 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
and Bolivia.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with NEW items from Mexico, Panama, Cuba
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Estelle weakened from hurricane to tropical
storm status Tuesday, churning maximum winds of 65 mph (105 kph) as
it moved farther out into the Pacific.
	   Estelle's maximum sustained winds fell below the hurricane
threshold of 74 mph (119 kph) overnight, the U.S. Hurricane Center
in Miami reported.
	   The storm was located about 1,300 miles (2,100 kilometers)
west-southwest of the tip of the Baja California Peninsula on
Tuesday and moving to the west at 14 mph (22 kph), the center said.
	   Estelle was expected to continue weakening as it moved over
cooler waters.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ An opposition party took to the streets of
Mexico City on Tuesday to whip up resistance to a dlrs 65 billion
bank bailout program whose beneficiaries allegedly include bankers,
corporations and rich businessmen.
	   The campaign of leafleting and a symbolic ``crucifixion'' of
bank debtors in the city's main square came hours after the
Democratic Revolution Party released a list of businesses whose
multimillion-dollar loans were paid off by the government under the
bailout.
	   The list contained few surprises _ many of the insolvent Mexican
companies listed have already taken over by the government _ but
still stirred outrage at the huge amounts of the loans in the
program, known as Fobaproa.
	   Fobaproa's directors said that the released list was not
accurate and insisted that the fund was not meant to benefit the
rich, but rather to protect the savers.
	   The Fobaproa program bought up loans from failing Mexican banks
in the wake of the 1994 peso devaluation, which forced many debtors
into arrears.
	   However, critics say that besides the genuinely bad loans, there
are many cases of bank fraud, insider-lending by bank officers, and
millionaires and companies who simply decided not to pay back money
they borrowed.
	   ___
	   PANAMA CITY (AP) _ A moderate earthquake rattled the border
region between Panama and Costa Rica, causing minor damage but no
injuries, officials said Tuesday.
	   The 5.0-magnitude quake occurred Monday night and was centered
50 kms (30 miles) west of Puerto Armuelles, a Panamanian town near
the border, the University of Panama reported.
	   The temblor caused minor damage to aqueducts in Puerte
Armuelles, authorities reported.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ U.S. entrepreneurs hoping to make investment
contacts in Cuba will meet Cuban businessmen in Mexico and on the
communist island next month, the Prensa Latina news agency reported
Tuesday.
	   Kirby Jones, an American who organized a similar conference in
March, said the upcoming meeting will give delegates an opportunity
to speak directly with high-level Cuban authorities and
representatives of the private sector, the government news agency
said, citing a report by Cuba's Radio Reloj.
	   Jones said businessmen from French, Israeli and U.S. companies
will attend the conference, which starts Sept. 9 in the Mexican
resort of Cancun and conclude two days later in Havana, according
to the report monitored in Mexico City.
	   In March, more than 50 U.S. business people participated in a
weekend conference carefully designed to keep them from violating
the 37-year-old U.S. economic embargo which bans them from spending
money in the communist island.
	   ___
	   LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) _ President Hugo Banzer replaced his
finance and housing ministers Tuesday.
	   Finance Minister Herbert Muller replaced Edgar Millares, who
resigned for personal reasons.
	   The new Housing Minister Amparo Ballivian, a former World Bank
Employee, replaced Javier Escobar, who resigned after his
Conscience of Nationhood party was thrown out of the ruling
government coalition Monday.
	   The cabinet shuffle took place two days before Banzer celebrates
his first year in office.
	   Muller, an energy minister from 1989 to 1993, was a Bolivian
representative for the Argentine energy company YPF. Ballivian had
been under-secretary of foreign commerce until Tuesday's
appointment.
</TEXT>
