<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Colombia-Guerrillas, 1st Ld-Writethru,0192 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Guerrilla attacks kill dozens as inauguration nears
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with higher death toll and additional details on
attacks &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo BOG101 &QL; 
 &UR; By JARED KOTLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ Bidding a violent farewell to outgoing
President Ernesto Samper, Colombians rebels have killed at least 40
people this week in a show of strength ahead of peace talks with
his successor, authorities said.
	   The attacks by the leftist Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia and the National Liberation Army killed at least 17 police
officers and 23 army soldiers and civilians in attacks in nearly
half of the country's 32 provinces, said police operations chief
General Alfredo Salgado. He said more than 30 guerrillas died in
the fighting, which also at least 48 police and 30 army soldiers
wounded.
	   He said seven soldiers died in a rebel attack on a hydroelectric
plant near Medellin, the country's second largest city, and an
attack on a police anti-narcotics base in southern Guaviare
province killed six police officers and three army soldiers.
	   The latest, graf 6 pvs
</TEXT>
