<SLUG> BC-Cuba-US-Trade,0183 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. group plans 2nd investment conference in Cuba
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ U.S. entrepreneurs hoping to make investment
contacts in Cuba will meet Cuban businessmen in Mexico and on the
communist island next month, the Prensa Latina news agency reported
Tuesday.
	   Kirby Jones, an American who organized a similar conference in
March, said the upcoming meeting would give delegates an
opportunity to speak directly with high-level Cuban authorities and
representatives of the private sector, the government news agency
said citing a report by Cuba's Radio Reloj.
	   Jones said businessmen from U.S., French and Israeli companies
would attend the conference, which will begin Sept. 9 in the
Mexican resort of Cancun and conclude two days later in Havana,
according to the report monitored in Mexico City.
	   In March, more than 50 U.S. business people participated in a
weekend conference carefully designed to keep them from violating
the 37-year-old U.S. economic embargo which bans them from spending
money in the communist island.
