<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Caricom-Castro,0230 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Caribbean Community secretary-general praises Castro visit
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) _ Edwin Carrington, the
secretary-general of the Caribbean Community trade bloc, on Tuesday
praised Fidel Castro's tour of the region as a ``healthy'' move
toward closer relations with Cuba.
	   ``I think it is a very important initiative by the Cuban leader
and a very timely initiative by the Community to have him visit the
member states,'' Carrington said.
	   Castro ended a six-day tour of Jamaica, Barbados and Grenada on
Monday. During rallies, he urged Caribbean countries to oppose the
U.S. embargo of the communist island and promised to broaden trade
and economic development ties in the region.
	   Carrington said the visit would bolster support within the
Caribbean Community for Cuban membership in the African, Pacific
and Caribbean States, a group of former European colonies that
receive trade perks from the European Union.
	   ``We have supported the (ACP) application very strongly and we
are extremely pleased to see efforts being made to bring Cuba
closer to the rest of the Caribbean countries,'' Carrington said.
``I could think of nothing more healthy and helpful at this time
for the development of Caribbean relationships.''
	   Cuba, a former Spanish colony, is eager to win European trade
protections for its citrus exports.
</TEXT>
