<HEADLINE>
East Timor talks begin at United Nations
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES in grafs 3, 4 with first day talks over, quote from
Portuguese foreign minister &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan launched
talks on the troubled territory of East Timor on Tuesday, meeting
with the foreign ministers of Portugal and Indonesia.
	   U.N. special envoy for East Timor Jamsheed Marker is chairing
talks this week aimed at brokering a peace deal for East Timor,
ruled by Portugal for centuries before Indonesia invaded in 1975.
	   ``In comparison with other talks, this time we have some
progress,'' Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime Gama said after the
first day of talks concluded.
	   He described Marker's proposals as ``substantive,'' but would
not elaborate.
