<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Paralyzed Gymnast,0569 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Another gymnast, paralyzed at 17, is prospering
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo FX103 &QL; 
 &UR; By ROB GLOSTER &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) _ As Adriana Duffy steers her wheelchair
through the lunchtime business crowd, she passes a health club
filled with young stockbrokers riding stationary bikes.
	   That once was a numbingly routine activity for her. Now it's
impossible.
	   At the 1989 World Gymnastics Championships in Stuttgart,
Germany, Duffy was competing for Puerto Rico when she slipped
during a practice vault, dislocated her neck and was left a
quadriplegic at age 17.
	   Another 17-year-old now lies in a New York hospital. Doctors are
pessimistic that Chinese gymnast Sang Lan, seriously injured two
weeks ago during a warmup vault at the Goodwill Games, will walk
again.
	   Duffy knows exactly what Sang will face _ the pain, the pity,
the embarrassed stares, and the emotional and physical barriers.
	   But Duffy also knows the possibilities.
	   She went on to get her degree at Stanford, graduated from Yale
Law School, and is an attorney at one of San Francisco's biggest
firms.
	   Duffy hopes that Sang, who is recovering from delicate spinal
fusion surgery, discovers that life doesn't end in a wheelchair.
	   ``I don't mind being an inspiration for her, but there's sort of
a negative flipside to it, which is that there are diminished
expectations for what you can do and the kind of life you can
have,'' she said.
	   ``People are inspired because they think your life has reason to
be really horrible, and it's like totally amazing that you can have
a decent or good or wonderful life.''
	   Confined to a wheelchair, Duffy is unable to make a fist or grip
a fork naturally. She uses only her thumbs to type legal documents.
	   Now 26, Duffy has followed the news of Sang's accident with
discomfort _ not because it reminds her of her own injury, but
because of the way the Chinese athlete's future is portrayed.
	   ``The coverage tends to be very negative, about how it's such a
tragedy, how horrible that her life is over,'' Duffy said. ``I
don't like to think of it that way. I sort of cringe at that.''
	   The maneuver she was practicing in 1989 was a routine one,
featuring a hand spring and a front somersault. Her hands slipped.
As soon as she landed, she realized it was bad.
	   She moved to a rehab center in Southern California. While she
was there, she attended a gymnastics meet at Cal State-Fullerton
that included her former Stanford teammates.
	   Rather than watching from a distance, Duffy got as close as
possible to the action.
	   ``She sat at the end of the vaulting runway in a wheelchair. She
was literally a couple of feet from the landing mat,'' said Breck
Greenwood, the Stanford women's gymnastics coach at the time.
	   After a few months at home in San Juan, she returned to school
and became president of the Stanford Intersorority Council. She
also became an advocate for disabled students, helping persuade
Stanford housing officials to modify dorms to accommodate students
using wheelchairs.
	   ``I think how fast she recovered was pretty much the amazing
thing,'' Greenwood said. ``She just decided, `OK, I'll be a good
student and run for student government and wow them like that.'''
	   Duffy said: ``My life is full, I've done a lot of things ... I
don't feel any desire to have anybody else's life.''
</TEXT>
