<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Malaysia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore refutes Malaysian allegations over checkpoint dispute
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JONATHAN DRAKE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Singapore has hit back at Malaysia, rebutting
its northern neighbors allegations in an ongoing border dispute
between two ASEAN allies.
	   A Home Affairs Ministry spokesman on Tuesday refuted five
assertions made by Malaysia since Singapore relocated its
immigration, customs and quarantine post on Saturday against the
wishes of its larger neighbor, state-run television reported.
	   Malaysia has condemned the move, maintaining its immigration
officers at the original Tanjong Pagar railway station bordering
the city-state's financial district in the south of the island, a
move Singapore has deemed unlawful and counterproductive.
	   The increasingly acrimonious argument is significant against the
backdrop of progressively souring relations between the Southeast
Asian neighbors.
	   A number of unresolved, perennial issues continue to plague
jittery relations, from straightforward land disputes to the sale
of water, which resource-scarce Singapore imports liberally from
Malaysia.
	   But the nations are also allies, belonging to the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations, a key regional body that also groups
Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Myanmar, the Philippines, Thailand and
Vietnam.
	   In their blunt comments, the Home Affairs Ministry said
unsubstantiated allegations from Malaysia blaming Singapore are
nothing new, and the city-state can only conclude that Malaysian
leaders do not know the facts or have chosen to disregard them.
	   Refuting claims that the relocation was sudden, unilateral and
deliberately timed when Malaysia was facing an economic crisis, the
spokesman reiterated that the intention to shift the checkpoint was
announced as early as 1989.
	   The spokesman also noted that allegations of Singapore's
arrogance and insensitivity over the issue were typical when
Malaysia has no logical arguments to offer.
	   He said that Singapore has every right to locate its
immigrations facilities at the border, while Malaysia's about-face
on the issue last year and its demand to illegally remain at the
old checkpoint were themselves arrogant and insensitive.
	   The ministry described the accusation of a ploy to seize the
Malaysian-owned land where Tanjong Pagar is located as completely
unfounded, and argued that the dispute was a result of Malaysia
repeatedly changing its position on the issue.
	   Finally, the spokesman described as absurd Malaysian claims that
the Singapore media had an agenda to incite Singaporeans to hate
Malaysia.
	   He noted that the Malaysian media, for their part, had generally
not reported on Singapore's statements while the city-state's media
had done so.
	   The spokesman said that Malaysia has promised to provide within
three months its legal arguments to prove its right to remain at
the old checkpoint. 	   
</TEXT>
