<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0737 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) _ Troops loyal to President Laurent Kabila
battled with rebellious Tutsi fighters Tuesday at opposite ends of
Congo in an uprising aimed at toppling the president's 14-month-old
regime. Gunfire was reported in the eastern town of Bukavu near the
border with Rwanda, said local aid workers. A provincial official
said the rebels were in control of the town, although some reports
indicated fighting there continued. Banyamulenge Tutsis and Rwandan
soldiers led the uprising against Kabila, accusing him of
widespread corruption and government mismanagement. In the
southwestern village of Kitona, fighting was reported at the town's
main military base, a government spokesman said. It was unclear who
was in control of the base in Kitona, but Kabila has vowed to crush
the uprising and called on his supporters for help. (CONGO)
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Waterlogged levees along China's flood-swollen
Yangtze River have started to collapse, wreaking death and
destruction on a massive scale, state media said Tuesday.
Torrential rains in southwest Sichuan province also have triggered
flooding that killed at least 20 people, pushing the known death
toll from floods caused by unusually heavy and early summer rains
this year to 1,288. With a tropical storm expected, the threat
mounted of further breaches along the already weakened levees that
protect millions of people and rich farmland from the Yangtze, the
world's third-longest river. (CHINA-FLOODS)
	   KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) _ The Taliban religious army said it
launched a pre-emptive strike Tuesday, capturing a town from
Afghanistan's opposition in preparation for an advance on the key
northern city of Mazar-e-Sharif. Taliban spokesman Abdul Hay
Muttayn said his fighters took the town of Saripul, about 100
kilometers (60 miles) southwest of Mazar-e-Sharif, after a one-hour
battle Tuesday. Taliban radio reported its troops were in full
control of the surrounding province, also called Saripul. Muttayn
said the opposition, which had retreated a few kilometers (miles)
south to Saripul after losing their stronghold of Shebergan on
Sunday, had been re-grouping for a counterattack. The reported
Taliban victory headed-off the counterattack, which could have
slowed its march on Mazar-e-Sharif, one of the opposition's few
remaining strongholds. (AFGHANISTAN-FIGHTING)
	   QIREZ, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Ethnic Albanian refugees swarmed a
truck laden with food, infant formula and medicine Tuesday,
desperately seeking help after Serb police permitted aid workers
into a besieged valley in Kosovo. Serb police have been barring or
slowing aid groups and diplomatic observers from reaching tens of
thousands of refugees driven from villages in the Yugoslav
province, where ethnic Albanian rebels are fighting for
independence. The International Committee of the Red Cross reached
the valley near Qirez, but fighting stymied plans by U.N. refugee
workers to send an aid convoy to Malisevo _ a former Kosovo
Liberation Army stronghold that fell to the Serbs in the current
offensive. Refugee agency spokesman Kris Janowski compared the
situation in Kosovo to what happened in 1992 in Bosnia, when
Bosnian Serb forces embarked on a policy of trying to empty areas
of their non-Serb populations. (YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO)
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Hours after the chief U.N. inspector left
Baghdad in a dispute over arms talks, President Saddam Hussein
approved a plan Tuesday that Iraq hopes will end crippling economic
sanctions. Richard Butler, who heads the U.N. Special Commission,
left Iraq on Tuesday, saying the government was refusing further
disarmament talks _ throwing into uncertainty the future of the
U.N. program to eliminate Iraq's arsenal of mass destruction. The
Iraqi News Agency reported that Saddam approved measures aimed at
ending the sanctions, but did not say what they were. Butler said
the impasse stemmed from Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz's demand
that Iraq be given a clean bill of health on its weaponry. ``I told
him that I cannot fulfill your demand because I don't have the
evidence,'' Butler said after flying into Bahrain en route to New
York. ``After I said that to him, Aziz replied, `Then we can't talk
any further.''' (IRAQ) 	   
</TEXT>
