<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0704 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 0000 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Stocks plunged Tuesday, with selling picking up
in the final minutes of trading as the Dow industrials tumbled
299.43 points in the third-biggest point loss ever. The Dow Jones
industrial average closed at 8,487.31 _ down 3.4 percent, in a
selloff that brought its losses to 9.1 percent, or 850.66 points,
from the record 9,337.97 of July 17. record. The accelerating slide
Tuesday, extending big losses of the past 2 1/2 weeks, raised
questions about the staying power of a bull market that had seen
the Dow nearly quadruple since October 1990. (US-CLOSING STOCKS)
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ A key gauge of future economic activity fell in
June for the second month in a row, caused largely by the strikes
at General Motors Corp. and signaling a further slowing of the U.S.
economy. But the Conference Board said it is premature to say a
recession is looming. The private business research group reported
Tuesday that its Index of Leading Economic Indicators for June
stood at 105, down 0.2 percent from the previous month. The decline
was in line with economists' expectations. The measure slipped 0.1
percent in May. Earlier, the board had reported it held steady
during that month. The back-to-back declines were the first since a
string of five declines in January through May of 1995, and the
Conference Board said they signaled ``slower growth ahead and only
a slight risk of a contraction.'' (US-ECONOMY)
	   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) _ KLM Royal Dutch Airlines said
Tuesday its net profit for the first quarter of 1998 rose 12
percent to 212 million guilders (dlrs 106 million) but was dented
by Asia's economic crisis. The results for the three months ended
June 30 were supported by a one-off gain, lower costs and improved
yields but hurt by ``trading conditions in the Asia-Pacific
region,'' the airline said. It didn't elaborate. KLM said the net
profit figure didn't include subsidiary Martinair, and that
operating profit would have risen 15 percent to 285 million
guilders (dlrs 142.5 million) if it had. Overall operating income
rose 5.2 percent to 262 million guilders (dlrs 131 million), at the
low end of analysts' expectations. (NETHERLANDS-EARNS-KLM)
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ The International Monetary Fund has
agreed in principle to allow Thailand to run a public sector
deficit of 3.5 percent of gross domestic product for the next
fiscal year, the finance minister said Tuesday. Tarrin
Nimmanhaeminda said after a Cabinet meeting that an IMF team
conducting a quarterly review of Thailand's dlrs 17.2 billion
economic rescue package had agreed to Thai deficit proposals. They
would allow the government to have a budget deficit equivalent to
1.5 percent of gross domestic product for the year to Sept. 30,
1999, plus a state enterprise investment budget deficit of 2
percent of GDP. (THAILAND-IMF)
	   LONDON (AP) _ British Petroleum PLC said Tuesday its quarterly
profits fell 20 percent to 695 million pounds (dlrs 1.16 billion)
as it suffered the effects of a severely depressed oil market. BP
said its pre-tax profits for the three months ending June 30
compared with earnings of 874 million pounds in the same period a
year earlier. Revenues plunged 30 percent to 6.24 billion pounds
(dlrs 10.42 billion), from 8.96 billion pounds, BP said.
(BRITAIN-EARNS-OIL)
	   LUDWIGSHAFEN, Germany (AP) _ Chemical group BASF said Tuesday
that earnings growth will level off in the second half of 1998
after a pre-tax profit rise of 14.5 percent in the first six months
of the year compared to the same period last year. Group sales
during the first half rose only 3.4 percent down from a 5 percent
increase predicted by market observers. Pre-tax profit rose to 2.82
billion marks (dlrs 1.58 billion) from 2.46 billion marks (dlrs
1.38 billion) and group sales were up to 28.7 billion marks (dlrs
16.1 billion) for the first half from 27.8 billion marks (dlrs 15.6
billion) during last year's like period. (GERMANY-EARNS-BASF)
</TEXT>
