<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-People and Places,0712 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
People and places in the news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items on ER, Kofi Annan, Prince Ernst August of
Hanover, Barbra Streisland, Ingrid Bergman's Ferrari, Peter
Ustinov. Some items may have moved as separates. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) _ ``ER'' stars Anthony Edwards and Noah Wyle
have signed new contracts that will keep them on the highly rated
NBC medical drama through the year 2002, series producer Warner
Bros. said Tuesday.
	   Edwards will become TV's highest-paid star in a dramatic series,
earning nearly dlrs 400,000 an episode for the next four seasons,
Daily Variety reported. Wyle's extension is similar but will pay
him a bit less.
	   According to the trade paper, Edwards' roughly dlrs 35 million
deal gives him a raise for the next two seasons, which were covered
by a previous contract, and for two additional years.
	   A Warner spokesman declined comment on the salaries.
	   The deals with Edwards and Wyle were key to the series, which is
losing George Clooney after the coming season. Clooney is focusing
on his film career.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ If Kofi Annan ever wants to quit as U.N.
Secretary-General, he knows just the man to take over: Sir Peter
Ustinov.
	   ``His qualifications are simply unbeatable,'' Annan said at a
luncheon honoring the British character actor for serving 30 years
as a goodwill ambassador for UNICEF.
	   ``He speaks French, German, English, Italian, Russian, Spanish
and even some Turkish and Greek,'' Annan said. ``Even the languages
he does not actually speak, he can imitate so well that it sounds
uncannily as if he is speaking them.''
	   And if that wouldn't be enough to fill Ustinov's day, Annan had
more work in mind for Ustinov.
	   ``He could easily double as permanent representative of all the
member states,'' he said.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) _ Newlywed Barbra Streisand is thinking about
it, but she hasn't made any definite plans for a concert tour.
	   Rumors about a possible tour next year or in 2000 reached a
crescendo in recent days, leading Ms. Streisand's publicist Dick
Guttman to release a statement Monday by the entertainer's longtime
manager Marty Erlichman.
	   No decisions have been made, Erlichman said, ``although many
attractive offers from throughout the world have been received and
the possibility is being contemplated.''
	   Ms. Streisand, who married actor James Brolin at her Malibu
estate on July 1, recently released the album ``On Higher Ground.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	   HANOVER, Germany (AP) _ Prince Ernst August of Hanover was fined
dlrs 50,800 for hitting a photographer trying to take pictures of
him with Princess Caroline of Monaco.
	   Charges of assault will be dropped if the prince agrees to pay
the fine, to be divided evenly between two charity organizations
and the state of Lower Saxony, state prosecutors said Tuesday.
	   Prosecutors said the prince beat photographer Karsten Thuernau
for seven minutes with an umbrella at his estate near Hanover on
Jan. 11.
	   Thuernau, who had been waiting to photograph the royal couple,
was not seriously injured. The prince had claimed he was trying to
hit Thuernau's camera.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   BEVERLY HILLS, California (AP) _ Romance surrounds a 1953
Ferrari that could fetch dlrs 250,000.
	   The late Ingrid Bergman's Ferrari 212 Pinin Farina Coupe, given
to her as a wedding gift by husband Roberto Rossellini and dubbed
``my growling baby'' by the actress, is one of the 65 featured
vehicles up for bid Aug. 16 at the Exceptional Motor Cars sale at
Pebble Beach Resorts.
	   ``Titanic'' director James Cameron's 1991 Callaway Speedster,
Kimberly Hefner's 1962 Chrysler 300 convertible and a 1989 Jaguar
XJS once owned by Frank Sinatra are also on the block. And there's
the Kimberly Cooper-Climax Formula 1 car driven by Jack Brabham in
the 1961 Indianapolis 500.
	   In April 1951, Miss Bergman and Rossellini were visiting the
Turin Auto Show when Miss Bergman was immediately struck by the
Ferrari's sleek styling. Rossellini vowed to have one made for her
as a wedding present and it was completed in 1953, records showed.
	   Auction spokeswoman Beth Shepherd said it was expected to fetch
dlrs 180,000 to dlrs 250,000. In 1953, the love coupe cost
Rossellini dlrs 12,000.
</TEXT>
