w2813 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Argentina-Britain-Fal     08-04 0284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Argentina-Britain-Falklands,0284 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Britain rejects Argentina's right to tax companies in Falklands
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) _ The British government opposes
Argentina's intention to fine oil companies that drill in the
Falkland Islands basin without its consent, a senior Foreign Office
official said Tuesday.
	   ``We reject Argentina's right to impose taxation on companies
where Britain is sovereign,'' said Tony Lloyd, foreign minister of
state for foreign and commonwealth affairs.
	   A bill pending in congress would levy a 3 percent royalty tax on
all oil or gas extracted from the region, and would make any
company refusing to pay this tax liable to sanctions.
	   The bill initiated by Senator Eduardo Menem, brother of
President Carlos Menem, was approved by the Senate in late April
and is awaiting debate in the lower house.
	   Lloyd said his government's opposition was based on the
extra-territoriality of the law because of British sovereignty, and
also because the law seeks to punish any company on the supply or
demand end of oil operations.
	   ``It's not in the interest of Argentina to go down the road of
extra-territoriality,'' Lloyd said. ``None of us ought to go down
that road.''
	   The controversy derives from differences over the 1995 Agreement
on Cooperation in Hydrocarbons, over which the governments haven't
yet reached a final accord.
	   Lloyd also reiterated his government's intentions to maintain
the sovereignty of the Falkland Islands over which the two
countries fought a 74-day war in 1982.
	   Argentina and Britain renewed relations in 1990 and later signed
treaties on oil and fishing rights in the waters surrounding the
islands.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Argentina-Britain-Falklands; CT:i; 
