<HEADLINE>
Dollar falls, Tokyo stocks edge lower in early trading
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar fell against the yen early
Wednesday, while Tokyo stock prices edged lower following a steep
drop overnight on Wall Street.
	   The dollar bought 143.88 yen in early trading, down 0.74 yen
from late in Tokyo and also below its late New York rate of 144.97
yen overnight.
	   The dollar weakened after a sharp overnight fall on Wall Street,
where the Dow Jones industrial average closed down 299.43 points at
8,487.31 on Tuesday, its third-largest point loss ever.
	   In Tokyo, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 8.45 points,
or 0.05 percent, to 16,015.13 points in the opening minutes of
trading. On Tuesday, the Nikkei closed down 141.50 points, or 0.88
percent.
	   The Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was down 1.50 points, or 0.12 percent, to 1,233.11. The
TOPIX closed down 10.63 points, or 0.85 percent, the day before.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond fell to 1.200 percent from Tuesday's finish of
1.220 percent, driving its price up to 111.79 yen from 111.66 yen.
