w2825 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANALYSIS-US-Clinton-L     08-04 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANALYSIS-US-Clinton-Legal Legacy,0637 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Frittering away White House privacy
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING to FIX slug &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-US-Clinton-Investigation &QL; 
 &UR; By TERENCE HUNT &QC; 
 &UR; AP White House Correspondent &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Again and again, the White House has been
rebuffed by courts in its battle to block testimony in the Monica
Lewinsky investigation.
	   Beyond the legal skirmishes of this summer, one of the legacies
of President Bill Clinton's legal struggle may well be a shrinking
of confidentiality and privilege for his successors.
	   ``Future presidents may take a dim view of President Clinton's
litigation strategy,'' said Jonathan Turley, professor of
constitutional law at George Washington University. ``He may
ultimately be viewed as something of a constitutional spendthrift
who easily frittered away the privileges of his office.''
	   In the six-month investigation of his relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky, Clinton has waged losing battles in asserting
lawyer-client privilege, executive privilege and a special
protective privilege covering Secret Service agents.
	   A president's private conversations with administration
attorneys are not shielded from grand jury questioning because the
lawyers are working for taxpayers, not just the president, a
federal judge and an appeals court have ruled.
	   Presidents have traditionally been reluctant to test executive
privilege in the courts in order to protect future administrations
from negative, binding rulings. Clinton's staff says the president
is waging his battles to preserve protections for his successors,
to defend the institution of the presidency rather than surrender
to an out-of-control prosecutor.
	   ``This was done on principle,'' said presidential counselor Rahm
Emanuel. ``This is where politics and principle are in tandem.''
	   Clinton also lost ground in the Paula Jones sexual harassment
case when the Supreme Court unanimously ruled that a president
could be forced into civil litigation during his term. Jones' case
was later dismissed by the trial court, but the high court's
precedent still stands.
	   There is a spirited debate within political and legal circles
about whether Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr has been too
zealous in his pursuit of the president, and whether Clinton has
been too aggressive in trying to prevent his aides and agents from
having to testify about his behavior.
	   But there is a widespread belief that the courts _ at least so
far _ have diluted presidential privacy.
	   ``The effect of these rulings is to weaken the presidency as an
institution,'' said Herman Schwartz, law professor at American
University. Seeking advice on sensitive matters, presidents will
not be able to turn to their senior aides, to their own counsel or
even to former presidents, if current rulings are upheld.
	   ``How can he seek the guidance of wise heads if those people can
be subpoenaed?'' said Schwartz. ``The only wise heads he can seek
are private lawyers at dlrs 450 an hour. It seems to me, almost
everybody who's not a lawyer is kind of startled at the continual
rulings that there's no privilege of any kind for these intensely
confidential matters. There is a commonsense assumption that people
need confidentiality in order to talk openly and if they don't get
it, they won't.''
	   The White House argues that it is Starr _ not Clinton _ who has
jeopardized the principle of presidential privilege.
	   ``I think the blame lies elsewhere,'' deputy press secretary
Barry Toiv said. ``I think it is not we who are seeking to breach
the attorney-client privilege. This has been done on a couple of
occasions and in a couple of different areas, and it was not done
by this White House.''
	   ____
	    &UR; EDITOR'S NOTE _ Terence Hunt has covered the Reagan, Bush and
Clinton presidencies for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
