<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japanese stocks slightly lower in early trading, dollar slides
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with first 30 minutes of Nikkei trading, other
details &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese stock prices fell slightly early Wednesday
following an overnight plunge on Wall Street, while the U.S. dollar
slid against the yen.
	   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 62.84 points, or 0.39
percent, moving to 15,960.74 points in the first 30 minutes of
trading. On Tuesday, the Nikkei closed down 141.50 points, or 0.88
percent.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section slipped 2.80 points, or 0.23 percent, to 1,231.81.
The TOPIX closed down 10.63 points, or 0.85 percent, the day
before.
	   In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average recorded its
biggest point loss of the year and its third worst ever, losing
299.43 points, or 3.41 percent, to 8,487.31 at Tuesday's close.
	   Traders said, however, that the Tokyo market was relatively firm
despite the overnight drop in New York because of expectations for
further action from Japan's new government to stimulate the
economy.
	   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa and senior policy makers of the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party Tuesday agreed Tuesday on a plan to
cut personal income taxes by about 4 trillion yen (U.S. dlrs 27.7
billion) and also by 2 trillion yen (dlrs 13.8 billion) for
corporations.
	   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar bought 143.88 yen in
early trading, down 0.74 yen from late in Tokyo on Tuesday and also
below its late New York rate of 144.97 yen overnight.
	   The dollar weakened after the sharp overnight fall on Wall
Street.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond fell to 1.200 percent from Tuesday's finish of
1.220 percent, driving its price up to 111.79 yen from 111.66 yen.
 &UR; (km) 	   
