<SLUG> BC-Congo,0498 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Alliance unraveling into violence in Congo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS pvs. &QL; 
 &UR; With Analysis-Rwanda-Congo &QL; 
 &UR; By KAMANGA MUTOND &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) _ The delicate ethnic and military alliance
that catapulted Laurent Kabila to Congo's presidency is unraveling,
with rebellious fighters battling his troops at both ends of the
central African country.
	   Gunfire has broken out in the eastern town of Bukavu near the
border with Rwanda, said local aid workers Tuesday. A provincial
official told The Associated Press that the rebels were in control
of the city, although some reports indicated that fighting
continued.
	   Banyamulenge ethnic fighters and Rwandan troops were leading the
uprising against Kabila, accusing him of widespread corruption and
government mismanagement.
	   Those groups played a key role in helping Kabila march to
victory last year over longtime Zairian dictator Mobutu Sese Seko.
	   But Kabila now accuses Rwanda _ whose vice president, Paul
Kagame, was widely viewed as helping him topple Mobutu _ of being
behind the movement against his leadership.
	   Rwanda denies orchestrating the mutiny. However, it has
increasingly complained that Kabila has done little to increase
security in the Great Lakes region of central Africa.
	   Fighting was reported at the military base in southwestern
Kitona, where rebel gunmen forced a hijacked private airplane to
land, said Kabila spokesman Yerodia Abdoulaye Ndombasi. It was
unclear who was in control of the base, 140 miles (225 kilometers)
southwest of Kinshasa.
	   The plane was hijacked by Banyamulenge fighters on the opposite
side of the country, in the eastern city of Goma. Ndombasi gave no
other details.
	   Earlier, Kabila vowed to crush the uprising and called on his
supporters for help.
	   ``Be assured we will take weapons to swiftly end this
rebellion,'' Cabinet minister Pierre Victor Mpoyo said on state
radio, quoting Kabila.
	   The vice governor of South Kivu province, Benjamin Serukiza,
said the Tutsi rebels had taken control of much of the province,
including Bukavu and its airport.
	   ``At the moment a large portion of the province is under the
control of the army, which is hostile to Kabila's regime,''
Serukiza said in a telephone interview.
	   Kabila convened an emergency cabinet meeting Tuesday to discuss
the government's response to the rebellion in the east and to
earlier gunbattles at two military barracks in the capital.
	   After he came to power, Kabila kept Rwandan troops on as part of
his defense force until he ordered them out last week. A few days
earlier, he fired his chief military officer, a Rwandan Tutsi
soldier.
	   ``Kabila has been very aggressive against his neighbors of
late,'' Rwandan chief of staff Gen. Kayumba Nyamwasa said Tuesday.
	   The ethnic Tutsi population in North Kivu has close links with
Rwanda, and Kabila's support and control of the region has been
faltering for months.
</TEXT>
