<SLUG> BC-Sports-Basketball-Worlds,0676 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ousts Australia; Italy, Argentina in quarterfinals
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS pvs &QL; 
 &UR; By STEPHEN WADE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ American coach Rudy Tomjanovich called it
a ``do or die game'' for Australia.
	   Well, R.I.P. Australia.
	   The mix-and-match Americans _ the no-name composite of CBA,
European pros and a college player _ kept Australia from claiming
the eighth and final quarterfinal spot in the World Basketball
Championship, dumping the Aussies on Tuesday 96-78.
	   Instead, the final place in Friday's quarterfinals went to
Argentina, which beat Brazil 86-76 and then had to wait several
hours for the Americans to oust Australia so they could advance
themselves.
	   ``For our tournament to hinge on a game with the United States
was tough. Talk about being behind the eight-ball,'' said Australia
coach Barry Barnes.
	   ``We kept changing defenses. We tried pressure, we tried laying
off their shooters but nothing worked,'' he added.
	   The Americans demoralized the Aussies in the first half with hot
shooting _ just under 60 percent from the field _ and a stiff
man-to-man that forced turnovers and got the Americans running. And
the second half was more of the same in the best U.S. performance
so far.
	   Jimmy Oliver led the U.S. attack with 18 and Jason Sasser added
15 with 10 of the 12 Americans getting on the scoreboard.
	   ``We had a lot at stake,'' U.S. coach Rudy Tomjanovich said.
``If we win we get the number one seed. If we lose we drop all the
way to four. It was a do-or-die for Australia, too.''
	   Australia _ silver medalists last month in the Goodwill Games _
was led by Shane Heal with 31.
	   Friday's quarterfinals look like this: United States (5-1) vs.
Italy (3-3), Spain (5-1) vs. Greece (4-2), Lithuania (4-2) vs.
Russia (5-1), Argentina (3-3) vs. Yugoslavia (5-1).
	   Under the complicated system to pair teams for the
quarterfinals, a U.S. loss could have pitted it against Yugoslavia
or Russia _ perhaps the two favorites. Every other team faced
similar last-minute twists.
	   In Argentina's critical victory, Marcelo Nicola hit 22 and
Fabricio Oberto added 21. Brazil got 22 from Marco Aurelio Pegolo
and 20 from Joao Jose Vianna.
	   Italy beat Puerto Rico 68-63 to claim the other quarterfinal
spot that was on the line Tuesday as the second round ended.
Slovenian-born Gregor Fucka hit 15 and scored the last five points
with a slam dunk, a layup and a free throw to lead Italy.
	   Jose Ortiz had 21 points and 14 rebounds for the Puerto Ricans
(2-4).
	   ``It would be a dream to be in the semifinals or the finals, but
right now we just have to concentrate on our next opponents,'' said
Italian center Giacomo Galanda.
	   Spain defeated Lithuania 86-80 in overtime and Russia won over
Canada 81-72 to pick up key victories.
	   Spain, the surprise team of the worlds, hasn't won a medal in a
major tournament in seven years _ bronze in the '91 Europeans _ and
has hardly been heard from since it shocked itself with silver in
the 1984 Olympics.
	   Forward Alberto Herreros, the leading scorer in the tournament,
had 27 and Alfonso Reyes added 19. Arturas Karnisovas, playing with
a bandaged head after a second-half collision with a Spain's
Ignacio de Miguel that drew blood, led Lithuania (4-2) with 20. But
he was scoreless in the last 11 minutes.
	   ``This has shown our basketball is decent and we're
competitive,'' said coach Lolo Sainz, who is in the first phase of
rebuilding and is expected in the next few years to dip heavily
into a rich pool of young talent.
	   Yugoslavia, after losing Monday to Italy 61-60, dumped home-team
Greece 70-56 with 19 points for Dejan Bodiroga. Fragiskos Alvertis
led Greece with 23 as the local team dropped its second straight
game after losing Monday to Russia.
	   Russia _ billed as the favorite with Yugoslavia to win the title
Sunday _ was topped by Vassiliy Karassev with 21 points and Sergei
Babkov and Sergei Panov with 14. Canada (1-5) got 14 points and 11
rebounds from Greg Newton. 	   
</TEXT>
