<SLUG> BC-Sports-Basketball-Worlds-Notebook,0560 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Greek organizers vs. Yugoslav officials and press
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By STEPHEN WADE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ Balkan neighbors Greece and Yugoslavia are
having a tiff off the basketball court.
	   The Greek organizing committee of these worlds has been
criticized in the Yugoslav press for its running of the
championship, and on Tuesday Greece replied.
	   The president of the Greek basketball federation Giorgos
Vassilakopoulos met Tuesday with FIBA president Boris Stankovic _ a
Yugoslav _ to try clearing the air.
	   ``We must not take into consideration, nor answer, nor be
affected by alleged foolish statements,'' Vassilakopoulos said in
his own statement. ``We must retain our athletic and friendly
relationships with Yugoslavia. Unfortunatley, I daily observe the
operation of a mechanism creating false news against the
championship, the organizing committee, Greece and me personally.
	   ``I am very much afraid that besides Borislav Stankovic, there
is chaos among the FIBA executives. That is why we have to do our
best to have Mr. Stankovic remain in his position.''
	   In general, the championship has been well run, but attendance _
without the Dream Team _ has been abysmal, except when Greece
plays. Organizers are expecting to lose money after talking about a
dlrs 1 profit when the Dream Team was still slated to come.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   BROWNOUTS: Forest fires in the Pendeli mountain area 30
kilometers (20 miles) north of downtown Athens _ fanned by strong
winds and stoked by 40C (100F) temperatures the last week _ are
being blamed for brownouts at local hotels and at the two
basketball arenas.
	   Tuesday's second-round game between Brazil and Argentina at
Peace and Friendship stadium was stopped for 15 minutes when the
lights dimmed and _ when they didn't come back up _ officials
resumed the game. All of the lights came up a few minutes later.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   OOH, CANADA: Former Duke center Greg Newton was Canada's leading
scorer through five games. The Canadians (1-5) won't play in the
quarterfinals, but Newton was pleased with his own play.
	   ``I think as the tournament progessed I've played better and
better and more opportunities have come to me,'' he said after
scoring 25 against Puerto Rico in a 94-81 loss.
	   The 2.08-meter (6-10) Newton played last season in Belgium with
Siemens but said he's looking for a new offer.
	   Canadian coach Steve Konchalski praised his main man.
	   ``He's been our leading scorer and rebounder and he's a player
we can build around,'' Konchalski said. ``The emergence of Greg
Newton is a tremendous factor for our future.
	   __ &QC; 
	   BASKETBALL ART: A sculpture by Greek artist Pavlos Kougioumtzis
called ``The Two Basektball Players'' will be donated Friday to the
Greek Basketball Federation by the municipality of Maroussi.
	   The 3-meter (10-foot) high statue will be housed in the Olympic
stadium, one of the two sites for these worlds.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   REBOUNDS: Spain's 2.01-meter (6-7) Alberto Herreros is the
leading scorer thorugh five games averaging 19.2 points per game.
Jose Ortiz of Puerto Rico lead in rebounds (10.6).
	   The best player in the tournament might be Yugoslavia's Zeljko
Rebraca, a 26-year-old 2.12 (7-0) center who leads with 14 blocks
in five games and was tied for third in rebounds averaging 9.6. 	   
</TEXT>
