<SLUG> BC-FEA-Indonesia-Media Freedom,0554 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian media gets into rhythm of new freedom, but worries
</HEADLINE>
linger &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ With decades-old curbs on press
freedom stripped away, Indonesia's media are joining an explosion
of public debate. One newspaper column even compared the nation's
former government to Nazi rule in Germany.
	   But while the new leadership preaches democratic reform, it
remains fearful that journalists may go too far in their
exuberance, spreading rumors or misinformation during a delicate
period in Indonesia. Fears of fresh unrest linger as the nation's
economic crisis weighs heavier on the poor.
	   ``The government wants the press to abide by a code of ethics
and to respect the national culture and moral values,'' Information
Minister Yunus Yosfiah said without elaborating.
	   The government began relaxing its control on the media following
the May resignation of President Suharto, who frequently shut down
publications that criticized him during his 32 years in power.
	   Now in editorial pages, it's open season on Suharto and his
family, accused by foes of deepening Indonesia's economic paralysis
by allegedly siphoning off national wealth.
	   On Tuesday, a Roman Catholic priest argued on the front page of
the respected English-language Jakarta Post that under Suharto, the
military used harsh tactics to crush separatist movements in remote
parts of the nation.
	   ``The further you traveled from Jakarta, the more common Nazi
SS-style practices became,'' wrote the Rev. Y.B. Mangunwijaya, who
is also a social worker.
	   Suharto's successor, President B.J. Habibie, is routinely
cajoled by columnists who say he's sluggish on reform.
	   Media managers are short of cash, but euphoric editors are eager
to print. Indonesia has issued 60 licenses for new publications
since the downfall of Suharto, whose government was loathe to grant
them.
	   Detak, a weekly newspaper banned under Suharto, is publishing
again. The cover of its first edition showed Suharto, his face
mostly hidden by a superimposed ninja mask, and a story said
remnants of the old regime lurked in the shadows, still a threat to
Indonesian democracy.
	   Last month, a proposal by Habibie that reporters be required to
obtain work licenses, much like doctors or engineers, angered
journalists who labeled it a throwback to the Suharto days.
	   As research and technology minister under Suharto, Habibie was
hardly a champion of press freedom. The government shuttered
Indonesia's most respected magazine, Tempo, in 1994 after it
published articles that angered Habibie.
	   Now, at least publicly, Habibie is good-natured about criticism
and even invites it.
	   ```The press is very important as the basis or foundation or
backbone of democracy,''' Parni Hadi, head of the official Antara
news agency, quoted Habibie as saying at a meeting last month.
	   Hadi said the spread of scandal sheets, easier to publish in the
freer climate, was leading to a deterioration of journalistic
standards. Publications speculate about the love lives of
well-known Indonesians, including a son of Suharto.
	   ``There are so many fake journalists, unqualified journalists,''
Hadi said. ``We are already on the brink of going too far.''
</TEXT>
