<SLUG> BC-Israel-Shooting </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two Jewish settlers killed, talks stuck over West Bank withdrawal
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Recaps previous to UPDATE throughout with fresh comments,
details; background &QL; 
 &UR; By AMI BEN-TOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ITZHAR, West Bank (AP) _ As tensions heightened between Israeli
and Palestinian negotiators over the scope of a West Bank troop
withdrawal, two Jewish settlers were shot and killed early
Wednesday in the same area Israel says it is reluctant to pull
forces from.
	   The double killings outside the Jewish settlement of Itzhar in
the West Bank was likely to further complicate peace talks, already
at an impasse.
	   The Palestinians have rejected Israeli proposals to alter an
American peace initiative which calls for Israel to withdraw its
troops from 13 percent of the West Bank.
	   Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, under pressure from
the strong Jewish settler lobby and right-wing members of his
Cabinet, has rejected the American plan, saying that it would harm
Israel's security by isolating several communities including
Itzhar. Israel offered to redeploy from ten percent of territory
and turn another 3 percent into a nature reserve where Israel would
retain overall security but that was rejected Tuesday by
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
	   Still, Jewish settler leaders said even a 10 percent withdrawal
would have left Itzhar cut-off and said Wednesday's killings were a
harbinger of things to come if redeployment goes through.
	   ``This is a tragic example of what is likely to occur in
ten-fold when troop redeployments are carried out. Itzhar, and
another 18 settlements will be turned into isolated islands,'' said
Settler Council leader Ahron Dombe. Dombe called on Netanyahu to
cancel talks until the assailants were found.
	   Like most Jewish settlements in the West Bank, Itzhar is perched
on a dusty, barren hilltop and looks out onto several small
Palestinians village on surrounding hillsides. Israel still
controls most of the area, allowing it to clamp down on the
villages, set up road blocks and conduct door-to-door searches for
the gunmen as it did Wednesday.
	   But the impending troop withdrawal would change that. Israeli
soldiers would not longer be allowed into the villages that lay
between Itzhar and the large Palestinian-run city of Nablus, 10 km
(6 miles) away.
	   In Nablus, Palestinian police commander Isam el-Dobi said Israel
had informed Palestinian authorities of the shooting and
Palestinian police were meeting to discuss possible coordination in
the case.
	   Israel and the Palestinians have been haggling for months over
the scope of the long overdue Israeli withdrawal and a U.S. peace
plan to get it off the ground. A little over two weeks of direct
negotiations, after American mediators failed to bridge gaps, has
not yielded any progress and Tuesday the Palestinians signaled they
may leave the talks altogether.
	   At Itzhar, settlers prepared funerals for the two men killed at
approximately 1:00am (22:00gmt) while on a routine nightly jeep
patrol of the settlement boundaries.
	   A statement from the Israeli army spokesman's office said the
two settlers, whose names were not immediately released, were
killed while in their jeep. Dombe said one of the men managed to
radio for help shortly after they were first fired upon. Dombe said
the assailants then came within close range of the jeep and fired
an additional bullet into the heads of each man, killing them
instantly.
 &UR; dl
</TEXT>
