<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Mexico-Tequila Challenger,0822 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Move over tequila, Mexican mezcal finding niche in export market
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos NY330-335 &QL; 
 &UR; By JULIE WATSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   OAXACA, Mexico (AP) _ The sun-broiled hills of Oaxaca are alive
_ with worms.
	   And so a marketing hook was born.
	   Zapotecan Indians and their burros trek up into the mountains
outside this southern Mexican city to harvest spiky,
iridescent-green agave plants and bring them back for cooking.
	   At crowded, smoke-filled cantinas in town, bartenders serve
locals and tourists the product of that work: the liquor mezcal,
famous for the dead agave worm bobbing in many of the bottles.
	   Once secretly brewed by tax-dodging farmers, mezcal now is being
sold by Mexican moonshiners-turned-entrepeneurs as an upscale drink
to 18 countries.
	   Some people tout mezcal as the equivalent of soaking in eight
years of sun _ the time it takes an agave plant to mature.
	   But much of the drink's appeal comes from that floating agave
worm, which Zapotecans have long considered a powerful aphrodisiac,
even making tortillas and salt from ground-up worms.
	   The worms are extracted from the hearts of agave plants during
the harvest. In 1950, Jacobo Lozano Paez, a Mexico City
entrepreneur and now owner of the company that bottles Gusano Rojo
mezcal, decided to put a worm in each bottle as a marketing gimmick
and a tradition began.
	   The liquor became a novelty drink across the border in the
southwestern United States, but its cachet has grown over the years
and demand has spread.
	   Mezcal exports have nearly tripled since 1994, according to
Mexico's export bank, Bancomext. Production doubled during that
period, and may top 1.6 million gallons (6 million liters) this
year.
	   Exporters in Oaxaca, where most mezcal is produced, say this is
no mere swill for guzzling college kids. And they are working hard
to distance mezcal from its more popular cousin _ tequila, which is
made in the state of Jalisco from a different kind of agave.
	   ``Tequila was promoted more as a party drink,'' says Cesar de la
Pena Dominguez, assistant manager of credit promotion at Bancomext
in Oaxaca. ``But we want to promote mezcal more as a fine cognac,
something different, very select, a mystical drink of the gods.''
	   Aged in oak barrels for four years and bottled in a hand-blown
pumpkin-shaped glass, Gran Reserva Beneva mezcal won a gold medal
at the 1998 World Spirit Championships. It sells for about dlrs 50
(445 pesos) a bottle.
	   Tehuana Anejo by Chagoya, a two-year mezcal priced at dlrs 33.95
(300 pesos) a bottle, also won a gold.
	   The more expensive brands don't contain the red worm. Promoters
still use worms in cheaper versions to catch people's attention
with the hope they'll move up to the aged mezcals.
	   Asian buyers want as many as five worms a bottle.
	   ``That's so each person can have a worm in their glass,'' says
Carlos Leon Monterrubio, fourth-generation owner of Joyas
Oaxaquena, which has produced mezcal since the 1800s.
	   But when dealing with the less adventuresome folks in the United
States, mezcal's marketers concentrate more on the liquor's purity.
	   By law, mezcal is guaranteed 100 percent agave with an official
seal. Faced with an overwhelming demand and limited land, most
tequila distillers add up to 49 percent cane liquor or other
alcohol unless the label states otherwise.
	   In 1996, distillers produced 1.5 million gallons (5.6 million
liters) of mezcal, of which 470,000 gallons (1.8 million liters)
worth dlrs 6.1 million (54 million pesos) was exported. Some 30
percent of exports went to the United States and 20 percent to
Asia. The rest to Europe, South Africa and South America.
	   About 29.6 million gallons (112 million liters) of tequila was
produced in the same period, including nearly 16 million gallons
(60 million liters) that was exported. Forty percent of exports
went to the United States.
	   Unlike modernized tequila factories, mezcal production has
changed little since Spanish conquerors began distilling agave in
the 1500s.
	   Fernando Romero Blas, a mezcal distiller, and a half-dozen
workers trek three hours with burros to harvest wild tobala agave,
just as his forefathers did when they began making mezcal in the
19th century.
	   Later, they will lead a horse-drawn mill stone over
bittersweet-smelling agave baked for days in an earthen pit.
	   But first, they surround the agave and ask Mother Earth's
permission before cutting the plant, which secretes a burning
liquid that causes skin rashes.
	   Romero, a Zapotecan Indian, buries hard-boiled eggs, mangos,
bananas and a burning cigarette in a pottery bowl. He pours mezcal
on the ground in the shape of a cross.
	   Then he pours a bit out for each of his men. Everyone toasts
before starting work.
	   ``We do this as a tribute to Earth,'' Romero says. ``We must
give something back.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-FEA-Mexico-Tequila Challenger; CT:i; 
