<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Ruiz Massieu,0277 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former deputy attorney general barred from holding office in
</HEADLINE>
Mexico &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ A former deputy attorney general has been
barred from holding public office for 20 years for allegedly
allowing police to brutalize suspects while he investigated the
assassination of his brother.
	   A resolution by the Comptroller General's Office dated Monday
accused Mario Ruiz Massieu of permitting police to coerce at least
two people into signing depositions in the 1994 case.
	   Ruiz Massieu is now under house arrest in New Jersey and
fighting extradition to Mexico. The comptroller's action is
administrative and does not involve criminal sanctions.
	   The comptroller's office said that on Sept. 28, 1994, Ruiz
Massieu knew about and allowed the federal judicial police chief
and other police officers to coerce witnesses while being
questioned.
	   One of them, Maria Eugenia Ramirez Arauz, a secretary,
``suffered serious pain that resulted in several injuries.''
	   Mexico has been trying to extradite Ruiz Massieu, accusing him
of attempting a cover up in his brother's murder, as well as
alleging illegal enrichment, drug money laundering and corruption.
	   U.S. federal courts rejected the charges because of inconclusive
evidence. An immigration judge dismissed deportation proceedings
against him in May 1997. But the government appealed that decision
and he remains under house arrest.
	   However, the U.S. government won a jury verdict last year,
allowing it to seize dlrs 7.9 million from dlrs 9 million Mario
Ruiz Massieu had in bank accounts in Texas, claiming the money came
from drug traffickers.
</TEXT>
