w2853 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-Russia-Struggling     08-04 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Russia-Struggling Herders,0789 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia branch of Sami reindeer herders struggles to survive
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Graphic RUSSIA SAMI &QL; 
 &UR; By DOUG MELLGREN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LOVOZERO, Russia (AP) _ Reindeer mean almost everything to a
Sami. Here, in the capital of Russia's Sami region, there are no
reindeer.
	   The only roaming animals to be seen are starving dogs
desperately searching for food outside the school, not
understanding that the people themselves go hungry and have no
scraps to throw away.
	   ``We are surviving, barely,'' said Nicolay Brylow, mayor of this
town of 3,700 people about 130 kilometers (80 miles) south of
Murmansk on Russia's Kola Peninsula.
	   The wretched conditions in Lovozero contrast sharply with the
lives of Sami in the Arctic reaches of Finland, Sweden and Norway,
where life isn't easy but there is plenty to eat and dogs are
athletic and sleek.
	   For millennia, the Sami _ a name they prefer to Lapp _ thrived
by following their reindeer flocks across Europe's Arctic. Then the
Iron Curtain fell and about 2,000 ended up on the Soviet side.
	   That meant reindeer herds were collectivized, to be tended by a
relatively few herders. The rest of the nomads were sent to
Lovozero.
	   The town is a mix of dreary Soviet-era concrete apartments and
sagging wooden houses, the wood silver-gray from decades of hard
weather and no paint. There are few cars, except the rattletraps of
those who sell shoes and clothes at the open-air market.
	   ``There are families who are starving, and many more that don't
get a balanced diet,'' said Dr. Marina Dubovtseva, a physician at
Lovozero's run-down and poorly supplied hospital.
	   Reindeer were the center of Sami lives, providing food,
clothing, transportation and even objects of religious worship. But
the reindeer now are far away from Lovozero, deep in the tundra,
and the herders' conditions are even worse than those living in
town.
	   ``The herders live under inhuman conditions,'' said Jan Terje
Nedrejord, city manager in Karasjok, Norway, a Sami town of about
3,000 people that is the site of the Norwegian Sami Parliament.
	   The Kola herders live in tents and hovels, with inadequate heat,
food and sanitation, he said.
	   Apart from hunger, the people of Lovozero suffer from
deteriorating health care, a declining birth rate, diseases caused
by pollution and widespread alcoholism. They often lack heat in
their homes during the bitter Arctic winter, and as many as half
are unemployed.
	   Conditions appear to be getting worse.
	   Formerly state-owned ``companies that process meat are either
bankrupt or about to go bankrupt, and they can't pay for the
products,'' said Olga Novriva, director of Tundra, one of two
reindeer cooperatives in the district.
	   Norwegian Sami are buying meat and also training young Russian
Sami in modern herding and the skills needed to process meat
locally, Novriva said.
	   About 200 kilometers (125 miles) to the west, the Sami of the
Nordic countries enjoy the generous social programs of the welfare
state. They have Sami colleges, newspapers and special rights as a
native people.
	   When the Nordic Sami reestablished contact with their kinsmen in
Russia in the early 1990s, they set up language and cultural
programs. That was quickly expanded to include soup kitchens and
donations of warm clothing, medicines and even small cash gifts.
	   ``We realized things are very bad in Lovozero,'' said Ante Javo,
a Norwegian Sami who leads the Karasjok-Lovozero Friendship
Society.
	   Jobs are scarce in Lovozero, especially with the biggest
employer, a mine and smelter that employed 1,300, shutting down.
	   Reindeer herding is again the main industry, employing 220
people. That is struggling, too, because the fragile tundra can't
withstand grazing by more than the current 65,000 reindeer.
	   ``It is impossible to increase production,'' said Novriva, at
the reindeer cooperative.
	   Despite daily hardships, the Kola Sami still seek their roots.
The local culture center is full of reindeer skin boots and
clothing, beaded jewelry and traditional handcrafts for sale.
	   Jakob Jakovlev showed off a knife with a carved reindeer horn
handle that he made with tools donated by Swedish Sami.
	   ``The Kola version of the Sami knife was lost, but we discovered
it again in photographs in the national archives,'' he said.
	   In another room at the center, adult Sami struggled to learn
their ancestral Sami dialect, Kildin, in a Norwegian-financed
course.
	   ``In the past, Sami were ashamed to call themselves Sami. Now it
is very much different. People want to learn,'' said Larisa
Avdeeva, head of the Kola Sami Association. ``We never lost our
roots as Sami.'' 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-FEA-Russia-Struggling Herders; CT:i; 
