<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-War Crimes,0455 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serbs enraged by death of Serb war crimes suspect in U.N. custody
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MISHA SAVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ The already strained relationship
between the Serbians and the Yugoslav war crimes tribunal has
worsened following last week's prison death of a Serb suspect in
U.N. custody
	   Milan Kovacevic, accused of atrocities during the Bosnian war,
died Saturday of a heart attack, triggering an avalanche of
allegations from Serb authorities that the Netherlands-based U.N.
court is anti-Serb.
	   In a statement published Tuesday in the state-run daily
Politika, the Yugoslav Justice Ministry said it had sent a sharp
protest to the tribunal, accusing it of ``inadequate medical
treatment for Dr. Kovacevic during his detention.''
	   The ministry said his death ``prevented Kovacevic from proving
his innocence before the tribunal'' and the court's ``reputation
has been brought into question.''
	   Kovacevic's death came just a month after another Serb suspect
in custody hanged himself in his high-security prison cell.
	   ``Only Serbs die in the Hague'' and ``Court without Justice''
were among headlines broadcast in the pro-government dailies here.
	   Tribunal spokesman Christian Chartier said last week that
Kovacevic had been under regular care by a heart specialist when he
died, and denied that the tribunal was lax in its care or
surveillance of jailed suspects.
	   Kovacevic, 57, had a history of health problems and had suffered
strokes. His lawyers say he had been denied medical treatment he
requested shortly before his death.
	   ``A person with such a serious heart problem had to be treated,
not left to die in a prison cell,'' said the Yugoslav government
committee in charge of cooperation with the Tribunal.
	   NATO-led peacekeepers in Bosnia apprehended Kovacevic last
summer. He was accused of genocide, war crimes and crimes against
humanity for alleged atrocities committed in northwest Bosnia's
Prijedor region in 1992.
	   He had pleaded innocent to all 15 charges against him and faced
a possible life sentence if convicted.
	   His was the U.N. court's first trial to deal specifically with
genocide. It began on July 6.
	   Yugoslavia, widely blamed for inciting the wars in Croatia and
Bosnia, has so far refused to extradite several suspects. Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic also has dodged demands to help
extradition of two top suspects, Bosnian Serb wartime leaders,
Radovan Karadzic and Gen. Ratko Mladic, who are presumed in hiding
somewhere in the Serb half of Bosnia.
	   Yugoslavia and the Serb leaders in Bosnia have been helpful to
the tribunal only in investigations concerning crimes against
Serbs.
</TEXT>
