<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Peru-Japanese Reparations,0315 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Official: Time running out for former interns to gain reparations
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LIMA, Peru (AP) _ A U.S. group on Tuesday urged Latin Americans
who were interned in Texas camps during World War II to act quickly
to take advantage of a reparations offer.
	   The United States announced two months ago that it would give
these Latins of Japanese heritage dlrs 5,000 each and an apology.
	   But the deadline for filing such a claim is Aug. 10 and many
qualified people still have not done so, Grace Shimizu of the
California-based Campaign for Justice, which fought for the
reparation, said in Lima.
	   Some 2,264 Latin Americans of Japanese descent, 80 percent of
whom were Peruvian, were held in the United States.
	   The U.S. government has never provided an explanation for the
internments, though many were later exchanged for U.S. prisoners of
war held in Japan.
	   The Latin Americans are particularly angry that
Japanese-Americans imprisoned during the war were awarded dlrs
20,000 by the U.S. government in a 1988 decision.
	   ``All of us were in the same situation, in the same
concentration camp ... It is such an open, unjust and irrational
discrimination that it is not acceptable,'' said German Yaki, who
was forcibly taken from Peru at age 12.
	   Yaki, 69, said a group of Latin Americans is planning to appeal
the U.S. decision in November, demanding the same compensation as
that received by Japanese Americans. He did not give further
details.
	   Shimizu, who visited Peru to warn people of the deadline, said
that 650 claims have been filed with the U.S. government and
another 300 to 500 people who are eligible still have not filed.
	   ``The Latin American-Japanese have waited more than 50 years for
an apology from the U.S. government. Now they can lose this if they
don't file their claim on time,'' she said.
</TEXT>
