<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Shooting,0629 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two Jewish settlers killed, talks stuck over West Bank withdrawal
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITS to some points. &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: Recaps previous to UPDATE throughout with fresh comments,
details; background, incorporates material from
Israel-Palestinians. &QL; 
 &UR; By AMI BEN-TOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ITZHAR, West Bank (AP) _ As tensions heightened between Israeli
and Palestinian negotiators over a proposed West Bank troop
withdrawal, two Jewish settlers were shot and killed early
Wednesday in the area that Israel says it is reluctant to give up.
	   The killings outside the Jewish settlement of Itzhar in the West
Bank were likely to complicate peace talks, already at an impasse.
	   The Palestinians have rejected Israeli proposals to alter an
American peace initiative that calls for Israel to withdraw its
troops from an additional 13 percent of the West Bank. The
Palestinians already have full or partial control over about
one-quarter of the territory.
	   Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, under pressure from
the strong Jewish settler lobby and right-wing members of his
Cabinet, has rejected the American plan, saying it would harm
Israel's security by isolating several communities that include
Itzhar.
	   Israel has offered to pull its troops from 10 percent of the
territory and turn another 3 percent into a nature reserve where it
would retain overall security. But Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
rejected the Israeli proposal on Tuesday.
	   Still, Jewish settler leaders said even a 10 percent withdrawal
would have left Itzhar cut off and said Wednesday's killings were a
harbinger of things to come if the pullback goes through.
	   ``This is a tragic example of what is likely to occur in
ten-fold when troop redeployments are carried out. Itzhar, and
another 18 settlements will be turned into isolated islands,'' said
Settler Council leader Ahron Dombe. Dombe called on Netanyahu to
cancel talks until the assailants were found.
	   Following the shootings, Israel placed a curfew on four
surrounding Palestinian villages and said it was searching the area
for the shooters.
	   Like most Jewish settlements in the West Bank, Itzhar is perched
on a dusty, barren hilltop and looks out onto several small
Palestinians village on surrounding hillsides. Israel still
controls most of the area, allowing it to clamp down on the
villages, set up road blocks and conduct door-to-door searches for
suspects.
	   But the impending troop withdrawal would change that. Israeli
soldiers would not longer be allowed into the villages that lay
between Itzhar and the large Palestinian-run city of Nablus, 10 kms
(6 miles) away.
	   In Nablus, Palestinian police commander Isam el-Dobi said Israel
had informed Palestinian authorities of the shooting and
Palestinian police were meeting to discuss possible coordination in
the case.
	   Israel and the Palestinians have been haggling for months over
the scope of the long overdue Israeli withdrawal and a U.S. peace
plan to get it off the ground.
	   More than two weeks of direct negotiations, after American
mediators failed to bridge gaps, has not yielded any progress. On
Tuesday, the Palestinians signaled they may leave the talks
altogether.
	   At Itzhar, settlers prepared funerals for the two men killed at
approximately 1:00 a.m. while on a routine nightly jeep patrol of
the settlement boundaries.
	   The Israeli army spokesman's office said the settlers, whose
names were not immediately released, were killed while in their
jeep. Dombe said one of the men managed to radio for help shortly
after they were first fired upon. Dombe said the assailants then
came within close range of the jeep and fired an additional bullet
into the heads of each man, killing them instantly. 	   
</TEXT>
