<SLUG> BC-Japan-Hiroshima-Paper Cranes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Paper cranes marking Hiroshima atomic bomb anniversary burned
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Thousands of folded paper cranes commemorating the
53rd anniversary of the world's first atomic bombing have been
found burned in a schoolyard in Hiroshima, police said Wednesday.
	   The destruction of the cranes occurred Tuesday, as Hiroshima
prepared events to mark the U.S. atomic attack on the southwestern
Japanese city on August 6, 1945.
	   ``Because of the timing, we can't help but think the incident is
connected with the anniversary,'' said a police spokesman, who gave
his surname, Kami.
	   The 5,800 ``origami,'' or folded, cranes _ a symbol of peace and
longevity in Japan _ were part of a memorial monument in the
courtyard of a Hiroshima junior high school.
	   Police were investigating the incident, but had not found any
suspects.
	   Every year, Hiroshima residents unite on Aug. 6 for a moment of
silence and ceremonies to commemorate the atomic bombing that
devastated their city and killed about 140,000 people.
	   Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi was to leave Wednesday for
Hiroshima to attend the memorial events.
	   On Tuesday, the Japan Council against Atomic and Hydrogen Bombs
launched a three-day anti-nuclear convention in the city.
	   Entitled ``From the Nuclear Age to a Nuclear-Free 21st
Century,'' the series of seminars and events will protest the
nuclear tests conducted by India and Pakistan this year, organizers
said.
 &UR; (js)
</TEXT>
