<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tokyo stocks slightly lower in early trading, dollar slides
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with late morning stock, bond and currency rates &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese stock prices fell early Wednesday
following an overnight plunge on Wall Street, while the U.S. dollar
traded lower against the yen.
	   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 180.82 points, or 1.13
percent, to close the morning session at 15,842.76 points. On
Tuesday, the Nikkei closed down 141.50 points, or 0.88 percent.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section slipped 9.03 points, or 0.73 percent, to 1,225.58.
The TOPIX closed down 10.63 points, or 0.85 percent, the day
before.
	   In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average recorded its
biggest point loss of the year and its third worst ever, dropping
299.43 points, or 3.41 percent, to 8,487.31.
	   Traders said, however, that the Tokyo market was relatively firm
despite the overnight drop in New York because of expectations for
further action from Japan's new government to stimulate the
economy.
	   On the Tokyo exchange, modest gains in some financial shares _
which have suffered heavy losses recently amid worries about the
economy _ helped offset losses in technology issues.
	   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa and senior policy makers of the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party on Tuesday agreed on a plan to cut
personal income taxes by about 4 trillion yen (U.S. dlrs 27.7
billion) and corporate taxes by 2 trillion yen (dlrs 13.8 billion).
	   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar bought 144.01 yen in
morning trading, down 0.61 yen from late in Tokyo on Tuesday and
lower than its late New York rate of 144.97 yen overnight.
	   The dollar weakened in line with the sharp overnight fall on
Wall Street.
	   The yen got a boost against the dollar as investors were
encouraged that the government seemed to be moving quickly to
implement its tax-cut plans, dealers said.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond fell to 1.210 percent from Tuesday's finish of
1.220 percent, driving its price up to 111.72 yen from 111.66 yen.
 &UR; (km-tz) 	   
</TEXT>
