r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-TaxPlan     08-04 0279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Tax Plan </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government promises only tax cheats will be hurt by new tax plan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Prime Minister John Howard on
Wednesday promised that his new tax package, which will include a
goods and services tax, will benefit all Australians.
	   The tax plan is expected to introduce a 10 percent goods and
services tax, but will also slash diesel fuel taxes to benefit
farmers and include hefty income tax cuts.
	   Treasurer Peter Costello announced the package, which is the
centerpiece of Howard's re-election campaign, will be made public
Aug. 13.
	   Howard said everyone would be a winner under the package.
	   ``I don't believe anybody, when you look at the generality of
the package, will be worse off except tax cheats,'' Howard told a
radio station.
	   Howard rejected comments by Queensland National Party director
Ken Crooke that the Senate, where Howard's government is in the
minority, is certain to reject the tax plan.
	   ``The government will put the plan before the Australian people
at the next election, whenever it is held, to give the government a
mandate not only in the House of Representatives, but also in the
Senate,'' Howard said.
	   But many members of the junior partner in Howard's governing
coalition, the rural National Party, oppose the tax plan and say it
should at least be delayed until the Asian economic crisis eases.
	   They are saying it is electoral suicide to go into an election _
which must be held by March 1999 _ promising voters new taxes.
	   Howard's party lost in a landslide in 1993 when it campaigned on
a similar plan to introduce a goods and services tax.
</TEXT>
