<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Crocodile Tamer </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thailand's famed crocodile tamer dies at 84
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ After decades of defying death in
crocodile shows, Thailand's most famous hunter and tamer of
crocodiles has died of lung disease at the age of 84, a spokesman
for the Samut Prakan Crocodile Farm said Wednesday.
	   Yuen Charoensuk, also known as Uncle Yao, died from emphysema on
Aug. 2 at the Vajiraprakan Hospital on the outskirts of Bangkok,
said Thananya Chankrachang, public relations director for the
Crocodile Farm.
	   Tourists from around the world have witnessed Yuen's shows since
he began performing at the farm in 1973. During his act he would
always put his head inside a crocodile's jaws.
	   Part Thai and part Vietnamese, he learned to hunt and tame
crocodiles from a Buddhist monk while visiting Cambodia during the
1960s. According to local folklore, Uncle Yao used black magic to
hunt and kill hundreds of dangerous crocodiles in Cambodia and
Thailand.
</TEXT>
