<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Property Slump </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Property agency says restrictive Thai laws stop sector rebound
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Restrictive laws that limit foreign
ownership are killing a potential rebound in Thailand's depressed
real estate sector, an international consultant said Wednesday.
	   Unless they are changed ``international investors will continue
to shun Thailand and will increasingly turn their attention to
opportunities elsewhere,'' said a report issued by Jones Lang
Wootton, a real estate consulting company.
	   Sales of buildings to local residents and foreign investors have
dropped drastically with few transactions reported during the first
half of 1998, the company said.
	   ``Two major reasons are the unwillingness of owners to accept
market realities and the wait-and-see approach of foreign
investors,'' the report said.
	   Massive oversupply in the property sector helped spark
Thailand's economic crisis in 1997. Banks and finance companies
lent heavily to developers who could not pay back the loans when
they could not sell their projects.
	   Yet despite oversupply and an economy in sharp recession, prices
have not dropped to levels many potential buyers want to see, the
consultant said.
	   ``Many investors are also awaiting positive changes to laws and
regulations about which there has been much talk but considerably
less action,'' the report said.
	   Among them are easing the limits on foreign ownership.
Foreigners are not allowed to own land in Thailand, and are
restricted to owning a maximum of 40 percent of any condominium
project and 49 percent of any company.
	   Although there have been proposals to change these laws, they
have met stiff resistance in parliament.
	   Jones Lang Wootton also urged that laws be changed to allow
foreigners to take leases on land or buildings for up to 99 years,
instead of the maximum 30 now allowed. Many foreign investors feel
that 30 years may not be long enough to get the return they are
hoping for on their projects, the report said.
</TEXT>
