r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Malaysia-SecurityLaw     08-04 0259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Security Law </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malaysia has 198 people detained under security law
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Malaysia's prime minister said 198
people were in jail under a powerful law that allows imprisonment
without trial, according to a news report Wednesday.
	   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said that 124 of those held
under the Internal Security Act, as the law is known, were detained
for forging national identity cards and travel documents, the Sun
newspaper reported.
	   Mahathir's comments were made in a written statement in
parliament Tuesday.
	   Another 66 people were being held for smuggling illegal
immigrants into the country, seven for deviant Islamic practices
and one person for involvement with a freedom movement in Aceh, an
independence-seeking region of Indonesia.
	   Earlier this year, 22 asylum-seekers from Aceh sought refuge in
the U.S. Embassy and U.N. compound after a violent police raid on
an illegal immigrant detention center left at least nine dead.
	   The United Nations granted the 22 men asylum, although Malaysia
does not recognize the Acehense as political refugees.
	   Mahathir said eight of the ISA detainees had been held for more
than two years, the statement said.
	   The ISA was introduced by British colonial rulers in 1948 to
fight communist guerrillas. Independent Malaysia retained the law
which allows for indefinite detention without trial.
	   It has been used in the past against opposition politicians,
activists and even academics who criticized the government.
</TEXT>
